<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Japan-Markets     06-03 0187</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Markets,0195</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Leading Index Hits Record High</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices rose moderately on the Tokyo Stock
Exchange on Saturday, lifting the market's main index to a record
high.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues gained 84.94
points, or 0.3 percent, to close at 27,906.48 points, a new high,
during Saturday's half-day session.
   The Nikkei's previous high was 27,869.36 points, registered
Thursday.
   The market barometer soared in early morning trading, but
profit-taking lowered the index slightly before the market's close.
   Traders said steel issues, especially Nippon Steel and Kawasaki
Steel, led the gain.
   ``Institutional investors are active today,'' said a broker at a
major securities firm on condition of anonymity. ``Japanese
investors were relieved by bullishness in New York following the
slightly worse-than-expected level of the U.S. unemployment rates.''
   The New York Dow Jones Average gained $18.85 dollars in
overnight trading, ending the largest weekly gain ever, traders
said.
   The volume traded in the first section of the exchange was 1.4
billion shares. Traders said the volume was higher than average for
half-day trading.
   The Tokyo foreign exchange market is closed on Saturday.
</TEXT>
