<1ST_LINE>r i PM-BRF--Britain-Train     06-03 0144</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Britain-Train,0149</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Future For London Train Stations Area</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 120-acre slice of London _ filled with railroad
yards, scruffy shops and low-quality apartment blocks _ will be
redeveloped in what one organization calls the largest inner-city
regeneration project in Europe.
   Britain's state-owned railroad on Thursday said $11 billion
would be spent to develop the huge and largely derelict area around
King's Cross and St. Pancras train stations.
   British Rail called it the largest urban redevelopment project
in Europe.
   The redevelopment of the site by the specially formed London
Regeneration Consortium will begin in 1990 and last 10 years,
British Rail said.
   The area will be developed to provide new offices, homes, shops,
business premises and leisure facilities.
   British Rail said the two stations will be merged and a new
subway station built to form the world's largest railroad station.
</TEXT>
