06-03 0474</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0840,0480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Heavy Rain Soaks Great Plains; Milder Showers Over Tennessee, Ohio
Valleys</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf, `In Texas ..., with 2 grafs to UPDATE with
Abilene storm; picks up 3rd graf: `Dallas got ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A severe storm system that stretched from Kansas deep into Texas
riddled the Great Plains with heavy rain and hail Thursday. A
separate storm system brought rain to the Tennessee and Ohio
valleys and southwest Virginia.
   In central Texas, a severe thunderstorm in Abilene smashed
windows and windshields with baseball-size hail, knocking down
power lines and uprooting trees. No injuries were reported,
authorities said.
   Wind gusts of up to 70 mph blew down utility poles and
overturned mobile homes in China Spring, in the central part of the
state. Gusts of 70 mph and marble-size hail were recorded near
Temple.
   Dallas got 1.70 inches and Waco got 1.50 inches of rain in a
six-hour period ending at 2 p.m. EDT.
   In Oklahoma, a tornado touched down near Marland, in the
northeast part of the state. Nickel-size hail fell near Hugo, in
southeastern Oklahoma. In Kansas, winds of up to 60 mph blew
through Sedan and pea-size hail fell in Ellinwood.
   Tornado watches were issued through the evening for parts of
western and north-central Texas, with severe thunderstorm watches
over much of Oklahoma, western and central Arkansas and southwest
Missouri.
   Farther east, a cold front stretching from North Carolina across
southern West Virginia and central Indiana to eastern Minnesota
sent the mercury plummeting. Terre Haute, Ind., untouched by the
front, sizzled at 91 degrees at 2 p.m. EDT; Fort Wayne, Ind., 200
miles north, had a reading of 56 at the same hour.
   Unseasonably cool weather predominated in the northern and
Middle Atlantic Coast states. A few showers were scattered over
Florida's southeast coast.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 47
degrees at Wenatchee, Wash., to 104 degrees at Palm Springs, Calif.
The morning low for the nation was 28 degrees at Chama, N.M.
   Friday's forecast called for thunderstorms over much of the
Southeast from the Carolinas and Georgia across the Tennessee and
lower Mississippi valleys to eastern parts of Oklahoma and Texas,
with more showers over the Middle Atlantic States, western
Pennsylvania, New York and northern Maine. Rain was also forecast
for eastern Minnesota, Iowa and southeast Nebraska, parts of the
interior Northwest and coastal sections from Washington to northern
California.
   High temperatures should remain in the 50s over parts of
northern New England and into the 60s from the northern and Middle
Atlantic Coast to the Great Lakes, and along the northern Pacific
Coast; in the low 90s in eastern Montana and parts of southern
Georgia and northern Florida, southwest Texas and parts of New
Mexico. Highs should range in the 70s and 80s elsewhere.
</TEXT>
