<FILEID>AP-NR-06-03-88 0234EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HeadstoneControversy     06-03 0552</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Headstone Controversy,0566</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Town Committee Angered By `Who The Hell' Headstone</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</NOTE>
<NOTE>Eds: Inscription without question mark cq.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN GALVIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CONCORD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sheila Shea was just trying for a last
laugh, but some officials say the cemetery that's the final resting
place of Louisa May Alcott is no place for a tombstone that reads:
``Who The Hell Is Sheila Shea.''
   Shea, who died a year and a half ago at age 43, is buried in the
historic Sleepy Hollow Cemetery, in whose ``Authors' Row'' are
buried Alcott and 19th-century luminaries Ralph Waldo Emerson and
Henry David Thoreau.
   The disagreement over the 3{-foot, gray granite headstone
recently surfaced at the Concord Cemetery Committee, which labeled
the inscription ``obscene.'' Some members of the committee, an
advisory body to the town's department of public works, pushed for
legal action to have the headstone removed.
   ``The cemetery really isn't a place to make a statement, it is a
place of memorial,'' Committee President Mary Elizabeth Baker said.
``Sleepy Hollow is a notable cemetery because of the people who are
buried there. It has a national reputation. We would hate to see it
become a sideshow.''
   Officials decided that the town could not afford a legal battle
and that it would be fighting from shaky legal ground, said Tony
Logalbo, town finance director. But they have changed the rules to
guard against similar headstones at the widely visited cemetery.
   ``It's a tourist site. People who are visiting the town of
Concord go to find the grave sites of well-known individuals from
history,'' Logalbo said Thursday. ``Some people in the town felt
that the sentiments it expresses were not in keeping with the
spirit of the site.''
   Town officials were divided over whether the word ``hell'' is
obscene.
   Concord, an affluent town 19 miles northwest of Boston, was
founded by the Puritans in 1635. It was the site of the second
Revolutionary War clash, the home of several well-known early
American authors, and site of Thoreau's celebrated Walden Pond.
   Shea, who is remembered by her friends as a warm, fun-loving
person, died in November 1986 of cancer. She had worked in the
accounting department of a Cambridge company, and had arranged and
paid for her friends to have dinner after her funeral.
   She was divorced and left a teen-age son and daughter.
   Norma Wentworth, a nurse who helped administer her chemotherapy
treatments, said she imagined Shea would be laughing at the
brouhaha over her headstone.
   ``She just had a very good sense of humor,'' Wentworth said.
``She did not intend to be malicious.''
   As a result of the debate over the headstone, anyone who wishes
to buy a plot at Sleepy Hollow in the future will be informed of
restrictions against ``improper or offensive'' headstones,
according to a recent measure approved by the town board of
selectmen.
   The measure would allow the cemetery committee to remove future
headstones, but the list of restrictions does not include any
specific words or phrases.
   Nancy Griffin, the executor of Shea's will, had contacted the
American Civil Liberties Union and vowed to fight any attempt to
remove her friend's headstone.
   ``No matter what Sheila's reasons were, a person has a right to
freedom of speech, dead or alive,'' Griffin said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
