<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     06-03 0596</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0623</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When the school cafeteria ran
out of pizza, milk and other items, 12-year-old Philip Costanzo
didn't bother complaining to the cook. He sent around a petition
and fired off letters to the media.
   Costanzo, a student at Jacksonville Beach Sixth Grade Center,
drew up a petition in January complaining that items on the menu
were not available to all students. He said he collected 600
signatures in two days among the school's 675 students.
   ``I was swamped with people wanting to sign it,'' he said.
   The youngster gave the petition to Principal Gail Brinson. He
said things improved for a while, but problems cropped up again.
   Philip doesn't eat lunch until 1:30 p.m., the next-to-last meal
shift. By that time, the cafeteria often runs out of the more
popular items. Worst of all, at one point students were given ham
and cheese sandwiches instead of the advertised pizza.
   This time, he fired off letters to the media.
   ``My classmates and I are sick of it! We hope that they pay
attention to this letter,'' he wrote.
   His letter got results when it was shown to school food
officials.
   ``In the future, every effort will be made to have all choices
available to all students at the school during the serving
period,'' said Catherine Bajalia, food services director for the
Duval County Schools.
   School officials blamed the problems on equipment malfunctions
and bad estimates of how many children would eat the school lunch
instead of food they bring from home.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>GILROY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It's a good time ... for the great taste
of ... garlic?
   That slogan may not yet be McDonald's latest ditty, but if some
garlic farmers get their way, the hamburger chain could someday be
singing the praises of the onion's more pungent relative.
   Organizers of Gilroy's annual Garlic Festival have persuaded the
owner of two local McDonald's to place packages of crushed garlic
alongside the usual condiments during the three-day festival, July
29-31.
   ``We're excited about it,'' said spokeswoman Darlene Dunham of
garlic-growing Christopher Ranch, which will package the 7-gram
servings.
   Tom Doran, McDonald's regional vice president, gave his blessing
to the garlic promotion.
   ``We encourage our franchises to be good neighbors,'' he said.
   But Doran emphasized that no plans were in the works to provide
garlic in any other McDonald's outlets.
   Dunham said her company hopes that the demand for garlic will be
so overwhelming that the huge chain will consider it for nationwide
distribution.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WILMINGTON, Del. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Terry Lee Griffith and Kathleen
Boutin get married Saturday, the best man naturally will be decked
out in tails _ three of them.
   The wedding is set to take place in the walking ring of the
Delaware Park horse track in Stanton where the best man, a horse
named The Maltese Cat, will be wearing a black-tie outfit.
   ``I guess you could call this fun _ my having The Maltese Cat be
my best man,'' Griffith said of one of the 16 horses he trains.
   But Griffith, 44, is serious about his choice of best man.
   ``The Cat has brought me through some rough times,'' he said.
   The Maltese Cat, one of four horses Griffith purchased for
$1,250 two years ago, has earned more than $40,000 for Griffith,
who said he faced bankruptcy in 1983.
   The wedding will take place in front of 300 friends and
relatives, including David Malatesta of Hockessin, ``who will stand
as my `human best friend,' my interpreter for The Cat,'' Griffith
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880603-0018 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-03-88 0247EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Summit-Allies Bjt   06-03 0671</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Summit-Allies, Bjt,670</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Europeans Praise Reagan, Gorbachev For Improving Ties</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The European NATO allies have widely
praised both the U.S. and Soviet leaders for using the Moscow
summit to forge a ``new stability'' in East-West relations.
   ``Respect, growing trust and affection are there'' between
President Reagan and Kremlin chief Mikhail S. Gorbachev after four
days of meetings, said Lord Carrington, the NATO secretary general.
   ``This personal bond, we all hope, augurs well for further
reductions of tension in the international atmosphere,'' he said in
a speech Thursday to the Royal Institute of International Relations
in Brussels.
   ``Things are moving in a good direction,'' said French President
Francois Mitterrand, speaking in Evian, France, after a meeting
with West German Chancellor Helmut Kohl, who also praised the
summit outcome.
   Hans-Dietrich Genscher, the West German foreign minister, said
the importance of the Moscow meeting _ the fourth for Reagan and
Gorbachev in 30 months _ went beyond the arms issues it dealt with.
   ``Through this summit the American-Soviet relationship got a new
stability, a new perspective,'' Genscher said in Brussels after he
and other alliance officials met with Secretary of State George P.
Shultz at NATO headquarters to hear details of the Moscow talks.
   Shultz gave an upbeat assessment of the summit and told
reporters afterward that the superpowers had come a long way in
their relationship since Reagan first met Gorbachev in Geneva in
November 1985.
   ``It is an undeniable and observable fact that the relationship
now is far better than it was at the time of the first summit,'' he
said.
   The Moscow summit produced no major arms agreements although two
secondary accords were signed, including one requiring at least 24
hours' advance notification before ballistic missile tests.
   The European allies are eager for Washington and Moscow to
conclude an agreement cutting their long-range nuclear missiles by
up to 50 percent. But they showed no outward sign of disappointment
that Shultz reported only modest progress in this area.
   Hans van den Broek, the Dutch foreign minister, said the summit
had provided ``a great measure of continuity and consistency'' in
East-West relations. This, he said, made it possible for the
superpowers to work gradually toward more disarmament.
   ``This is not a process of quick fixes, but at least there is a
process,'' he said.
   European officials who heard Shultz's report on the Moscow
meetings said afterward they were not discouraged by the apparently
slim chances completing a new arms reduction agreement before
Reagan leaves office next January.
   ``The firm will expressed in Moscow by both sides on (arms
control) ... is an essential condition for decisive progress in
Geneva,'' Giulio Andreotti, the Italian foreign minister, told
reporters.
   Carrington stressed that Gorbachev deserves much of the credit
for recent improvements in U.S.-Soviet relations, particularly for
the Intermediate-range Nuclear Forces treaty that the U.S. and
Soviet leaders put into force on Wednesday. The treaty is the first
to eliminate an entire class of nuclear weapons.
   ``I don't think it would have happened without him,'' Carrington
said in an interview with The Associated Press at his NATO office.
   He added that Reagan and the NATO alliance did their part by
sticking to a ``twin-track'' strategy of deploying U.S. cruise and
Pershing II nuclear missiles in Europe while also seeking to
negotiate cuts.
   Carrington also indicated that he saw little chance of Reagan
and Gorbachev holding a fifth summit, since both sides have planed
down the odds of completing agreement soon in the Strategic Arms
Reduction Talks.
   ``There would only be a fifth summit if it was possible there
were going to be a START agreement,'' he said. ``I would have
thought it doubtful there would be one otherwise.''
   Genscher said that despite the long odds of a START deal being
completed this year, the Moscow summit offered new hope in all
areas of arms control.
   ``It seems important to us that both sides want to use the next
months to come to agreements,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
