<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Deaths 1stLd-Writethru a0890 06-03 0384</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Deaths, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0890,0391</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS Kapoor; An AMs separate moved as a0888 on Hildreth as
a0753 on Fong and as a0894 on Kapoor.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Horace Hildreth</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Horace A. Hildreth, whose career as
lawyer, broadcast executive, college president and two-term
governor of Maine was capped with four years' service as a U.S.
ambassador, died Thursday at age 85.
   Hildreth practiced law in Portland and began his Hildreth
Network of Maine radio and TV stations before he went into
politics. The Hildreth Network included the state's first
commercial radio station, Bangor's WABI.
   In 1940 he was elected to the Maine House and later that same
year he won promotion to the state Senate, where he became
president in 1943. He was elected governor in 1945.
   President Dwight D. Eisenhower appointed Hildreth in 1953 as
ambassador to Pakistan, the Moslem country carved out of India in
1947. At that time, Hildreth had been president of Bucknell
University four years.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Emily Fong</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Emily Lee Fong, a leader of Sino-Japanese
War relief efforts, died May 21 of heart failure. She was 90.
   Fong became a charter member of the Chinatown YWCA and helped
organize a YWCA Red Cross Auxiliary, teaching women to roll
bandages during World War I. She helped rally more than 100
Chinese-American associations in the United States to contribute to
the war relief effort.
   In World War II, Fong joined the American Women Voluntary
Service to sell war bonds and ferry soldiers to and from the
Presidio's Letterman Hospital.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Raj Kapoor</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Raj Kapoor, a actor known as ``the
Charlie Chaplin of India'' for his comedy roles and who was given
India's highest movie honor, the Dada Saheb Phalke Award, died
Thursday. He was 64.
   Kapoor acted in 60 films and produced or directed 18 others over
a career that spanned four decades. Almost all his movies were hits
in India, and he was perhaps the most popular Indian film actor
abroad with followers in the Soviet Union, the Middle East and
China.
   Among his best-known films was ``Awara'' (The Vagabond), in
which he borrowed from Chaplin and played the part with trousers
riding high above his ankles and a perpetual forlorn look on his
face.
</TEXT>
