<1ST_LINE>r a PM-People-Brown     06-03 0262</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Brown,0270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lawyer For Wife Of James Brown Withdraws Diplomatic Immunity
Motion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AUGUSTA, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A lawyer for the wife of singer James Brown
says he plans to withdraw a motion asking for diplomatic immunity
for his client because her husband was once praised as the ``No. 1
ambassador.''
   Attorney Allen W. Johnson had asked a Richmond County State
Court judge to dismiss misdemeanor traffic charges on grounds that
Adrienne Brown has diplomatic immunity.
   Mrs. Brown, 38, was charged with driving under the influence of
drugs, speeding and criminal trespass Sept. 3, 1987. She pleaded
innocent, and the case is expected to go to trial later this month.
   Johnson's motion, made Tuesday, was based on a statement made by
U.S. Rep. Douglas Barnard, D-Ga., two years ago on James Brown
Appreciation Day in Augusta, which lies close to Brown's home on
Beech Island, S.C. ``James is indeed our No. 1 ambassador,''
Barnard said.
   Johnson's motion said Brown ``is America's No. 1 ambassador and
as such should have diplomatic immunity and such immunity extends
to his wife, the accused herein.''
   Johnson said Thursday he would withdraw the motion, adding that
he filed it only because every possible defense had to be explored.
He said he has since determined that the congressman intended his
comments as a goodwill gesture and a figure of speech.
   Diplomatic immunity shields officials of foreign nations from
criminal charges while they represent their countries in the United
States.
   The Browns have recently had several highly publicized fights,
and Brown has said he plans to file for divorce.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
