<1ST_LINE>r i BC-Summit-UnresolvedIssues     06-03 0577</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Summit-Unresolved Issues,570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Unresolved Issues In US-Soviet Summit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan's fourth summit with Soviet
leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev left many unresolved matters, and the
joint communique issued by the two leaders acknowledged that
``serious differences remain.''
   Here are the unresolved issues:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>`START' TREATY:</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   It was once hoped that the summit would be crowned by an
agreement to slash long-range nuclear weapons 30 to 50 percent. But
the leaders made only modest progress on a strategic arms reduction
treaty. On mobile missiles, the two sides agreed to restrict them
to designated territories so they could be counted more easily. But
the dimensions of the areas were not set. The superpowers did not
resolve two other problems, monitoring cruise missiles aboard
warships and whether the U.S. anti-missile research program can be
squared with the 1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty.
   Both leaders said it was still possible to reach agreement on a
START treaty during the Reagan administration, but there seemed
little real prospect for a breakthrough.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>CONVENTIONAL WEAPONS:</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   There was disagreement and no resolution of the issue of
conventional weapons in Europe. Negotiations are ongoing in Vienna
between the countries of the Warsaw Pact and NATO alliance. There
had been hints that Gorbachev might unilaterally withdraw 50,000 to
100,000 troops from Eastern Europe to gain a public relations
advantage in the negotiations. That did not occur, however.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>CHEMICAL WEAPONS:</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Like conventional arms, the issue of chemical weapons is the
subject of multilateral treaty negotiations under way in Geneva.
There was no resolution at the summit of the Soviet goal of a
U.S.-endorsed sweeping ban on lethal chemical weapons. The U.S.
says it wants a ``global chemical weapons agreement'' which can be
verified.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>REGIONAL CONFLICTS:</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   On Afghanistan, Soviets already have agreed to withdraw from the
country under a U.N. agreement signed this spring. Moscow says it
tends to abide by its agreement, but has also hinted serious
problems over continued U.S. arms shipments to the rebels funneled
through Pakistan.
   On Angola, where U.S. and Soviet officials have been trying to
arrange a withdrawal of 40,000 Cuban troops from the country, the
two sides set a September deadline for completing a deal on the
withdrawal. But there was no resolution of how to accomplish that
withdrawal. Any withdrawal would have to be accompanied by
implementation of U.N. resolution 435, calling for an end to the
South African occupation of Namibia, another unresolved issue.
   The United States wants the Soviets to stop selling weapons to
Iran in the Gulf war and to pressure Vietnam to remove its troops
from Cambodia. The United States also wants the Soviets to end aid
to Nicaragua's Sandinista government. The Americans were unable to
enlist Soviet support for an embargo against Iran, but some signs
of movement appeared on the Cambodia issue, with the Vietnamese
promising last week to pull all their troops out by 1990. The
subject of Nicaragua was brought up, but no apparent progress was
made.
   On the Mideast, the Soviets want a full-blown international
peace conference to reach a settlement, while the United States
favors a mostly ceremonial conference that would lead to bilateral
talks between Israel and its Arab neighbors. Gorbachev said there
had been a ``drawing closer of our positions'' and that the Soviets
are ready to consider restoring diplomatic relations with Israel
once an international conference is convened. But unresolved are
Palestinian participation in the conference as well as the nature
of that conference.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
