<1ST_LINE>r w PM-SouthAfricaSanctions     06-03 0572</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-South Africa Sanctions,560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Banking Committee Approves Tighter Sanctions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House Banking Committee has added its
support to legislation that would cut virtually all economic ties
with the apartheid government of South Africa.
   The Democratic-controlled panel on Thursday endorsed the bill by
a 34-14 vote, largely along party lines. The measure would escalate
the economic pressure imposed two years ago when Congress passed a
limited sanctions law over President Reagan's veto.
   A similar bill had been approved May 3 by the House Foreign
Affairs Committee, and the legislation still must be considered by
several other House panels before being sent to the full House for
a vote.
   The bill would force a virtual cutoff of U.S. economic ties to
South Africa, forcing divestiture of U.S. investments within a year
and prohibiting most exports and imports. It also would tighten
restrictions on U.S. lending to South African companies and would
ban U.S. military and intelligence cooperation with Pretoria.
   Approval came after the panel narrowly adopted, 27-24, an
amendment offered by an opponent of the legislation, Rep. Bill
McCollum, R-Fla., that would have the effect of making it even
tougher, but at the same time more difficult for Congress to pass.
   The amendment would have extended South African import
prohibitions to include not only products from that country, but
products from other countries which contain components or parts
made in South Africa. The provision would affect many items
containing industrial diamonds, among other products.
   McCollum argued that the move would prevent other countries from
stepping in to snap up the share of trade given up by the United
States. But opponents said the provision would be impossible to
enforce because of the difficulty of tracing the origin of items
like diamonds.
   ``This is an effort to kill the bill with pseudo-kindness,''
said Rep. Barney Frank, D-Mass.
   In 1986, the latest year for which figures were available, U.S.
direct and indirect investment in South Africa totaled an estimated
$4 billion. Total bilateral trade for that year was roughly $2
billion. A recent congressional report noted that since 1984, 156
U.S. companies have withdrawn from South Africa and another 157
still have direct investments or employees there.
   The Reagan administration is strongly opposed to the
legislation, preferring instead a policy of ``constructive
engagement.'' That policy calls for maintaining political and
economic ties to South Africa in the belief that such ties give the
United States more leverage to promote reforms in South Africa's
system of racial separatism.
   Several members of the Banking Committee expressed concern that
U.S. banks would suffer from the increased lending restrictions,
which would ban rescheduling of outstanding loans.
   Chairman Fernand St Germain, D-R.I., noted that there had been a
flurry of lobbying against the measure by banking interests, who
argued they would be forced to sell off South African loans at
discounts.
   A primary sponsor of the sanctions bill, Foreign Affairs Africa
subcommittee chairman Howard Wolpe, D-Mich., acknowledged there
would be some costs for a limited number of U.S. interests, and
said some South Africans could realize short-term benefits.
   ``I wish there were a way to add pressure without cost or
inconvenience to American business,'' Wolpe said. ``But there is no
way to do that.'' He said it is in the long-term best interests of
the United States to avoid what he termed ``an evolving war''
between the races in South Africa.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880603-0024 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-03-88 0136EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-SpellingBee Bjt   06-03 0521</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Spelling Bee, Bjt,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thirteen-Year-Old Spelling Bee Winner Says Hard Work Pays Off</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX6</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   National Spelling Bee winner Rageshree
Ramachandran says she's not sure what profession she'll pursue, but
she already knows that hard work pays off.
   ``Study as much as you can, and don't stop after the eighth
grade because it's what comes later that counts,'' is her advice to
other would-be champions.
   The 13-year-old from Fair Oaks, Calif., outlasted runner-up
Victor C. Wang of Camarillo, Calif., in a grueling 45-minute,
one-on-one finale Thursday.
   Her winning word in the 61st annual contest, sponsored by
Scripps Howard newspapers, was ``elegiacal,'' an adjective used to
describe the couplets, or pairs of lines, in some poems.
   As the judges nodded their heads that she had won and the
hundreds of spectators in the hotel ballroom applauded and cheered,
she stepped back from the microphone and a smile spread across her
face.
   ``Anything I go into would involve writing, even if it's math or
science,'' the eighth-grader said later.
   Rageshree, who was born in India and whose parents are both
statistics professors, said she had studied spelling for at least
two hours daily since January, helped by her mother, father and
younger sister.
   Victor, a 14-year-old from Camarillo, Calif., stumbled when he
misspelled ``stertorous,'' replacing the first ``o'' with a ``u.''
The word is an adjective used to describe harsh, snoring sounds.
   For a while, neither child had much luck as they were asked to
spell a series of words that both proved unable to pin down. After
Victor misspelled ``balmacaan,'' a loose overcoat, and a bee
official spelled it correctly, the eighth-grader drew laughter from
an equally perplexed audience by asking, ``Who makes up these
words?''
   Rageshree won $1,500 and several other prizes, while Victor
garnered $1,000.
   It took 935 words to find a winner from the record field of 200
hopefuls. After Wednesday's first day of competition, 144 of them
remained.
   The competitors began falling faster Thursday as the words were
drawn less frequently from study lists that had been distributed
and more often from Webster's Third New International Dictionary,
the contest's bible.
   As the second day wore on, the words increasingly drew gasps of
puzzlement from the audience and audible sighs of relief from
contestants who had threaded their way through the puzzles they had
been given.
   Iris Liu, the tournament's youngest competitor ever, lasted
until the fifth round. But Iris, a Muncie, Ind., third-grader who
turns nine on June 20, lost her way spelling ``waywiser,'' an
instrument that measures distance, offering ``weighweiser.''
   Reaching the finals was a feat in itself. The 200 finalists had
started among 8 million to 9 million competitors who entered local
bees across the country. The 102 girls and 98 boys in the finals
came from 47 states, the Virgin Islands, Guam, Puerto Rico, the
district of Columbia, and Mexico.
   Contestants won $750 for finishing in third place, $500 for
fourth, $400 for fifth, $300 for sixth, $200 each for seventh
through 10th, $100 each for 11th through 20th. The remaining 180
received $50 each.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
