<DOCNO> AP880603-0028 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-03-88 0312EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Drugs-Money Bjt   06-03 0482</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drugs-Money, Bjt,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Proposed US Drug Czar Would Have $2.6 Billion Bank Account</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Declaring that Congress cannot
``micro-manage'' the war on drugs, a House panel is proposing
creation of an administration drug coordinator who would have an
instant $2.6 billion bank account.
   The novel, flexible approach was unveiled Thursday by the six
Democrats and three Republicans of the House Appropriations
subcommittee on commerce, justice, state and the judiciary _ the
panel that dispenses most of the nation's drug war money.
   Chairman Neal Smith, D-Iowa, said the House leadership has not
taken a position on the legislation.
   Traditionally, Congress allocates a set amount to an agency, and
breaks down how much should be spent for each major function over a
particular period.
   But Smith said Congress cannot keep up with the changing needs
of the more than 30 front-line drug fighting agencies. The
coordinator would therefore decide how to dispense the money based
on the needs of the moment, Smith said.
   ``There is no way that the Congress can ... micro-manage a war
on drugs any more than the Congress could micro-manage a war on the
battlefield,'' he said.
   Smith offered this example of how the system would work:
   ``As an opportunity to curtail imports becomes available, more
money may suddenly be needed for the Drug Enforcement
Administration, FBI, Border Patrol, Coast Guard, Immigration and
Naturalization Service, or one of the agencies involved in this
aspect.
   ``On the other hand, if there have been some big busts, more
money will be needed for the courts, for the Marshal's Service, for
the prison services, for prosecutors' offices and various other
agencies involved in enforcing the law.''
   The legislation is an appropriation bill, which means the money
would become available immediately if the president signed it.
Usually, omnibus drug bills are authorization measures that state
Congress' intent to provide money, but separate appropriations
measures are then needed to actually make it available.
   Passage of an authorization does not guarantee that the
appropriation will be approved, or will be as much as the
authorized spending ceiling.
   The new proposal would exceed the budget ceiling reached at a
``summit'' agreement between President Reagan and Congress late
last year. The agreement permitted additional spending for dire
emergencies, a designation provided for the drug war money bill.
   Previous bills have called for a ``drug czar'' with authority to
coordinate strategy among different agencies. This bill differs,
because the coordinator's only job would be to dispense the money.
   Rep. Harold Rogers, R-Ky., said the use of illegal drugs is the
type of emergency the summit agreement had in mind.
   ``Despite our best efforts, drugs are increasing in
availability. Violence associated with these drugs is growing at a
similarly alarming rate,'' he said.
   Nonetheless, Rogers predicted a ``tough fight'' to win passage
of the legislation because of budget constraints facing Congress.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880603-0029 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-03-88 0313EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Panama     06-03 0298</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Panama,0308</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Military Says U.S. Runs Clandestine Radio Station</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOSEPH B. FRAZIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Panama's military has charged that a
U.S. government agency is operating a clandestine radio station to
destabilize the government.
   The Defense Forces' press office, in a statement Thursday, said
the opposition Radio Constitucional is run by the Foreign Broadcast
Information Service, which it said is a CIA operation.
   The broadcast service collects information on everything that
happens in Latin America, particularly Panama, the communique said.
It said the operation is based in the former Panama Canal Zone.
   The statement was the latest in a series issued by the military
accusing the United States of plotting to undermine the government.
   The U.S. Embassy denied that Radio Constitutional is linked to
the Foreign Broadcast Information Service.
   It said in a prepared statement that Foreign Broadcast has been
a part of the embassy since 1979 and that it gathers information
from newspapers and radio and television broadcasts and sends it to
Washington.
   The embassy statement said the reports are open to the public
and available to foreign governments by subscription.
   Before becoming a function of the embassy, Foreign Broadcast was
a part of the U.S. Southern Command, it added. The command is the
headquarters for U.S. military activities in Latin America.
   Radio Constitucional apparently is operated by Panamanians
opposed to Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega, chief of the 15,000-member
Defense Forces and the country's de facto leader.
   The station has a very weak signal and few listeners are able to
find it or keep it tuned in for long.
   Noriega is under federal indictment in the United States on drug
trafficking charges. The Reagan administration has imposed economic
and trade sanctions against Panama in an effort to oust the general.
</TEXT>
