<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FarmScene     06-03 0726</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Farm Scene,740</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Purchases Fueling Growth in Farm Exports</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Growth of U.S. farm exports is being fueled
mainly by larger Soviet grain purchases, according to Agriculture
Department economists.
   Soviet purchases account for 68 percent of the total volume
increase this year. At 77.3 million metric tons, total farm exports
are running 21 percent ahead of the first six months of 1987, USDA
economists say.
   Thus far this year the Soviets have purchased 9.3 million metric
tons of U.S. farm commodities with a value of more than $1 billion,
according to a world production and trade report issued by USDA
earlier this week. The exports have been mainly wheat, corn,
soybeans and soybean meal.
   In the first half of last year, the Soviets bought 335,700 tons
of U.S. commodities with a value of $42.7 million.
   Japanese purchases of U.S. commodities were up in the first six
months of the year by more than 2 million metric tons, with big
gains in wheat, corn, grain sorghum, soybeans, vegetable oils and
horticultural products.
   Chinese purchases increased by 1.5 million metric tons. The
primary increases were in wheat, corn, soybeans and baby chicks.
The same commodities were the leaders as Korea enlarged its buying
by 695,000 tons and there also was a marked rise in sales of
cotton, cattle hides and fruit juice.
   Wheat has been outpacing all other commodities as American
exports surge, largely because of the lower dollar, federal export
programs and reduced supplies abroad attributable to adverse
weather.
   Wheat exports in the first six months of 1988 were 8.8 million
tons, or $764 million, above the comparable figures for 1987. Corn
posted a gain of 3.4 million metric tons, soybeans 898,000,
vegetable oils 483,000, horticultural products 322,000 and cotton
136,000 metric tons.
   The Soviet Union and China have been major wheat buyers along
with various North African and Mideast nations. The fastest growing
market for high-value products, such as vegetable oils, meat and
almonds, have been the European Community and the middle and
high-income countries of the Pacific Basin.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The changing international trade picture comes
under review as a major farm women's group, Women Involved in Farm
Economics (WIFE), comes to Washington for its annual government
affairs seminar.
   ``International trade decisions have a very direct and immediate
effect on everyone in production agriculture,'' said a statement
from WIFE President Alice Parker of Royal City, Wash.
   In specific, the group will focus on current discussions aimed
at revising the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade and the
free-trade agreement under which the United States and Canada are
planning to phase out tariffs between the two North American
neighbors.
   Delegates from 22 states plan to be on hand to personally try
their hand as Capitol Hill farm lobbyists.
   The two Agriculture Committee chairmen, Rep. E. ``Kika'' de la
Garza, D-Texas, and Sen. Patrick J. Leahy, D-Vt., are jointly
sponsoring a legislative affairs breakfast Tuesday as part of the
seminar.
   A panel of experts ranging from federal officials to a grain
company lobbyist will be on hand to make sure the trade issue gets
a full airing.
   Delegates also will get an update from attorneys on a lawsuit
filed by WIFE against the Agriculture Department, contending that a
farm wife should not be barred by payment limitation provisions of
the farm program from getting federal subsidies to which she
otherwise would be entitled.
   A federal court recently found in favor of the group.
   The department had been barring some payments under legislation
aimed at barring families from increasing their federal payments
merely by restructuring the ownership of their property.
   Environmental concerns also will be spotlighted at the session.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   World tobacco production this year is being
forecast at 6.5 million tons, a 5 percent increase over the 1987
harvest, the Agriculture Department says.
   China's projected 19 percent increase to a record 2.3 million
tons is largely responsible for the rise, according to and world
production and trade report released by USDA on Thursday.
   Chinese plantings were larger than expected following an
increase of 30 percent in producer's returns last year for
flue-cured tobacco, which represents about 80 percent of that
country's harvest.
   U.S. production is likely to increase 11 percent because of
higher production quotas for burley and flue-cured tobacco, USDA
said.
</TEXT>
