<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Brasil-Sarney     06-03 0459</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Brasil-Sarney,0472</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Constituent Assembly Gives Sarney Five-Year Term, Election In 1989</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANA HAYWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawmakers rejected an attempt to call an
early presidential election and allowed President Jose Sarney to
complete a five-year term ending in 1990 even though polls
indicated that voters want elections now.
   The Congress, sitting as a Constituent Assembly to rewrite the
Constitution, on Thursday voted 328 in favor of a five-year term
and 222 in favor of four years.
   Leftist lawmakers wanted the election in November this year, but
the assembly decided the country's estimated 75 million eligible
voters will go to the polls in November 1989. Brazilians have not
voted for a president since 1960.
   The voting, which began after nine hours of debate, was
interrupted repeatedly by shouts of ``elections now'' and ``Sarney
out.'' After the vote, legislators unveiled a huge sign that read:
``Five years: betrayal of the people.''
   Polls taken over the past year consistently have shown a
majority of Brazil's 143 million people want presidential elections
this year.
   The five-year term is subject to a final vote, but political
analysts say it will pass when the entire constitution is voted
chapter by chapter later this year.
   The issue has been one of the most heated of the Constituent
Assembly, which already has approved the five-year term for future
presidents. The current constitution gives presidents a six-year
mandate.
   Lawmakers elected in 1986 have been spending the last 14 months
writing a new constitution to replace the one handed down by a
military junta in 1969.
   Sarney, 57, took office in 1985 as the running mate of Tancredo
Neves, who died before taking office. Neves was a civilian selected
in an electoral college vote to pave the way for non-military rule.
The military government had ruled since a 1964 coup.
   Sarney, who was leader of the military-backed Social Democratic
Party before taking office, has often alluded to a military threat
if the assembly shortened his term. Sarney still counts the
military chiefs among his closest supporters.
   ``My duty is to leave the nation institutionalized and not allow
the climate of freedom and consolidation to turn into a Prague
spring,'' Sarney said in a recent interview with the respected
daily Gazeta Mercantil newspaper.
   Sarney was referring to the popular protests demanding
democratic reforms in Czechoslovakia 20 years ago that were crushed
by Soviet troops.
   Sarney has maintained that uncertainty over his term has kept
him from properly running the country, deprived him of a strong
political base and is a reason for Brazil's economic problems.
   Critics charge Sarney has only been concerned with his term,
allowing inflation to soar to a projected annual rate of 600
percent and investment to drop to almost zero.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
