<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Summit-Quotes     06-03 0324</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Summit-Quotes,320</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are quotes from President Reagan's trip to
London on Thursday and his farewell in Moscow at the end of his
summit with Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>GORBACHEV FAREWELL:</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   ``Our dialogue has not been easy,'' the Soviet leader said,
``but we mustered enough realism and political will to overcome
obstacles and divert the train of U.S. Soviet relations from a
dangerous track to a safer one. It has, however, so far, been
moving much more slowly than is required by the real situation,
both in our two countries and in the whole world.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>REAGAN FAREWELL:</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   ``I would like to think that our efforts during these past few
days have slayed a few dragons and advanced the struggle against
the evils that threaten mankind ... And I would like to hope that
like St. George, with God's help, peace and freedom can prevail,''
said Reagan, noting that their farewell was taking place in a
Kremlin hall named for the Order of St. George.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>REAGANS IN LONDON:</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   ``Let me put it very simply: I'm very happy to be in London,''
Reagan said, when asked whether he was glad to be in London and not
Moscow.
   ``I'm very happy to see the queen at all times,'' Mrs. Reagan
replied when asked whether she was happy to be seeing Queen
Elizabeth II rather than Raisa Gorbachev.
   ``I think he's a good bloke,'' said onlooker Justine Griffin,
asked about the U.S. president.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>SUMMIT ASSESSED:</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   ``We share his opinion that it was a successful and substantial
summit,'' said Hans-Dietrich Genscher, West German foreign
minister, after meeting with Secretary of State George P. Shultz.
``Through this summit the American-Soviet relationship got a new
stability, a new perspective.''
   ``Let's remember that the Soviet negotiators always seek to
cripple us in areas where they fear we might utilize our
comparative technological advantages,'' said Edward L. Rowney,
Reagan's special adviser for arms control matters.
</TEXT>
