<1ST_LINE>r a BC-Steinway     06-03 0379</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Steinway,0400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>24 Pianists Play; Steinway Unveils 500,000th Piano</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Will stand for PMs.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After 24 pianists had played on two ``ordinary''
Steinway grand pianos for nearly four hours, stagehands unveiled
and pushed to the center of the Carnegie Hall stage the 500,000th
Steinway built in America.
   Wendell Castle, introduced as America's premiere furniture
designer, who created the ebony piano's case with its unusually
large sculptured legs, took a bow.
   ``Who's going to be the first to play on it?'' asked master of
ceremonies David Dubal, one of the 24 pianists. Somebody yelled:
``Van Cliburn.'' Dubal continued: ``The future of piano music, Mr.
Albert Kim.''
   Kim, who studies at the Manhattan School of Music, played
several short pieces and an encore.
   Cliburn and his mother, Rildia Bee Cliburn, who started giving
her son piano lessons when he was 3, had just been on stage. From
Steinway's president, Bruce Stevens, Cliburn received an award of
achievement for professional excellence and inspiration to young
performers.
   Cliburn did not play.
   Most of the pianists who did play are not world famous.
   Three among the best known, Lazar Berman, who came from Moscow,
Alexis Weissenberg and Shura Cherkassky, born in 1912, were saved
until after the second intermission Thursday night. And all three
were splendid.
   They were followed by 19 pianists alternating between two pianos
to play the 22 sections of Schumann's ``Carnaval.''
   Before that, the best known pianists were Grant Johannesen, Ruth
Laredo and Misha Dichter, who played a two-piano duet with his wife
Cipa.
   Each piece was short and introduced by Dubal or Hai-Kyung Suh.
   Other pianists participating were Navah Perlman, born in 1950,
daughter of violinist Itzhak Perlman, Peter Orth, Joseph
Kalichstein, Robert Taub, Jose Feghali, Leon Bates, Jean-Yves
Thibaudet, Miss Suh, Christopher O'Riley, Alexander Toradze,
Barbara Nissman, Stephen Hough, Alec Chein, Ilana Vered, Edmund
Battersby and Jerome Rose.
   The evening celebrated the 135th anniversary of the piano
company in America and was a benefit for the Steinway Foundation,
which is being set up to promote the composition and performance of
piano music.
   The new piano, valued at $500,000, will be taken on a world tour
with stops in the Far East, Europe as well as the United States.
</TEXT>
