<FILEID>AP-NR-06-03-88 0253EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Jackson-Gangs     06-03 0767</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jackson-Gangs,780</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jesse Jackson Meets With Gang Members, Blames Desperation for
Violence</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LA12 of June 2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson walked into the heart of the
city's gang territory and emerged shaking his head after hearing
tales of violence, drugs and failed government policies.
   ``In a real sense they feel they have no way out,'' said the
Democratic presidential contender. He was flanked by a dozen
members of the Bounty Hunters offshoot ``set'' of the Bloods gang,
whose violent lives were depicted in the film ``Colors.''
   With Secret Service agents at his side, the Democratic candidate
met with reporters after a two-hour meeting Thursday with gang
members inside the gymnasium at the 5,000-resident Nickerson
Gardens project, a housing area plagued by gang crime.
   Desperation was the message heard by Jackson, whose candidacy
and interest in the community briefly eased its sense of
hopelessness.
   ``I'm glad he came, I think it's a lot of hope,'' said Maurice
Washington, 16, who identified himself as a member of the Bounty
Hunters.
   Another gang member who met with Jackson, identifying himself
only as ``Dog,'' said the violence will stop only when parents
wrestle back control of their children.
   ``I told him (Jackson) to tell these parents to watch their
kids. Police ain't gonna do it. It's gotta start in the home,''
said Dog, pointing to the seemingly endless rows of
graffiti-scarred buildings in the projects.
   ``They believe unlimited access to guns and drugs compounds the
crisis because a combination of the drugs, the guns and the money
creates a kind of unholy triangle in the situation,'' Jackson said.
   ``A gang is nothing but an organized group of people who form in
an act of desperation and hopelessness and turns to unacceptable
anti-social behavior,'' Jackson said.
   He complained that government programs and services aimed at
heading off gang violence and helping residents of the gang-plagued
neighborhoods aren't coordinated.
   ``After all these killings, why hasn't leadership on all levels
been convened?'' asked Jackson. He condemned the lack of day care,
job training and scholarship recruitment in Nickerson Gardens.
   ``One young man said there are no equal rights, there are only
equal wrongs,'' the candidate said.
   ``I offer the youth today a partnership,'' Jackson said. ``I
will have to fight the flow of drugs. They must cut demand for
drugs.
   ``In many ways these young people, these grapes, have been
turned into raisins. Grapes of hope are now raisins of despair.
Their powers to believe have been turned into cynicism,'' the
candidate said.
   The Jackson campaign touted the meeting in the gang-infested
projects as a private dialogue with leaders of the Bloods and
Crips, but those at the table were actually former members and
young low-echelon members.
   ``It doesn't really make any difference,'' Jackson said.
   City Councilman Nate Holden pointed out: ``Here, you never
really get out of a gang.''
   Steve Valdivia, the director of Community Youth Gang Services
which helped arrange the meeting, was impressed with Jackson's
visit.
   ``In a community that reproduces gang members, an environment
where there is no choice but to be on the wrong side of the law, I
can see a need for 10 Jesse Jacksons,'' Valdivia said.
   ``We don't have those leaders here. Leaders here don't see
beyond there own limited agenda,'' he said. ``The fact is law and
order is not the end-all to everything. Jesse Jackson realizes
that's not where it starts or ends. It always has been, and always
will be, social and economic issues.
   ``When a man like that comes in and says he cares and wants to
do something about it, and has the power, then I'm all for it.''
   Asked why leaders of the Crips and Bloods weren't in on the
meeting, Valdivia explained there are over 250 sets of Crips and
Bloods.
   ``There is no way in the world you can get all those groups
together in one place and have peaceful co-existence,'' he said.
   More than 380 people were killed in gang violence in Los Angeles
County last year.
   Some local residents _ many of whom have lost friends and
relatives to gang shootings _ expressed hope at the attention
Jackson brought to their concerns, but also skepticism that any
changes could be achieved.
   ``I don't know, I doubt it,'' said James Tapla, 17, who
described himself as a Bounty Hunter ``marked'' by rival gangs.
   ``You can't go nowhere without somebody wanting to beat you down
or shoot you. I lost three close friends'' to gang violence, he
said. ``I'm tired of it. It's time for this to stop.''
</TEXT>
