<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Japan-Israel     06-03 0254</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Israel,0260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japan Calls For Israeli Withdrawal From Lebanon</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan has called on Israel to withdraw completely
from southern Lebanon and improve its treatment of Palestinians in
the occupied Gaza Strip and West Bank.
   Officials from the Foreign Ministry also said Thursday that
Japanese Foreign Minister Sosuke Uno is expected to urge Israel to
withdraw from the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip when he visits
Israel at the end of June.
   Japan plays a small political role in the Middle East but its
economic role, especially its purchases of oil and its exportation
of high-technology equipment, is substantial.
   ``Since the Israeli invasion into Lebanon in June 1982, Japan
has consistently called for an unconditional Israeli withdrawal
from Lebanon,'' Foreign Ministry spokesman Koichi Haraguchi told a
regular news conference. ``I'd like to take this opportunity (on
the sixth anniversary) to reaffirm that there has been no change in
this policy.''
   Referring to Israel's actions against Arab protesters in the
occupied territories, Haraguchi said, ``the current handling of the
Palestinian people in those areas is not kindly welcomed and we
express our hope that the current conduct will be stopped
immediately.''
   Foreign Minister Uno is scheduled to visit Israel as part of a
six-day, four-nation Middle East tour beginning June 22. He will be
the highest ranking Japanese official ever to visit Israel, the
officials said.
   About 200 Palestinians have been killed in the West Bank and
Gaza Strip since the anti-occupation uprising began nearly six
months ago.
</TEXT>
