<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880603-0043 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-03-88 0352EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-CaliforniaPoll     06-03 0221</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-California Poll,200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Tops Jackson in Statewide Poll, But Jackson Gains</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic presidential contender Michael
Dukakis held a solid lead over rival Jesse Jackson, according to
the latest survey here, but Jackson was gaining ground, the poll
suggested.
   The survey, taken by the San Francisco Examiner and television
station KRON, indicated the Massachusetts governor led Jackson by
24 percentage points, 52 percent to 28 percent. Twenty percent were
undecided.
   The poll of 600 registered Democrats, questioned on Tuesday and
Wednesday, had a margin of error of 4 percentage points, the
Examiner reported in Thursday's editions.
   A similar survey, taken in mid-May, suggested Dukakis was
leading by 37 percentage points, 60 percent to 23 percent.
   ``While Jackson has shown growth the last couple of weeks, he
continues to have an extremely narrow base,'' said Examiner
pollster Stephen Teichner. ``He faces a pretty big task in closing
the gap.''
   Teichner said a low turnout on election day would help Jackson
because his base appears to be ``extremely committed.''
   In the more recent poll, black voters were backing Jackson by a
72 percent to 9 percent margin in the most recent poll. Asians
continued to overwhelmingly support Dukakis, by a margin of 61
percent to 20 percent. Hispanics split 47 percent to 34 percent in
favor of Dukakis.
</TEXT>
