<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Israel-Prison     06-03 0637</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-Prison,0658</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Press Visits Prison, Arab Inmates Complain of Heat, Humiliation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICOLAS B. TATRO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KETZIOT, Israel (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Palestinian inmates complained of heat,
hunger, and humiliation to foreign journalists who toured this
prison camp for the first time since the six-month uprising began
in the occupied territories.
   This center in the Negev Desert held 2,483 Palestinians,
detained without trial. Of those, 2,061 have been sentenced to up
to six months in jail.
   Many are teachers, journalists, doctors and community leaders
imprisoned to prevent the spread of unrest, which began Dec. 8.
   The journalists talked Thursday with the prisoners, who live in
clusters of open tents.
   ``They said I was active in politics, but I believe I am here
because I am a journalist,'' said Qasem Ali, who worked part-time
for The Associated Press.
   ``I think conditions here made the people more radical and
created more hatred and this is the problem,'' said Ali, 29, who
stood behind a fence topped with barbed wire. He smoked one of five
cigarettes given to each inmate daily.
   Prisoners complained of being made to kneel, hands behind their
backs, for lengthy, twice-daily roll calls in the scorching heat at
the prison, located near the Egyptian border 20 miles south of the
occupied Gaza Strip.
   Being made to kneel was the principle complaint of Abdel Aziz
Randisi, a pediatrician from Khan Yunis in the Gaza Strip who was
jailed for six months without trial on March 20.
   Randisi said prisoners who break any of the camps manifold rules
are forced to kneel.
   ``I will refuse. Really, our hearts are grieving, and we would
rather die than do this kneeling,'' he said.
   At one point, prisoners brought out Saad Dahdour, 21, of Gaza,
who had a bruise over his right eye and said he was made to stand
in a toilet and beaten after arguing with guards about treatment
for a toothache.
   Other complaints included a ban on mass gatherings that
prevented group prayers on the Moslem Sabbath, not enough water to
bathe frequently to wash off the desert dust, small portions of
food, infrequent newspapers and a ban on radio and television.
   Col. David Tzemach, the camp commander, showed reporters a
storeroom with fresh produce and large amounts of canned meat. He
also cited round-the-clock medical care and frequent visits by the
Red Cross.
   Referring to complaints that inmates were made to sit in the hot
sun for 30-minute roll calls, he snapped: ``They are liars. They
don't sit in the sun for that long. It only takes 10 minutes for a
roll call.''
   He said mass gatherings were banned after Friday prayer services
turned into political rallies with Palestinians singing nationalist
songs and, in one case, throwing stones.
   Tzemach recalled that on one occasion more than 100 prisoners
reported sick with stomach aches and fevers, but doctors found only
three to be sick.
   ``It was just a big show,'' he said.
   Prisoners also said family visits were not allowed. Tzemach said
these were suspended after a bus carrying visitors was stopped in
the occupied West Bank and burned by Arab protesters who opposed
such visits since they involved cooperating with the Israelis.
   Rejecting accusations of beatings, Tzemach said the maximum
punishment was three days in an isolation cell, a punishment
usually imposed only for those who try to incite revolt or violence
against guards.
   ``For minor offenses like refusing to come out for roll call,
prisoners are made to stand in the corner,'' the camp commander
said.
   Earlier this week the human rights group Law in the Service of
Man urged that the camp be closed, saying the conditions were
``inhumane.''
   It said prisoners were moved from the occupied territories into
Israel, in violation of the Geneva Convention governing the
treatment of civilians in occupied areas.
</TEXT>
