<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Gorbachev     06-03 0445</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gorbachev,0459</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gorbachev Wit And Vitality Dominate Meeting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mikhail S. Gorbachev's human touch warmed a
friendly crowd of peace activists who came to the Kremlin to praise
his policies and offer him gifts ranging from a toy for his
granddaughter to a Chicago Bears sweatshirt.
   On a day that President Reagan left Moscow, Americans and other
Westerners talked excitedly and hugged each other after addressing
Gorbachev and walking up to the front of the Kremlin's circular
Sverdlov Hall to present him with a gift.
   The 57-year-old Soviet leader's wit and self-assurance, which
have overcome the stereotype of old and ailing Soviet leaders,
dominated Thursday's three-hour session with hundreds of peace
activists.
   He combined the style of an American politician on the stump
with the substance of Soviet policies. He defended Soviet positions
on human rights, arms control and ``perestroika'' _ his
restructuring drive.
   The activists, many of whom said they already supported a number
of Soviet policies, applauded frequently.
   Gorbachev praised them for their efforts. ``I can now see that
public initiatives are ahead of politics,'' Gorbachev said.
   Among the gifts he received were a plaque proclaiming his home a
zone of peace, a solar-powered watch, a ``peace now'' T-shirt,
posters, paintings and an American Indian peace pipe.
   ``I think we're going to have an exhibition after this
meeting,'' he said at one point. ``An exhibition of souvenirs.''
   William Sloan Coffin, Vietnam War-era chaplain at Yale
University and former senior minister at New York's Riverside
Church, told Gorbachev the United States has traditionally been
ahead in the arms race, ``but in the race to disarm, the roles
apparently are reversed.''
   ``He's the statesman we've been waiting for,'' said Marty
Coleman of Pasadena, Calif., who presented Gorbachev with a toy
from her granddaughter Amanda to give to his granddaughter Oxana.
   Gorbachev observed that a grandmothers' association existed in
the Soviet Union, but added, ``It's now necessary to create a
grandfathers' association.''
   Later he returned to the theme, addressing a woman who
represented an organization called ``Grandmothers for Peace.'' ``I
suggest the founding of a rival organization,'' he said.
   ``Man, my knees are shaking,'' said Russell Red Bear, an
American Indian representative as he returned to his seat.
   Gorbachev had just autographed a book for imprisoned former
American Indian Movement leader Leonard Peltier, whose case Soviets
often cite as an example of U.S. human rights abuses.
   As is his custom, Gorbachev opened the meeting with a lengthy
statement. Representatives of at least 32 American groups and of
peace organizations from many other countries then lined up at four
microphones spread around the hall to make statements.
 
</TEXT>
</DOC>
