<2ND_LINE>PM-Political Briefs,720</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>For Democratic Convention, Phones Anywhere</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There may be more than just the sounds of birds
coming from the trees when the Democratic National Convention
begins next month in Atlanta.
   Telephone companies, busy rewiring the city for the political
conclave, say they will install phones just about anywhere, even in
trees.
   ``The news media have got to be able to cover the news where it
happens. We have to be able to respond,'' said Paul Harman,
convention coordinator for Southern Bell.
   The company has created a special 9,000-line phone system that
will allow the 20,000 delegates, alternates, reporters and
technicians expected in town for the July 18-21 convention to call
each other by using only a four-digit number from hotels and
convention facilities across Atlanta.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bush Lead Narrow Over Hypothetical Dukakis-Bentsen Democratic
Ticket</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Although he claims to be a favorite son, a recent
newspaper poll indicates Vice President George Bush could face a
close race in Texas in this fall's general election if Sen. Lloyd
Bentsen of Texas was on the Democratic ticket headed by Michael
Dukakis.
   The Houston Chronicle poll, released Thursday, showed 48 percent
of those surveyed preferred Bush, the all-but-certain Republican
nominee, while 41 percent said they would vote for Dukakis when
voters were asked to consider only the two candidates.
   However, when the Democratic front-runner was paired with
Bentsen as his running mate, Bush led Dukakis by only two
percentage points, 43 percent to 41 percent, falling within the
poll's three-point margin of error.
   The poll surveyed 785 voters between May 13-28.
