<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Obit-Roberts     06-03 0174</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Roberts,0180</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Editor Who Defended Press Freedom Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Brian Roberts, a former newspaper editor who faced
jail for championing press freedom over a report on the Nigerian
civil war, has died at age 81, a family death notice said.
   Roberts, who died Thursday, spent 37 years with the Telegraph
newspapers in London and edited The Sunday Telegraph from 1966 to
1976.
   In 1971, he was acquitted at an Old Bailey trial of charges
under the Official Secrets Act. Roberts had published a
confidential diplomatic report on the prospects in the Nigerian
government's war to prevent the secession of the eastern territory
of Biafra.
   He was the first British journalist to be awarded the gold medal
from the Institute of Journalists for his stand. He campaigned for
an amendment of the act, which makes even trivial official
information an official secret.
   Roberts said the section ``hovered in the background of his
journalistic career like a vulture.''
   Roberts left a widow, Dora, and a son.
   The cause of death was not revealed.
</TEXT>
