<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Philippines     06-03 0472</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Philippines,0487</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Military Raids Convent to Search For Rebels</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CEBU CITY, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Military intelligence agents
raided a convent in an unsuccessful search for three Communist
rebels, military and church sources said today.
   Rev. Jose Borces, executive secretary of the Visayas Secretariat
for Social Action, said armed intelligence agents told the nuns in
Wednesday's raid at the Missionary Sisters of Mary that they were
looking for three members of the rebel's Mindanao Commission.
   The agents had a search warrant signed by a judge, according to
Borces, but he said they told the nuns they thought the convent was
a private home.
   Borces said he complained to Cardinal Ricardo Vidal, archbishop
of Cebu, about the raid in Cebu City about 300 miles south of
Manila.
   Col. Geronimo Dumadapat, chief of the area Military Intelligence
Group, said his office had information that the convent was used as
a hideout for members of the banned Communist Party of the
Philippines.
   He said the building had been under surveillance for about a
month before the raid.
   The military has charged in the past that rebels receive support
from social activist priests and nuns. Several priests in the
central Visayas islands have been identified as leaders of the
National Democratic Front, an umbrella organization of 12
underground groups controlled by the Communists.
   On Thursday, the military said religious cultists hacked to
death five Communist rebels in a surprise attack during which they
freed 15 villagers kidnapped by the guerrillas.
   The military also reported gunmen believed to be Communist
rebels shot dead five Philippine Constabulary troops as they played
basketball in Lanao del Sur province of Mindanao island.
   Lt. Col. Edgar Centino, spokesman for the army's 4th Infantry
Division, told reporters that five New People's Army guerrillas
Wednesday kidnapped the 15 villagers near Lianga in Surigao del Sur
province, about 550 miles southeast of Manila.
   Members of the Sacred Heart of Jesus religious cult caught up
with the rebels as they and their captives rested under a tree. The
cultists then attacked with machetes and killed all five rebels.
   The military frequently uses members of religious cults to fight
the rebels.
   Meanwhile, today in Manila, President Corazon Aquino proclaimed
democracy ``the natural shelter of freedom'' as she opened a
conference of 14 nations from Asia, Europe and Latin America which
have cast off dictatorship.
   Mrs. Aquino appealed to the delegates during the four-day
conference to search for ways to ensure that democracy ``retains
its guiding power'' in the world.
   The conference, proposed last year by Foreign Secretary Raul
Manglapus, brings together delegations from the Philippines,
Portugal, Uruguay, Honduras, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Guatemala, El
Salvador, Nicaragua, Greece, Spain, Argentina and the Dominican
Republic.
   Conference officials said invitations were sent to nations which
had overthrown dictatorship since 1973 and taken steps to build
democratic institutions in their wake.
</TEXT>
