<1ST_LINE>r a PM-FamilyGraduation     06-03 0473</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Family Graduation,0486</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Family Ends An Era _ And Starts Another _ At High School</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WEST DEPTFORD, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Commencement day at West Deptford
High School will span two generations for Gloria and Wilbert
Holmes, as the last two of their 18 children receive diplomas with
the first of their 36 grandchildren.
   ``It's the end and it's the beginning,'' said Mrs. Holmes, 58.
``I thank the Lord that it's over for me, but I still babysit every
morning.''
   The Holmes family will fill an entire section at the ceremony.
Only one child cannot attend: Donald, an Army sergeant stationed in
Germany.
   ``One of the most striking things about the Holmes family is
that all of the children have been polite, well-behaved
individuals,'' said William G. Stubbs, the high school's principal.
``None has ever gotten into serious trouble in school.
   ``I wish Mr. and Mrs. Holmes would market their formula for
raising children,'' he said.
   Like many mothers, Mrs. Holmes predicts she will be wiping tears
from her eyes at the June 22 ceremony. But after seeing the
children through school, her husband said he will be cheering.
   ``I'm so glad it's over,'' he said, referring to the graduations
of his two youngest children, 18-year-old Herbert and 17-year-old
Frances. ``Maybe now she (Mrs. Holmes) and I can have some time to
ourselves,'' said the 63-year-old retired maintenance man.
   Mrs. Holmes is a bit more sentimental, and pointed out that her
36 ``grannies'' are constantly at the house anyway. Wayne Young,
17, is only the first grandchild to graduate from high school.
   Mrs. Holmes admitted that over the years, her children sometimes
thought she was too strict. When dining out, for instance, she
never let them ask for seconds ``because people would think that
with so many of us, they were all starving to death. But when they
started having their own children, they began to know what I was
doing.''
   Despite her happy memories, Mrs. Holmes said she does not want
her children to have so many of their own. One son already has six
children, ``and I hope he doesn't have any more,'' she said.
   ``They all have good jobs that they shouldn't give up,'' Mrs.
Holmes said.
   Sally Jordan, a teacher who recalls most of the Holmes family,
said, ``They've been an exceptional group of kids.''
   One time, Ms. Jordan had three of the Holmes daughters on the
field hockey team she coached.
   ``They let me know that their mother made a chart and they had
chores to do and they'd just have to work field hockey around it,''
she said.
   ``I think it's a tribute to fine parents,'' Ms. Jordan said.
``Their parents expected a lot of them and cooperated with the
school system. I've often used them as great examples of the way
kids should be brought up.''
</TEXT>
