<2ND_LINE>PM-Sri Lanka, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0478,0560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two More Dead In Election-Related Violence</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with today's violence. PICKS up
4th graf, `At least ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Suspected Sinhalese extremists today
killed two candidates in Sri Lanka's Southern province and burnt
government buildings, a day after they attempted to disrupt voting
in two other provinces.
   A police officer in Colombo said one victim belonged to the
governing United National Party and the other to a communist
alliance.
   The officer, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said he had no
further details on the killings.
   At least 75 cases of arson in the Southern province, which
electes members to local government councils on June 9, were
reported, he said. The targets were government buildings and
electricity and telephone posts, he said.
   The violence erupted hours after officials announced results of
elections held on Thursday in the Western and Central provinces.
   The United National Party won 87 of the 158 seats at stake while
a three-party communist alliance won 60 seats. The Sri Lanka Moslem
Congress clinched nine seats and two members of the Liberal Party
were also elected, the election department announced.
   The polling was marred by violence blamed on the People's
Liberation Front, an extremist Sinhalese group.
   At least six people, including two policemen, were killed on
Wednesday and Thursday as the front launched a wave of arson and
bombings in an attempt to disrupt voting.
   Members of the front burnt 15 government buildings, two trains
and at least six buses in the Western and Central Provinces where
polling was held, officials said.
   On Thursday, polling booths were attacked by Sinhalese radicals
with bombs and grenades, police officers in Colombo said. The
officers spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The front opposes the plan to elect provincial councils in the
nine provinces in the country, saying it gives too many
concessisons to Tamils.
   The plan is aimed at giving the minority Tamil community, which
makes up a majority of the population in the Northern and Eastern
provinces, more say in local government to quell their five-year
separtist war.
   Four of the country's provinces went to the polls on April 28 in
elections that were also won by the United National Party.
   The Southern province is to elect council members next week but
polls in the Northern and Eastern provinces have been posponed
indefinitely because Tamil rebels have renounced the peace plan and
are continuing their violent agitation for an independent homeland.
   Tamils form 18 percent of Sri Lanka's 16 million people. The
rebels claim that their community is discriminated against by the
Sinhalese, who comprise 75 percent of the population and control
the government and military.
   Thursday's polls were also marked by opposition allegations of
rigging. Rajiva Wijesiwha, president of the Liberal Party, said
members of the governing party impersonated voters after driving
opposition representatives out of polling booths.
   Election Commissioner Chandrananda De Silva said the charges
were being investigated. He said 1.5 million of the 3.6 million
eligible voters participated in the polls.
   The turn-out is considered low when compared to past elections
in Sri Lanka. A Liberation Front threat to shoot voters is believed
to be the cause of the low turnout.
</TEXT>
