<1ST_LINE>r w PM-WashingtonInBrief     06-03 0438</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Washington In Brief,430</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Air Force says two of its facilities
within the United States and three overseas structures have
unacceptably high levels of natural radioactive radon gas.
   The service said in a statement issued Thursday that the high
readings turned up at its academy and Peterson Air Force Base near
Colorado Springs, Colo. and at Andersen Air Base on the island of
Guam in a new testing program.
   The Air Force would not identify the other two bases outside the
country until it had notified the host country's government.
   The service said it is launching a more extensive radon testing
program and that it would take ``quick corrective action'' at the
facilities where the high gas levels have been found.
   Radon is a colorless, odorless natural product of decaying
uranium in the soil. Medical research has indicated that exposure
to high levels of radon over extended periods may increase the risk
of lung cancer.
