<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Fratricide     06-03 0293</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Fratricide,0303</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Brother Shoots Brother Over Bicycle</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WILLIAMSTOWN, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 12-year-old boy shot his 14-year-old
brother to death in an argument over a bicycle, state police said.
   Freddy Partin of Williamstown was charged with second-degree
manslaughter Wednesday in the death of his brother, Timothy. The
boys had been quarreling over who would ride their bicycle when the
shooting occurred, police said.
   Police said Freddy rode the bike to a nearby service station
after the shooting Wednesday, borrowed a quarter from the cashier
and called his mother, Nannie Jane Partin, to tell her what
happened.
   ``There's no rhyme or reason here,'' said state police Trooper
Jim Dolwick. ``One brother winds up killing the other over
something as trivial as a bicycle. How do you explain that?''
   The two boys were at home alone in the living room of the small
frame house rented by their mother when the shooting occurred,
police said. It was not immediately clear who owned the gun.
   Both boys attended Williamstown Elementary School, where classes
ended two weeks ago for the summer.
   Janis Fox, supervisor of instruction for the Williamstown
schools, said Ms. Partin, who is a single parent and employed at a
fast-food restaurant, ``worked a lot and I'm sure the boys were
left alone a lot because of that.''
   She said neither of the younger brothers was a discipline
problem in school, but Freddy ``is a child who had to learn to
control his temper.''
   Freddy was charged as a juvenile, and Grant County Attorney Jim
Purcell said the maximum sentence he could receive would be to be
placed in the care of the Kentucky Cabinet for Human Resources
until he is 18.
   The boy was released to the custody of his uncle, Richard Partin.
</TEXT>
