<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Kapoor-Obit     06-03 0282</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Kapoor-Obit,0290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Indian Film Star Raj Kapoor Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Raj Kapoor, India's most famous film
star, has died after a month in the hospital following an asthma
attack, state television reported. He was 64.
   Kapoor, known as ``the Charlie Chaplin of India,'' acted in 60
films and produced or directed 18 others over a career that spanned
four decades. Almost all his movies were hits in India, and he was
perhaps the most popular Indian film actor abroad, with followers
in the Soviet Union, the Middle East and China.
   Among his best-known films was ``Awara'' (The Vagabond), in
which he borrowed from Chaplin and played the part with trousers
riding high above his ankles and a perpetual forlorn look on his
face.
   A semi-biographical film, ``Mera Naam Joker'' (My Name is
Joker), filled 25 reels and allowed the audience two intermissions
in its more than four-hour showing.
   Kapoor, who died Thursday, was stricken on May 2 during a film
awards ceremony at which he was given India's highest movie honor,
the Dada Saheb Phalke Award. He was already in such weakened
physical condition that Indian President Ramaswami Venkataraman had
to come down from the stage to give him the trophy.
   The actor later was carried from the auditorium and hospitalized.
   Kapoor's father, the late Prithvi Raj Kapoor, was a stage and
screen actor and three of Kapoor's sons _ Randhir, Rishi and Rajeev
_ are popular actors. Kapoor's two younger brothers, Shammi and
Shashi, also are screen stars.
   Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi issued a statement mourning the
death, calling Kapoor, ``a person who became a legend in his
lifetime.''
   There was no immediate word of funeral arrangements.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
