<2ND_LINE>PM-Somalia-Trapped, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0411,0381</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>PRECEDE London</HEAD>
<HEAD>Somali Rebels Say Foreigners Safe In Captured Areas, Warn Against
Evacuation</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS thruout to UPDATE with rebel statement.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHELLE FAUL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Somali rebels have warned the
United States and other foreign governments against trying to
evacuate about 160 foreigners trapped by Somalia's civil war.
   However, the anti-government guerrillas said they would agree to
a U.N.-sponsored removal of the foreigners, who were in parts of
northern Somalia that apparently fell into rebel hands earlier this
week.
   The foreigners, mostly aid workers, include Americans, Britons
and French.
   The British Foreign Office said about 25 Britons were there and
that they were not considered in immediate danger.
   There were reports Thursday that the United States and Britain
intended to remove their nationals. None of the Africa-based
diplomats for both countries contacted by The Associated Press
verified those reports.
   Saeed Yusuf, a rebel spokesman in Addis Ababa, said Thursday his
guerrilla movement would cooperate only with an evacuation
organized by the United Nations.
   ``We reject and warn against any form of intervention against
this just war of liberation,'' Yusuf said. ``We are worried that
this might be an excuse to turn the evacuation into a kind of
intervention. Our troops would have no choice but to stand against
them.''
   The United States is Somalia's most important ally, and Britain
was the former colonial ruler in northern Somalia.
   The rebels claimed they captured the main northern town of
Hargeisa on Tuesday after a nine-hour battle. However, the British
Foreign Office said Somali government officials denied the claim.
   Government officials could not be reached for comment today.
   Yusuf said government troops were trying to regain the town.
   The rebels said they took Berbera, Somalia's main seaport and
the site of a U.S. Navy construction unit, on Wednesday.
   Yusuf said the rebels controlled most of the countryside in the
north and a cluster of small towns in the center of the region.
   He said the foreigners in those areas were safe in their homes.
   ``Any danger is from the side of the government troops who are
engaged in the shelling of towns won by the SNM (rebels),'' he said.
</TEXT>
