<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Denmark     06-03 0347</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Denmark,0360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Schlueter Ready To Present New Minority Coalition</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COPENHAGEN, Denmark (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Acting Prime Minister Poul Schlueter
was reported to be close to an agreement today on a new coalition
government, ending a six-week political impasse that began with a
dispute over Denmark's links with NATO.
   Schlueter was expected to present his minority cabinet to Queen
Margrethe II later today, the conservative Berlingske Tidende
newspaper said.
   The cabinet would be made up of Schlueter's Conservative Party,
Liberals and Social-Liberals.
   The tripartite coalition would command 67 seats in the
179-member Folketing (parliament), compared with the 70 mustered by
the outgoing four-party group that has governed Denmark since 1982.
   Niels Helveg Petersen, leader of the Social-Liberals, said on
Danish radio that he had won ``crucial concessions'' on security
policy during talks with Schlueter and Liberal leader Uffe
Ellemann-Jensen.
   Petersen's small centrist party, which held the balance of power
in the outgoing parliament, helped topple Schlueter's minority
government over the nuclear arms issue.
   The Folketing passed an opposition-sponsored resolution April 14
calling on the government to remind visiting warships of Denmark's
longstanding peacetime ban on nuclear weapons.
   Following strong objections to the resolution by Denmark's NATO
allies, Schlueter called a snap election for May 10 rather than
implement the resolution.
   The ballot was inclusive, and a stalemate emerged between the
eight parties which won seats.
   The coalition agreement hammered out between Schlueter, Petersen
and Ellemann-Jensen, who is acting foreign minister, was not made
public.
   In the new cabinet Schlueter and Ellemann-Jensen would retain
their posts, as would Finance Minister Palle Simonsen. Petersen
would be appointed economic affairs minister, Berlingske Tidende
predicted.
   The leftist opposition, comprising Social Democrats and the
Socialist People's party, together have 79 seats.
   The rar-right Progress party, which made the biggest gains in
the election, has 16 seats. But it was excluded from coalition
talks because its anti-tax and anti-immigration policies are far
outside Denmark's mainstream politics.
   In order to make room for the Social-Liberals, Schlueter shed
the two junior partners from his previous coalition, the nine-seat
Center Democrat and the four-seat Christian People's parties.
</TEXT>
