<1ST_LINE>r p PM-SanDiegoMayor     06-03 0555</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-San Diego Mayor,0570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Maureen O'Conner Cruising To Election Day In Laid-Back Contest</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Retransmits to fix category code</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Maureen O'Connor is cruising to election
day next week in a mayoral contest that the news media in the
nation's seventh-largest city have virtually ignored because even
insiders find it dull.
   ``To even say the race has been boring is too generous _ it
hasn't been that exciting,'' political consultant Nick Johnson
said. ``It seems like Maureen O'Connor is on a perpetual honeymoon
and the rest of San Diego is on the Love Boat.''
   O'Connor, who won the seat in a special 1986 race called after
former Mayor Roger Hedgecock's felony conviction, has been an
overwhelming favorite in Tuesday's non-partisan primary since the
race's outset.
   She has waged a low-key, low-budget campaign against City
Councilman Floyd Morrow and three minor candidates: semi-retired
public relations official John Kelley, City Hall gadfly Rose Lynne
and businessman Charles Ulmschneider.
   The race _ the city's fourth mayoral contest in five years _ has
drawn only cursory attention from the city's 875,000 residents and
its news media.
   Radio ads have been scarce and television commercials rarer. A
series of debates that marked recent mayoral campaigns fell flat
this year when O'Connor refused to participate.
   The candidates' only major joint appearance will be a one-hour
debate to be broadcast on local television Saturday night.
   ``There wasn't a need for a lot of (debates) because we've all
run for office before and the public already knows who we are and
where we stand,'' said O'Connor, the city's first female mayor.
``This is kind of like a reunion.''
   By race's end, the candidates' combined expenditures may barely
top $100,000.
   O'Connor had spent only $48,839 by May 21, about $220,000 less
than she spent gaining the seat in 1986. In her unsuccessful 1983
bid, O'Connor _ wife of Robert O. Peterson, founder of Jack in the
Box restaurants _ spent $780,000 and was accused of trying to buy
the election.
   O'Connor, 41, maintains that her somnolent campaign is in
keeping with San Diegans' attitude toward the contest.
   ``We've had so many mayor's races lately that most people are
just tired of it,'' she said.
   But Morrow, a 55-year-old lawyer who finished third in the 1986
race behind O'Connor and City Councilman Bill Cleator, has accused
O'Connor of behaving like royalty, not an elected official.
   ``Local government is supposed to be the level of government
closest to the people, but you couldn't prove that by Maureen,''
said Morrow, who says the mayor views the campaign ``more like a
coronation than an election.''
   There are few differences between O'Connor and Morrow _ both
Democrats _ on most citywide issues.
   Recent polls indicated O'Connor has a 2-1 lead over Morrow. She
needs to win more than 50 percent of the vote to forgo a November
runoff. Should she receive less, the top two finishers will face
each other in November.
   O'Connor says she has restored stability to City Hall after
Hedgecock's forced resignation and other scandals, enhanced the
average citizen's access to the mayor's office and strengthened
growth-management policies.
   Hedgecock was forced to resign from his four-year term after he
was convicted of perjury and conspiracy stemming from allegations
that he plotted with political backers to illegally finance his
1983 mayoral campaign.
</TEXT>
