<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Reagan-Reporters     06-03 0157</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan-Reporters,150</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With PM-Reagan Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Reagan Plays Oneupmanship With Reporters</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan, after being asked several times
this week why he seemed tired, turned the tables on reporters in
London today, suggesting that his interrogators ``take the rest of
the day off.''
   Reagan, who seemed fatigued and who walked with an apparent limp
on occasion during his five-day summit with Soviet leader Mikhail
S. Gorbachev, was barraged with questions while posing for pictures
with Japanese Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita.
   The rapid-fire questioning came toward the end of a week in
which Reagan was asked whether he was tired and whether he was
sleeping well.
   Reagan said ``I wasn't tired,'' and White House chief of staff
Howard Baker said ``we're all tired.''
   So today, when Reagan was commencing his talks with Takeshita,
the president interrupted reporters, saying:
   ``We have to go to work. Why don't you take the rest of the day
off?''
</TEXT>
