<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Britain-Dresses     06-03 0177</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Dresses,0183</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tokyo Museum Buys Old Dresses</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dresses which graced royal occasions between the
two world wars were snapped up on Thursday led by a Japanese museum
which paid up to five times the estimated value for some items.
   Auctioneers Phillips said the Fashion Foundation Museum of Tokyo
bought the eight best lots among the 600 dresses.
   The museum paid $6,120 for a Coco Chanel brown chiffon dress and
$3,660 for a 1920s black silk dress by Madeleine Vionnet.
   Molineux, Worth and Lanvin were among the designer labels on the
dresses, many of which had been worn by ladies-in-waiting at
Buckingham Palace. They were passed on to Ellen Wallis who ran a
discreet second-hand dress service.
   When her business closed in 1937, Mrs. Wallis left the dresses
to her daughter, Robina. After Robina's death last year, the
dresses were found in crates in the stables of her manor house in
Cornwall.
   ``What was found was a time-capsule of superb French haute
couture,'' said Phillips's costume specialist, Anne-Marie Benson.
   The auction totaled nearly $94,000.
</TEXT>
