<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Iran 1stLd-Writethru a0511 06-03 0301</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Iran, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0511 ,0304</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rafsanjani Rallies Iranian War Effort</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS thruout to UPDATE with Rafsanjani quotes, CORRECT
reason why he was called `temporary speaker,' TRIMS, no pickup</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN MARRIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran's new acting commander-in-chief
today told Iranians they must take the war with Iraq more seriously
following recent battle defeats.
   Addressing a Moslem prayer congregation in Tehran, Hashemi
Rafsanjani said there should be ``no compromise, no submission, and
no backing down from our rights'' in the war, the Islamic Republic
News Agency said.
   ``We should take the situation more seriously,'' Rafsanjani told
the worshipers.
   Iran has suffered two recent major defeats at the war front.
   Iraqi forces on April 18 retook the southern Iraqi Faw
peninsula, which had been captured by Iran in February 1986. Then
on May 25, Iraqi troops retook arge chunks of Iraqi land east of
Basra.
   The twin defeats for Iran, along with a series of naval clashes
with the United States in mid-April, apparently have jolted the
Tehran rulers into making the leadership changes.
   The official news agency referred to the 53-year-old politician
as the ``temporary speaker'' of parliament. He was elected
temporary speaker during a parliament session May 29.
   According to parliamentary rules, a permanent speaker cannot be
chosen until the credentials of new deputies to the parliament have
been approved, a process which has not been completed following
recent elections.
   The agency reported that Rafsanjani sent a cable to the
87-year-old Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini thanking the patriarch for
appointing him acting commander-in-chief on Thursday.
   In his cable to Khomeini, Rafsanjani expressed hope that he
would succeed in carrying out his new duties ``with divine
dispensations and through the all-out cooperation of the people and
the armed forces,'' the news agency reported.
</TEXT>
