<1ST_LINE>r i PM-India-Heat     06-03 0212</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-India-Heat,0219</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Heat Death Toll Exceeds 400, Religious Rite Fails To Bring Rain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A searing heat wave in northern India
has left nearly 400 people dead in the past six days, the United
News of India reported.
   The temperature in parts of Punjab state exceeded 113 degrees.
New Delhi registered a high of 111 degrees.
   An effort to invoke rain through a Hindu fire ritual, called a
yagna, apparently failed, the news agency said Thursday.
   The yagna was performed last week in the town of Mathura in
Uttar Pradesh state, with meteorologists allowed to monitor
potential weather changes, UNI said.
   The scientists reported Thursday that despite the sacred flames,
no rain has fallen on Mathura or surrounding areas.
   The desert state of Rajasthan continued to be hardest hit, with
45 more people dead Thursday of sunstroke and other heat-related
illnesses, the news agency said.
   Since the heat wave began last week, 336 deaths have been
reported in the state. The total includes 15 in Madhya Pradesh
state, 11 in Orissa, six in Uttar Pradesh state and two in
Maharashtra, UNI said.
   At least 27 deaths have been reported in New Delhi. The United
News of India said that 40 people were hospitalized Thursday with
heat-related problems.
</TEXT>
