<FILEID>AP-NR-06-03-88 0723EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PrisonRiot     06-03 0448</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Prison Riot,0460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Accused Ringleaders File Suit Claiming Rights Being Violated</HEAD>
<DATELINE>McALESTER, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nine inmates accused of participating in
a prison riot last month have sued the state, claiming they are
being held improperly at Oklahoma's maximum-security prison and are
forced to live in unsanitary conditions.
   The suit, filed by mail this week, claims the inmates have been
``forced to wear nothing but their underwear'' since arriving at
the Oklahoma State Penitentiary here.
   Shortly after the riot last month, corrections officials said
inmates believed to be directly involved in the uprising were being
clothed only in underwear for security reasons. Spokesman Jerry
Massie said Thursday he was not certain if the inmates had been
given clothes since.
   The nine are being held at the McAlester prison with about 40
inmates accused of involvement in the three-day riot at the
medium-security Mack Alford Correctional Center in Stringtown.
   Sixteen other convicts accused of involvement in the riot, which
ended May 16, pleaded innocent Tuesday to charges during initial
appearances in Atoka County.
   Preliminary hearings in the riot cases are set to begin next
Tuesday at the Atoka County Courthouse. Prosecutors said their
investigation is continuing and more charges could be filed.
   In the lawsuit filed through the mail this week in McAlester,
inmate Brad Allen Smith claims the convicts are not allowed to wear
anything but underwear while being held in the special cells at the
McAlester prison unit called ``the rock.''
   The unit was closed by a federal court order in the early 1980s,
but was reopened after the riot. Most of the inmates in the unit
are accused of being the ringleaders or main participants in the
uprising, authorities said.
   Smith alleges the inmates are being forced to live in dirty,
unhealthy conditions and are denied the right to exercise and to
use the prison law library.
   He also claims inmates have not been allowed to shower and have
been denied clean underwear and basic hygiene items. The suit
claims the cells have no electricity or ventilation systems.
   Other inmates allege in the suit that prison officials did not
follow proper Department of Corrections policies in placing them in
the special unit.
   Another 400 inmates from Mack Alford who authorities said did
not participate in the riot are housed in the East and West units
at the state prison here, which were reopened after court-ordered
closings to accomodate the large influx of inmates.
   Two inmates in those units also filed a lawsuit claiming their
rights have been violated. They allege their living conditions are
substandard, that raw sewage leaks into their cells and that they
are not allowed to exercise or use the law library.
</TEXT>
