<1ST_LINE>r a PM-RepentantDealer     06-03 0299</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Repentant Dealer,0309</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woman Walks Into Station And Confesses Drug Dealing</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Rosezine is cq</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PATERSON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An 18-year-old woman walked into the city
police station and handed over a bag containing 87 vials of crack,
saying she was tired of dealing drugs and wanted to turn herself in.
   Rosezine Jones, charged with possession of the potent form of
cocaine and possession with intent to distribute, did not enter a
plea during her arraignment Thursday, said municipal court clerk
Princess Reaves.
   A plea will be entered at a probable cause hearing scheduled
June 14, Ms. Reaves said. Ms. Jones did not yet have an attorney
and was returned to Passaic County Jail, where she has been held on
$35,000 bail since her arrest Wednesday morning, Ms. Reaves said.
   Detective Andrew Murray said Ms. Jones, who is less than 5 feet
tall and weighs barely 100 pounds, told him she operated alone,
traveling to Harlem in New York City a few times a week to purchase
crack.
   She sold it around Paterson, including at a playground two
blocks from a parochial school, police said.
   ``She just said she didn't want to do it anymore,'' Murray said.
   He added he didn't think Ms. Jones told police the whole story.
   ``I don't think she could get away with doing that,'' he said.
``I'm pretty sure she was working for someone.''
   Police also speculated she may have taken the drug from someone
and turned herself in out of fear for her safety.
   The crack she turned over to police has an estimated street
value of $1,600, Murray said.
   Regardless of why Ms. Jones acted, Murray said, he does not
expect others to follow her lead.
   ``There's a lot of money to be made,'' he said. ``They're not
giving themselves up.''
</TEXT>
