<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Israel 2ndLd-Writethru a0552 06-03 0738</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0552,0756</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Strike Begins, Occupied Territories Shut Down</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with one Arab killed, seven
wounded in West Bank. CORRECTS anniversary of invasion of Lebanon
in 12th graf pvs: `In addition...' Trims. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By G.G. LaBELLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Palestinian protesters virtually shut down the
occupied territories today in a general strike viewed as a test of
the six-month Arab uprising. One Palestinian was shot and killed
and seven were injured during demonstrations in the West Bank.
   The army put 190,000 Palestinians under restrictions to prevent
violence on the opening day of the three-day strike called to
protest a new Middle East visit by Secretary of State George P.
Shultz. A leaflet calling for the strike said Shultz was trying to
quell the uprising.
   Shultz returns to the Middle East today for the fourth time in
five months to win support for a U.S. plan that calls for an
international conference to launch peace talks.
   In the West Bank village of Shuykh, Israeli soldiers fatally
shot 20-year-old Mustafa Ahmed Halaika in the chest, officials at
the Alia Hospital in nearby Hebron said.
   They said two other Arabs were wounded in the legs or arms, and
four suffered beating injuries or the effects of tear gas when a
protest broke out in the village.
   Hospital officials also said that a 15-year-old Palestinian was
wounded in his left arm during clashes with Israeli soldiers in the
nearby village of Siir.
   The army command said it was checking the reports. One military
official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said reports from
the village said Halaika was killed by civilians, but the reason
for his death was not clear.
   In Jerusalem's walled Old City, a group of youths demonstrated
on the sacred Temple Mount after today's Moslem prayers, raising
the outlawed Palestinian flag, police said.
   In the Gaza Strip, nearly all shops were closed, public transit
was shut down, and streets were still. Similar reports came from
cities and towns in the West Bank.
   In Bethlehem on the West Bank, outlawed Palestinian flags flew
from electricity poles, and normally crowded Manger Square was
deserted.
   ``Observe the strike, or we are going to burn,'' read a slogan
painted on a wall.
   Few of the 110,000 Palestinians who work in Israel reported to
their jobs, according to Arab and Israeli media reports.
   Today's strike contrasted sharply with one on Monday, when
thousands of Arab workers defied orders issued in a leaflet from
the underground United National Leadership of the Uprising.
   Monday's strike supported Israeli officials' view that the
uprising was waning, and political analysts said the new three-day
protest would be a test for the uprising.
   ``This is very important for the image of the leadership'' said
Clinton Bailey, an Arab affairs expert at Tel Aviv University.
   Saib Erakat, a Palestinian political science professor,
predicted full compliance. ``The Israelis have been saying since
December that the uprising is dying down,'' said Erakat, who
teaches at the West Bank's An-Najah University.
   He said Monday's partial failure came from confusion over dates,
not fatigue among Palestinians.
   In addition to Shultz's visit, the strike call also coincides
with the sixth anniversary of Israel's invasion of Lebanon on
Monday, and Sunday's 21st anniversary of the 1967 Middle East war
in which Israel captured the West Bank and Gaza Strip from its Arab
neighbors.
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir said in remarks broadcast today by
the army radio that he saw signs the uprising was waning, but he
added:
   ``Unfortunately, there are also things that prevent this from
happening, including all kinds of undesirable intervention by Jews
and Israelis.''
   Curfews were clamped today on the Shati and Jabaliya refugee
camps in Gaza and the towns of Shuweika, Jamain and Qalqiliya in
the West Bank, an army spokesman said. Eight other areas were
declared closed, preventing people from coming and going.
   Nearly 170,000 people in the Gaza Strip and another 20,000 in
the West Bank were affected by the restrictions.
   According to U.N. figures, 199 Palestinians have been killed in
the uprising. Two Israelis also have died.
   The army on Thursday retracted figures it released earlier this
week which put the Arab death toll at 207. The army said it had
changed how it compiles the deaths, and spokesman Col. Raanan
Gissin said the army was certain of only 152 deaths, all at the
hands of soldiers.
</TEXT>
