<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Trains Bump,0148</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trains Bump; 20 To Hospitals</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An elevated train bumped into another train on
the city's South Side today, sending at least 20 people to
hospitals for treatment of minor injuries, authorities said.
   The train was traveling about 5 mph when it hit a work train
carrying five Chicago Transit Authority repairmen, supervisor Joe
Daquilante said.
   Electric power was temporarily cut so rescue crews could get to
the trains, but traffic resumed shortly after the incident,
Daquilante said.
   Three hospitals reported 20 people in their emergency rooms.
   ``They had whiplash, just minor stuff,'' said Nellie Davis, a
nursing supervisor at Chicago Osteopathic Medical Center, where 12
people were checked and released.
   Another half dozen were treated and released at Holy Cross
Hospital, and Michael Reese Hospital and Medical Center was
treating two people with neck and back pain.
</TEXT>
