<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF--HogFarm     06-03 0201</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Hog Farm,0206</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Downtown Hog Farm To Call It Quits</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HYGIENE, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The owners of a hog farm set up to protest
zoning in downtown Hygiene have decided to call it quits.
   ``We hope to be gone before the snow flies,'' said Jerry Swart,
who managed the hog farm for the owner, Houston Downs. ``We hate
this county so bad, we never wanted to come here in the first
place.''
   Downs wanted to use the property as a covered parking facility
for recreational vehicles and said if his land was not rezoned to
commercial, he would install a hog farm. And he did.
   ``I am not for wall-to-wall growth, but then I am not for
government taking something away without compensation,'' said
Swart. ``That can't be democracy.''
   But nobody really seemed to care if there was a hog farm in the
middle of this small northern Colorado community. In the end, Swart
and Downs lost between $4,000 and $5,000 on the venture.
   ``The only thing we didn't have happen to us was swine
cholera,'' Swart said. ``With that you go out one morning and find
all of them dead.''
   And so, the Hygiene Hog Farm is for sale.
</TEXT>
