<DOCNO> AP880603-0103 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-03-88 0907EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Soviet-Sakharov     06-03 0573</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Sakharov,0592</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sakharov Says Gorbachev Deserves Benefit Of Doubt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nobel Peace Prize winner Andrei D. Sakharov told
reporters today that Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev must be
given the benefit of the doubt to implement his reforms and improve
human rights.
   In a scene that would have been unthinkable in the past,
Sakharov spoke to reporters for almost two hours at the Foreign
Ministry press center.
   Sakharov said the fact that he was appearing at the press center
``reflects a change in the situation in this country and it's not a
matter of me changing my position.''
   One of the Soviet Union's leading physicists, Sakharo was a
founder of the Soviet dissident movement and was confined for
nearly seven years to the closed city of Gorky for his criticism of
the Soviet intervention in Afghanistan.
   ``I believe sizeable changes have taken place of late. Of
course, they are not exhaustive and do not ensure the full
implementation of human rights,'' Sakharov said.
   He said he has ``a lot of apprehensions'' about the future of
Gorbachev's reforms for Soviet society but believes they ultimately
will succeed because they are a historic necessity.
   ``We should give it an advance measure of trust,'' he said. ``An
expression of trust in perestroika at this time would only
encourage it, and improve the human rights situation.''
   Perestroika, which means ``restructuring,'' refers to
Gorbachev's efforts to reform the economy and society.
   Sakharov praised this week's Moscow summit meeting, but said the
Americans and Soviets could have made more progress on nuclear
weapons talks.
   ``The specific results of the summit were not as impressive as
the Washington summit,'' he said.
   Sakharov urged the two sides to work for more progress on a
treaty to halve their long-range nuclear missiles, saying they can
work around their disputes over Reagan's planned Strategic Defense
Initiative _ the ``Star Wars'' space-based nuclear shield _ and
verification.
   ``I am sure that talking about the 50 percent cuts an agreement
is possible even without any connection to the SDI program,'' he
said. Settling of verification problems is possible if the two
sides decide politically to do it, he said.
   Sakharov's wife, Yelena Bonner, bitterly criticized a reporter
for asking whether Sakharov had made an agreement with authorities
not to talk about certain topics at the unusual news conference.
   She said Sakharov held the news conference because reporters in
Moscow for the summit meeting between President Reagan and
Gorbachev had called ``from morning to night,'' asking for
interviews.
   Sakharov, who helped develop the Soviet hydrogen bomb in the
1950s, won the Nobel Peace Prize in 1975 for his human rights work.
   In January 1980, he was banished to the closed city of Gorky for
criticizing the Soviet military intervention in Afghanistan and
remained there until December 1986, when Gorbachev allowed him to
return to Moscow.
   He has since returned to his scientific work and has become
increasingly reluctant to talk to reporters. Instead, he has
expressed his opinions in several letters published in the official
Soviet press.
   He said he was told late last year by President Gury Marchuk of
the Soviet Academy of Sciences that he may not leave the country
because of secret information to which he had access until 1968.
   ``Personally, I believe it's not a matter of my former access to
secret information. It's a matter of confidence in me,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
