<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ShopperAd     06-03 0213</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Shopper Ad,0218</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Bag Lady' Ad Pulled After Opposition</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERSEY CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An advertisement for a swank shopping
mall that used the term ``bag lady'' to describe a well-dressed
shopper has been pulled after city officials called it offensive.
   Officials at Newport Centre, a new mall on the Jersey City
waterfront across from Manhattan, apologized and withdrew the
newspaper spots.
   The ads asked, ``What you do call a typical shopper at Newport
Centre?''
   ``Bag Lady,'' is the answer, next to a picture of a woman
dressed to the nines and holding a Newport Centre shopping bag.
   Barbara Willis, a spokeswoman for Newport, said the ad campaign
was developed around the theme of shopping bags, and the reference
to bag lady was ``just one of those things that got by us.''
   She said the shopping center had received several telephone
calls complaining the ads were insensitive to homeless people who
must carry around their belongings in shopping bags.
   Mayor Anthony R. Cucci said: ``Bag lady has a very special
meaning in Jersey City, and it is not this. They should know
better.''
   City Council President Glenn Cunningham said: ``I'm sure it
wasn't meant to be tasteless, but it sure ended up being tasteless.
Housing the homeless is a major problem here.''
</TEXT>
