<FILEID>AP-NR-06-03-88 0933EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-AIDSCommission 1stLd-Writethru a0415 06-03 0841</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AIDS Commission, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0415,820</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Watkins Sees Little Room For Debate Over AIDS Recommendations</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Tops with 6 grafs of new Watkins comments; picks up 4th graf,
`The AIDS'
^By JERRY ESTILL</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of the White House AIDS
commission said today he sees little room for debate over his
strong recommendations, which are getting rave reviews from public
figures active in the battle against the disease.
   As affected groups challenged President Reagan to follow through
on the recommendations made public Thursday, commission chairman
James D. Watkins stressed his call for strong federal
anti-discrimination protection of AIDS victims. He said on NBC-TV's
``Today'' show that without such protection, fear among victims
will make the fatal disease ``very difficult to control.''
   The administration is on record _ through Health and Human
Services Secretary Otis R. Bowen _ as opposing federal legislation,
saying the issue should be addressed at the state and local level.
   Watkins, a retired Navy admiral, said there could still be
debate on the commission before the recommendations, which now
number 579, go to the president. But he said, in his opinion, there
is little room for debate.
   ``I believe we're there, and it's certainly, in my opinion, from
the nearly 600 recommendations, a kind of indictment on all of us
that we haven't done the job in being responsive to this
epidemic,'' Watkins said.
   Response to the report from members of Congress, gay rights
groups and health officials was enthusiastic.
   ``The AIDS commission is giving us sound recommendations,'' said
Rep.
   Henry Waxman, D-Calif. ``I hope the president will follow his
own commission's advice.''
   Waxman is among several members of Congress pushing for
anti-discrimination legislation.
   Tim Sweeney, deputy executive director of the New York-based Gay
Men's Health Crisis, termed the report ``courageous, aggressive and
compassionate.''
   ``We challenge the president, Congress and presidential
candidates to respond to this report by implementing its
recommendations,'' said Sweeney.
   Paul Kawata, director of the National AIDS Network, applauded
most of the report, particularly the sections calling for more
financial support for community-based AIDS groups. The National
AIDS Network is an umbrella organization covering more than 450
such local education and service agencies.
   Bailus Walker Jr., the former Massachusetts health commissioner
who heads the American Public Health Association, a private
organization of health professionals, said the recommendations
``are a rational, intelligent and compassionate response to the
epidemic'' and should ``serve as a blueprint for a coordinated
federal, state and local program designed to address the full scope
of the problem.''
   Most of the 269-page draft recommendations Watkins issued
Thursday are expected to be adopted with little substantive change
by the full commission and become its final report to the White
House on June 24.
   Watkins told reporters the proposals represent ``my estimate of
consensus within the commission,'' with the exception of a final
chapter which was not discussed in advance with other commissioners.
   In that chapter, Watkins calls for legislation giving the
surgeon general sweeping powers to deal with future national
medical emergencies that would be declared by a president.
   The report went on to call for ``federal legislation which
clearly provides comprehensive anti-discrimination protection for
HIV-infected individuals.''
   ``HIV-related discrimination is impairing this nation's ability
to limit the spread of the epidemic,'' Watkins' report said. ``As
long as discrimination occurs, and no strong national policy with
rapid and effective remedies against discrimination is established,
individuals who are infected with the HIV (the AIDS virus) will be
reluctant to come forward for testing, counseling and care.''
   Watkins said implementing all his recommendations probably would
call for spending about $3 billion a year more than is now being
budgeted for AIDS. About half that would be for expanded drug
treatment programs, a cornerstone of the commission's interim
report.
   Among the major Watkins recommendations:
   _Strong new laws on confidentiality, with sanctions to protect
the identity of those who test positive for the AIDS virus.
   _Greater state-federal financing of innovative methods of care
for people with AIDS.
   _Establishment of effective state partner-notification programs
targeted at those who have had sex with someone known by health
authorities to be infected with the virus.
   _Viewing the scope of the epidemic in terms of the number of
people infected with the virus _ perhaps as many as 1.4 million
Americans _ rather than the number who have so far developed AIDS,
less than 70,000. Scientists believe almost all of those infected
will eventually develop the disease itself.
   _Implementation of a comprehensive health education curriculum
in American schools, covering kindergarten through 12th grade, to
be in place by the year 2000. The curriculum _ including the point
at which AIDS should be discussed _ would be determined at the
local level.
   Under Watkins' plan, the surgeon general would take charge in
national health emergencies and be authorized to ``waive `business
as usual' procedures which impede emergency responsiveness.''
   Watkins says the present federal health bureaucracy has ``not
been successful in facilitating a response to a public health
emergency and resulted in a slow, halting and uneven response.''
</TEXT>
