<1ST_LINE>u i PM-China-Demonstration 2ndLd-Writethru   06-03 0525</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Demonstration, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0571,0543</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Beijing University Students Protest Death Of Classmate</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2 grafs for 4th pvs, `The official ...' to UPDATE with
third person detained. Pick up 5th graf pvs: `The demonstration...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 2,000 students from China's most
prestigious university took to the streets today to protest the
death of a fellow student in a brawl.
   The students at Beijing University put up posters angrily
demanding speedy punishment of local youths who killed the student
and tighter security around campus.
   Foreign sources said the illegal demonstration began
spontaneously at about 11 p.m. Thursday after students read a
poster on campus describing how Chai Qingfeng, a 22-year-old
geophysics student, had been attacked and killed.
   No participants were arrested.
   Officials said today that three people suspected in Chai's
slaying were detained and others were being sought.
   The demonstration was the largest since massive pro-democracy
rallies in December 1986 and January 1987. Those demonstrations led
to shakeups in the government and a conservative backlash against
``bourgeois liberalization.''
   The sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the
students arrived at Tiananmen Square, the large plaza in central
Beijing, shortly before dawn and passed through the square before
stopping at the Ministry of Public Security where they presented a
list of demands.
   About 700 students completed the 10-mile walk from the campus in
northwest Beijing to the square.
   During the march they linked arms and shouted for ``justice and
human rights.'' One banner read ``Pay back the blood debt.''
   Police monitored the march but did not interfere, said one
18-year-old marcher.
   The group marched around Tiananmen and then went to the nearby
Public Security Ministry, where ``the officials saidthey understood
us but that it is not a good idea to take to the streets,'' said
the woman marcher, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   The students presented eight demands, including the speedy
arrest and punishment of the killers, then got on buses and
returned quietly to campus.
   Students said Chai was beaten to death by ``hooligans'' when he
was buying liquor at a store outside the campus. Campus officials
said the attack took place Wednesday night, and Chai died Thursday.
   The Beijing Daily reported today that Chai, a graduate student,
was among three students from the geophysics department who were
attacked by thugs outside a small restaurant near the campus. It
did not say whether the other two were injured.
   The daily quoted city officials as saying that such acts of
violence will not be tolerated in the capital and that they had
asked police to deal quickly and severely with the assailants.
   The students also demanded full media coverage of the slaying, a
memorial service on campus for Chai, government compensation for
his family and tighter campus security.
   One poster called for a boycott of classes until the killers
were arrested, but students said most students attended classes.
   Last December about 1,000 students from the University of
Foreign Economic Relations in Beijing demonstrated over a similar
incident when a student was knifed to death by hoodlums.
   One of the attackers in that incident, a 22-year-old man, was
executed.
</TEXT>
