<1ST_LINE>u i ReaganBasksinTributesandPageantryinLondon     06-03 0906</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>Reagan Basks in Tributes and Pageantry in London</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 9 grafs new with motorcade color, anti-Contra
demonstrators; picks up pvs 5th graf bgng, Reagan returned; editing
changes, deletions throughout to tighten.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARCUS ELIASON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hailed by trumpet fanfares and cheering crowds,
President Reagan today savored London's pageantry-filled tribute to
his performance at the Moscow summit and a toast from Prime
Minister Margaret Thatcher as ``one of the greatest U.S.
presidents.''
   The president rode triumphantly through the streets of the
British capital near the end of a two-day stopover en route home
from Moscow. Londoners waved at his motorcade from along the River
Thames, from the tops of doubledecker buses and from boats in Hyde
Park's Serpentine Lake.
   Flanked by bewigged, scarlet-robed city fathers at Guildhall,
the 12th century seat of London's lord mayor, Reagan was welcomed
as a peacemaker and won a standing ovation for an emotional speech
on East-West relations, laced with jibes at the anti-nuclear lobby
and jokes about his age.
   Lord Mayor Sir Greville Spratt invoked the names of Ulysses S.
Grant and Woodrow Wilson, past U.S. presidents who have spoken at
Guildhall, and reached to Milton and Shakespeare for words to
describe his admiration for Reagan.
   Not to be outdone, Mrs. Thatcher quoted Tennyson's line,
``Strong in will, to strive, to seek, to find and not to yield.''
Turning to Reagan, she said:
   ``Thank you Mr. President, thank you for the summit, thank you
for your presidency, thank you for your testament of belief and God
bless America.''
   The only visible dissent came from actress Julie Christie and
eight other British show business personalities who picketed
Guildhall during Reagan's speech to protest U.S. involvement in
Nicaragua. They waved placards reading, ``U.S. Out of Central
America'' and distributed leaflets urging withdrawal of support for
the Contra rebels.
   ``The president saw a more open society in Red Square than here
in London,'' Miss Christie said, complaining that police kept the
demonstrators out of sight of the president's motorcade.
   Mrs. Thatcher hailed Reagan's summit talks as ``a tremendous
success.''
   Reagan returned the compliment, paying a special tribute to his
close friend and ally. The president noted that Mrs. Thatcher had
been among the first to suggest the West could ``do business'' with
Gorbachev.
   ``At this hour in history, prime minister, the entire world
salutes you and your gallant people and gallant nation,'' he said.
   Most of Reagan's 26-hour visit was ceremonial, including
parades, tea with Queen Elizabeth II, and dinner at Mrs. Thatcher's
residence at 10 Downing St.
   The prime minister said she was especially pleased with Reagan's
strong stance on human rights and his street encounters with
Muscovites because ``the Russian people would find it difficult now
to see the United States as a threat in the future.''
   Reagan told her he felt Gorbachev was ``vigorous and determined
to carry out'' his reform program, officials said.
   Reagan invited Mrs. Thatcher to Washington in November after the
presidential election to see him before he leaves office. She
immediately accepted, and White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater
said she presumably would also meet the president-elect.
   Unlike U.S. presidents, who are limited to two terms, British
prime ministers can serve for an indefinite period. Mrs. Thatcher,
having been elected three times, has indicated she wants to lead
her Conservative Party to a fourth victory.
   Mrs. Thatcher, a firm believer in nuclear deterrence, is wary of
sweeping arms cuts. A British official speaking on condition of
anonymity said Reagan told Mrs. Thatcher he would not be rushed
into an agreement to halve the superpowers' long-range nuclear
missiles.
   ``We don't have any reservations about the position of the
United States on this,'' the British official said.
   But when a reporter asked Reagan to comment on Gorbachev's claim
that arms negotiations were going too slowly, he replied: ``I'd
like to speed them up.''
   Shortly after their arrival Thursday, the President and Mrs.
Reagan drove to Buckingham Palace, where there were waves and
cheers from some 1,500 spectators as they drove through the ornate
black-and-gold gates of the 285-year-old palace. They were greeted
by Queen Elizabeth II.
   ``Nice to see you again. How are you Mr. President?'' said the
queen, entering the marble-columned main hall wearing a
sapphire-blue dress.
   A reporter asked Reagan if he was glad to be out of Moscow and
in London. Reagan replied diplomatically: ``Let me put it very
simply: I'm very happy to be in London.''
   Elizabeth received the Reagans alone, since her husband Prince
Philip was out of town. Her son and heir Prince Charles later
called on Mrs. Reagan at the ambassador's home.
   From the palace, Reagan drove to nearby Whitehall to inspect an
honor guard in the graceful, columned quadrangle of the Foreign
Office.
   Mrs. Thatcher, 62, whose nine years in office have paralleled
the Reagan tenure and forged close ties, received him with a warm
embrace of clasped elbows.
   The Welsh Guards in their scarlet tunics and tall black bearskin
hats played the American anthem and two Irving Berlin hits.
   Then Reagan and Mrs. Thatcher walked next door to 10 Downing St.
for talks, and Mrs. Reagan arrived later for a dinner of lobster
mousse, chicken with pate de fois gras and raspberries.
   After dinner Mrs. Thatcher and Reagan watched from a window as
horsemen and a band performed the ceremony of Beating Retreat, one
of the rituals leading up to the queen's birthday.
</TEXT>
