<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Summit-EasternEurope     06-03 0546</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Summit-Eastern Europe,0560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Eastern Bloc Praises Summit, But Criticizes U.S. Intransigence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Moscow summit eased tensions between
the United States and the Soviet Union, but U.S. intransigence
prevented progress on nuclear disarmament, news reports in
communist Eastern Europe said today.
   ``Some shady aspects of President Reagan's visit cannot
overshadow the fact that the summit turned into a significant
political event blazing the trail toward the 21st century,''
Otechestven Front, a Bulgarian daily said.
   Reagan and Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev met in Moscow from
Sunday to Thursday. It was their fourth meeting.
   An editorial in the Czechoslovak Communist Party newspaper Rude
Pravo said the Soviet-U.S. dialogue had reached ``a new higher
level after several `icy' years.'' But it added: The United States
has gone a considerable part of the way but does not want to go to
the end of this road.''
   Rude Pravo said, ``U.S. politicians cherish an illusion that
nuclear weapons `protect peace' ... and that is why they are
necessary for U.S. security. They also claim that space weapons
protect against nuclear weapons.''
   The daily criticized the United States for ``stubbornly trying
to gain unilateral advantages ... mainly in ... talks on a 50
percent reduction of strategic weapons and in such an important
question as the SDI program.''
   The Soviet Union also has called on the United States to scrap
the proposed Space Defense Initiative, or ``Star Wars.'''
   In Hungary, Magyar Nemzet, the daily of the Communist-led
Patriotic People's Front, commented: ``One can already feel the
beneficial effect of an international crisis-settling mechanism in
motion and ... a compromise-oriented approach on the part of both
superpowers seems to be taking shape.''
   The Hungarian trade union daily Nepszava said: ``Even if there
have been some less heartening moments at this summit, like
Reagan's meeting with dissenters, his meetings with the Soviet
people took place in an atmopshere that washed away the memory of
such moments.''
   It added, ``Naturally, we would have simply loved to read in the
joint communique a reference to `a great leap forward' toward the
next missile treaty ... We regret that instead of a leap only a
modest step has been taken.''
   The East German Communist Party newspaper Neues Deutschland said:
   ``It is with great satisfaction that all those who are committed
toward securing peace have also accepted the fact that now there is
a joint draft of a text for a treaty on reducing and limiting
strategic offensive weapons.''
   The Polish Communist Party daily Trybuna Ludu said: ``One cannot
shake the impression that the American side did not rid itself of
the deeply rooted prejudices and inhibitions.''
   ``All smiles, but what is inside it?'' said one Polish
journalist, who was asked for his reaction.
   ``We are satisfied,'' Stefan Staniszewski, a spokesman for the
Polish Foreign Ministry, said. ``We think that the summit was
successful. ... Not (only) as a summit but as a process which will
be continued in the future.''
   The summit shows the Soviet and U.S. governments see each other
as partners ``in a way in which they were not always able to see
themselves in the past,'' said Warsaw's Zycie Warszawy daily. ``It
warrants the presumption that the change of the U.S. presidency
should not alter the practice now adopted.''
  
</TEXT>
</DOC>
