<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Iran-Iraq     06-03 0323</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Iran-Iraq,0335</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iraq Says Iranian Plane Tried To Bomb President's Residence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S.-built Iranian plane today tried to
bomb Iraqi President Saddam Hussein's residence north of Baghdad,
but ground defenses chased the aircraft away, the Iraqi military
command announced.
   In a statement carried by the state-run Iraqi News Agency, the
military command said the F-4 Phantom fighter-bomber attempted to
attack the residence at 5:55 a.m.
   While maneuvering to evade the ground fire, the plane dropped
its load of explosives in an area close to the president's home in
the village of Ouja, the report said. No one was hurt in the
incident, it said.
   The agency, monitored in Nicosia, said Hussein chaired a meeting
of the country's ruling Revolutionary Command Council just after
the attempt.
   Iran and Iraq have been at war since September 1980. The two
sides have periodically bombed each other's cities in what has been
called ``the war of the cities,'' which began in 1984.
   The statement did not say if Saddam was at the residence, just
south of his hometown of Tikrit, during the attempt.
   It did not explain how the plane flew undetected all the way
from the border, 110 miles to the east. Tikrit is about 100 miles
northwest of Baghdad.
   But military analysts say, flying at ground level, an F-4 could
evade radar nets.
   On Thursday, Iran's revolutionary patriarch, Ayatollah Ruhollah
Khomeini, appointed the powerful parliament speaker, Hashemi
Rafsanjani, acting commander-in-chief. The post had been held by
Khomeini himself since the 1979 Islamic revolution.
   Addrssing a Moslem prayer congregation at Tehran University,
Rafsanjani said today that Iranians must take the war with Iraq
``more seriously,'' especially after recent defeats on the war
fronts.
   Iraqi troops have recaptured territories in two major offensives
in recent weeks. They retook the southern Faw peninsula in April
and dislodged the Iranians from Shalamchah, a startegic area east
of the southern city of Basra, last month.
</TEXT>
