<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SkyscraperFire     06-03 0338</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Skyscraper Fire,0347</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fire-Ravaged Skyscraper To Upgrade Fire Alarms</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The fire-ravaged First Interstate Bank tower
will get an upgraded fire alarm system and a $3-million sprinkler
system as part of a deal to reopen the 62-story downtown high-rise,
fire officials said.
   The skyscraper that is California's tallest building has been
closed since May 4, when a fire gutted 4{ floors, killing one man
and injuring about 40 other people.
   City fire officials announced Thursday that a partnership of the
Equitable Life Assurance Society and UCB Realty Corp. was agreeable
to upgrading its alarm system beyond what is required by law.
   The upgrades will include additional smoke detectors, fire doors
to enclose elevator vestibules and a third water pump for the
sprinkler and water standpipes.
   The improvements don't have to be completed before tenants
return as long as the existing system is working properly, said
city Fire Department Battalion Chief Kenneth Johnson.
   Tower owners have verbally agreed to the upgrading, although the
exact timetable and specifications are still being negotiated,
Johnson said.
   ``We are obviously going to work hand in hand with fire
officials. It's obviously in our best interests and the best
interests of our tenants,'' said Jerry Poppink, a spokesman for the
Equitable-UCB partnership, which owns the building.
   When the May 4 fire broke out, the building's sprinkler system
was nearly 90 percent complete but not operational. A building
spokesman said owners expect to restore the existing fire alarm
system and activate the sprinklers by next month.
   Sprinklers weren't mandatory for the high-rise because it was
built a year before a law requiring sprinklers took effect in 1974.
   Meanwhile, the Fire Department is continuing to investigate
whether to seek misdemeanor charges in the case in connection with
possible fire code violations, said Capt. John Scherrei.
   ``Was there a delayed alarm? Were the security people informed
of what to do? Were they notified to call the Fire Department? Were
there code violations?'' Scherrei said, listing the key questions
in the Fire Department's investigation.
</TEXT>
