<FILEID>AP-NR-06-03-88 1050EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d a PM-SchoolOrder     06-03 0274</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-School Order,0282</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Lifts Longstanding Supervision Of Oxford School System</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OXFORD, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge has ended almost two
decades of judicial supervision of the Oxford Municipal School
District, ruling that it now complies with desegregation
regulations.
   The district ``has become fully unitary in all aspects ... 19
years has certainly been more than a reasonable time to continue
under supervision of a federal court,'' U.S. District Judge William
C. Keady said in an an order filed here Thursday.
   The school system had been under court order since it was
ordered desegregated in 1969 following a complaint filed by blacks
in 1968.
   The district sought to have the order lifted and the issue was
argued in a two-day hearing in May.
   Blacks, represented by lawyer and local NAACP president Alvin
Chambliss, argued that the system was still discriminatory in
achievement grouping, employment, activities and discipline.
   The district has about 2,700 students in two elementary schools
and a junior and senior high school. About half are white and half
are black.
   Keady said the system has been supported by the community and
``white flight to a nearby academy has been minimal.''
   Under the court order, the district had been required to submit
lengthy reports on its activities to the court twice a year, said
Superintendent Bob McCord.
   McCord said the district was pleased more with what the ruling
said than its lifting of the paperwork.
   ``I think what this says is the school district has done more
than an adequate job of running a fair system,'' McCord said. ``I
think it speaks well of the system, the board and the community.''
</TEXT>
