<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Soviet-Party     06-03 0455</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Party,0470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Delegate Battle Raging As Moscow Party Meets</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opponents of Mikhail S. Gorbachev's reforms are
trying to block leading reformers from attending an upcoming
Communist Party conference, a key supporter of the Soviet leader
said today.
   Sociologist Tatyana Zaslavskaya, a main author of Gorbachev's
reform campaign, spoke about the party battles as Gorbachev
attended a meeting of the leaders of Moscow's Communist Party to
choose delegates for the conference.
   The official news agency Tass said Gorbachev addressed the
meeting, which was opened and closed by Politburo member and Moscow
party head Lev N. Zaikov.
   Details of the speeches or any other debate were not immediately
available. Tass said 319 delegates were chosen to represent the
almost 1 million Communists of Moscow at the conference.
   Zaslavskaya said at a news conference that ``the most pronounced
advocates of `perestroika' were not selected'' in initial elections
for party conference delegates. But Vitaly Korotich, editor of the
weekly Ogonyok, said this week the initial selections might be
revised at today's meeting.
   Tass said all 319 delegates chosen had ``recommended themselves
with concrete deeds as champions of perestroika,'' but did not
mention any names.
   Leading reformers such as Zaslavskaya, economist Abel
Aganbegyan, historian Yuri Afanaseyev, sociologist Fyodor Burlatsky
and economist Gavril Popov received the most votes from party
organizations at their places of work, but were stricken from the
list of potential candidates at the next level, equivalent to
precincts.
   ``Rank and file communists were somehow screened from the
process,'' Zaslavskaya told foreign and Soviet journalists at a
news conference sponsored by the Foreign Ministry.
   Other reformers have told Western reporters this week in Moscow
that they were trying to get their names resinstated at the city
party meeting.
   Similar developments have been reported in other Soviet cities
and regions, although the reports have not been as detailed as for
Moscow.
   Zaslavskaya said opposition to reform came from middle-level
party officials and managers who felt that their power was being
threatened.
   And she denied reports that Politburo member Yegor Ligachev was
leading the conservative movement and would be asked to resign.
   ``Of course the views of Ligachev are not as radical as those of
Gorbachev. But there are no grounds for thinking that he should be
dismissed,'' she said.
   The party conference, which opens on June 28, will be the 19th
of its kind in party history, but the first since 1941.
   The English-language service of Radio Moscow said the conference
of 5,000 delegates ``will discuss the process of perestroika and
ways of promoting it and will map out measures to further
democratize the party and society.''
   Perestroika refers to Gorbachev's efforts to reform the Soviet
economy and society.
</TEXT>
