<1ST_LINE>r a PM-UnitedChurch     06-03 0274</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-United Church,0282</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Committee Of United Church Of Christ Picks Cleveland For
Headquarters</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOROTHY GAST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A special committee of the 1.7 million-member
United Church of Christ announced today that it will recommend the
church move its national headquarters from New York to Cleveland.
   More than a year ago the executive council of the United Church
suggested that headquarters be moved to St. Louis, but changed its
recommendation and said only that the headquarters be moved out of
New York by 1991.
   The recommendation came a year after the church's 16th General
Synod delayed selection of a site and decided that a special
committee should resolve the issue.
   The decision won't become final until the church's next synod in
Fort Worth, Tex., in 1989, said public relations coordinator Martha
Gotwals.
   In a news release today, the 12-member committee said many
factors led to the choice of Cleveland, ``including the mission of
the church and its priorities, the continuing commitment to
ecumenical relationship, stewardship and cost factors, the strong
and diverse presence of the United Church of Christ, quality of
life issues and demographics.''
   The move could mean as many as 310 new jobs for Cleveland, and
some members of the New York staff are expected to transfer, Ms.
Gotwals said. Some of the church's leases in New York expire in
1989, she said.
   Ms. Gotwals said the church hasn't selected a specific location
for the new headquarters but that a site will be chosen before the
synod meets June 29, 1989.
   The church's executive council had considered Cleveland,
Chicago, Louisville, Ky., Indianapolis, New York and St. Louis.
</TEXT>
