<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Jackson 1stLd-Writethru a0462 06-03 0712</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jackson, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0462,710</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Calls for Outlawing AIDS Discrimination</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates in top 6 grafs with Jackson comments on AIDS, picking
up in 2nd graf pvs, The two</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson called today for immediate
federal action to stop discrimination against victims of the deadly
disease AIDS.
   Jackson, in a campaign statement distributed to reporters,
praised a draft report issued Thursday by the chairman of the White
House AIDS commission, and he said the government should quickly
heed the report's recommendation of strong federal
anti-discrimination protection.
   ``The Reagan-Bush administration must act now to stop
discrimination against people with AIDS in all areas, including
employment, housing and insurance,'' Jackson said.
   ``The president must take every available step, including an
executive order, to stop discrimination now, and the Congress must
legislate strong new laws to protect confidentiality and rights.''
   ``We cannot wait to commit more resources,'' he said. ``All
presidential candidates must agree that we need to spend what is
necessary to meet the challenge. We cannot wait to lead our nation
away from discrimination and fear-mongering. All leaders must speak
out now.''
   Jackson's comments were released just before he left for a
one-day foray into New Mexico and Montana today before returning to
California for the finale of his Democratic presidential campaign.
His campaign manager insisted: ``We're gaining.''
   The two small states and New Jersey join California in closing
out the Democratic primary season with elections on Tuesday.
   After spending much of Thursday talking to gang members and
urging local authorities to address the root problems of gang
violence, Jackson took his upbeat message to a housing project in
heavily Hispanic East Los Angeles, and then headed to a peace rally
in Los Angeles.
   Along the way, he picked up some words of praise _ but not an
official endorsement _ from Los Angeles Mayor Tom Bradley, who said
he would keep his voting preference in the privacy of the voting
booth.
   Jackson appeared relaxed and jovial despite the growing
inevitability that he will lose the nomination to front-runner
Michael Dukakis.
   Jackson's campaign manager, Gerald Austin, acknowledged Thursday
that Jackson faces an uphill battle to win Californoa's primary on
Tuesday, a fact reflected in polls showing Dukakis with an
overwhelming lead in the state.
   But Austin said he believes Jackson has ``some momentum now,''
adding: ``We're gaining.''
   ``But we've got a long ways to go,'' Austin admitted. ``We've
got our job cut our for us to turn our people out'' to vote.
   That goal has been reflected in Jackson's speeches here as he
tells supporters that their votes do count and that they should not
be swayed by reports that Dukakis all but has the nomination
wrapped up.
   His campaign has begun a $700,000 television advertising blitz
for the final days of the California campaign, which will include a
$150,000, half-hour broadcast at 8 p.m. on Monday, election eve.
   The show will be not only an appeal for votes but also a
``closing statement for the campaign,'' that will feature an upbeat
``celebration of the year'' of campaigning, Austin said.
   It will feature footage of Jackson's campaign, and an interview
with the candidate by a yet-unnamed celebrity, he said. Jackson
also will make a closing statement to viewers.
   Jackson and Bradley met privately at City Hall and then convened
a meeting with six gang members and various representatives of city
and county agencies.
   The meeting at City Hall was added to Jackson's schedule after
Dukakis canceled a scheduled debate in the Los Angeles suburb of
Torrance because his wife was having delicate spinal surgery today.
   Bradley said that Jackson's meeting with gang members that
morning in a Watts housing project _ where Jackson also had spent
the night _ provided ``one more item of impetus'' to city efforts
against gang problems.
   ``I will commit to bring together resources ... to deal with
what is an urgent problem in our society and our city,'' the mayor
said.
   Without officially endorsing his fellow black politican, Bradley
said Jackson had run a ``thoroughly remarkable campaign,'' and had
``energized millions of people'' across the country.
   ``I commend you for what you have done in showing what is
possible for this country,'' the mayor told Jackson.
</TEXT>
