<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PreachingChildren 1stLd-Writethru a0565 06-03 0463</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Preaching Children, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0565,0475</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Preaching Child Suspended Again On The Last Day of School</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 9 grafs to update with 5-year-old suspended on
last day of school for preaching again, picking up at the 7th graf
previous, beginning ``When Strode.''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MARION, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 5-year-old boy returned to school today
and resumed shouting Bible verses, drawing yet another suspension
on the last day of classes for preaching and refusing to enter
school.
   Matthew Strode was on campus at Eastfield Elementary School for
about 20 minutes before he was suspended, said Assistant Principal
Shirley Ramsey.
   The boy's brother, Duffey, 11, whose own suspension ran through
today, stood outside the school gate, joining Matthew in his
preaching.
   On Thursday, school officials had breathed a sigh of relief when
Matthew and his sister failed to return to school after their
latest 10-day suspension.
   ``It was good to have a nice quiet morning,'' David Ricketts,
superintendent of McDowell County Schools, said Thursday.
   Before today, Matthew and his sister, Pepper, 6, had been
suspended four times for defying school authorities and breaking
school rules by preaching, or in Pepper's case standing, outside
Eastfield Elementary after being asked to enter the building.
   Today's suspension, on the last day of school, was for one day.
   The children's father, David Strode, had said Thursday that he
saw no need to send his children to school because arrangements had
been made for them to take their final tests today.
   ``My father in heaven will take care of us,'' Strode said.
   When Strode took Duffey back to school May 27, there were two
altercations with protesting parents. The parents gave him with a
petition of 474 signatures calling for him to stop his children
from preaching.
   Duffey told reporters Thursday he expects to preach somewhere
during the summer. ``I just like preaching the daily word,'' he
said.
   ``The children have had enough preaching in two months to fill
their bellies for a lifetime,'' Strode said. ``The people who have
rejected it have sealed their doom to an everlasting fire.''
   School officials Thursday positioned sheriff's deputies at the
top of the driveway and instructed parents to drop off their
children and leave the campus immediately. Reporters also were
restricted to certain areas of the grounds.
   School officials have said the preaching is in reaction to
Duffey's suspension in April after a scuffle with some other
children.
   ``I think Mr. Strode had an ax to grind with the school
system,'' Ricketts said. ``He chose this way to do it.''
   Strode has said he is building a house on the west side of town,
so the children probably will go to a different school when classes
resume in August. The Strodes claim a constitutional right to
preach on school grounds.
</TEXT>
