<1ST_LINE>u i PM-SouthAfrica-Blast 4thLd-Writethru a0614 06-03 0585</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-South Africa-Blast, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0614,0598</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Explosion Outside South African Bank Kills Four</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS thruout to UPDATE with race of fourth body, definition
of limpet mine, purpose of next week's protest. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bomb hidden in a trash bin
exploded today outside a bank, killing four people and injuring 19,
police said. It was the deadliest bombing in South Africa in more
than a year.
   The lunch-hour blast went off at 1:30 p.m. outside a branch of
the Standard Bank in Roodepoort, a city bordering the west side of
Johannesburg. Three black men and a white woman were killed.
   The explosion followed four other bombings in the past two weeks
which authorities have blamed on the African National Congress
guerrilla movement.
   The ANC had no immediate comment on the bombing, but issued a
statement from its headquarters in Lusaka, Zambia, saying the month
of June ``must be a period of united and decisive popular
offensive'' against the government.
   The statement endorsed a three-day, anti-apartheid protest
scheduled to start on Monday, saying South Africa's economy ``must
grind to a halt'' on those days.
   A Roodepoort police spokesman, Maj. Tiene Halgryn, said eight
people were seriously injured in the explosion, including two
whites and six blacks. He said 11 other people suffered lesser
injuries.
   Police said most of the victims apparently were waiting at a
street corner for a traffic light to change when the explosion
occurred.
   The blast shattered at least a dozen windows in the bank, as
well as windows in nearby stores, and glass was strewn across a
nearby intersection in Roodepoort's central business district.
Police said the explosive device was a small limpet mine, which can
be attached to another object, and they conducted a search for
other bombs after cordoning off the area.
   A majority of the bombings blamed on the ANC have involved
limpet mines. Posters in government buildings around the country
show pictures of these devices and encourage members of the public
to be on the lookout for them.
   The death toll from today's explosion was the highest from a
bombing in South Africa since four white policemen were killed by a
car bomb outside a Johannesburg courthouse in May 1987.
   It was the fifth bombing reported in the Johannesburg-Pretoria
area in a nine-day span. Only one of the other blasts caused
injuries _ a mine placed in a flower box in Pretoria which exploded
May 26, injuring four white women.
   Police have blamed the blasts on the outlawed ANC, which has
waged a bombing and sabotage campaign since 1961 as part of its
efforts to topple the white-controlled government. The ANC has
neither confirmed nor denied responsibility for the recent bombings.
   Today's ANC statement said the group had distributed leaflets in
South Africa endorsing the nationwide protest planned Monday
through Wednesday by anti-apartheid labor unions, church groups and
other activists.
   The groups organizing the protest in South Africa are prohibited
by law from promoting a general strike, but it is expected that the
protest will take that form. Government officials and employers
have warned that workers who participate face dismissal or legal
action.
   The protest is intended to oppose the bannings of major
anti-apartheid organizations and other government moves against
opposition trade unions, newspapers and individual activists.
   Under apartheid, South Africa's 26 million blacks have no vote
in national affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and
maintain separate districts, schools and health services.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
