<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SouthKorea     06-03 0631</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-South Korea,0651</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>South Korea Proposes New Talks With North</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL SHIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government proposed new talks with
communist North Korea, and thousands of radical students declared
Friday they will march to the demilitarized zone in an effort to
force unification of the peninsula.
   Prime Minister Lee Hyun-jae wrote a letter to North Korea
proposing discussions, possibly this month, about the Olympic Games
scheduled for Seoul in September and other pending issues. It was
read on the radio Friday.
   Later in the day, 3,000 students from 18 schools held a campus
rally in Seoul in support of a march next Friday to the village of
Panmunjom to meet with North Korean students on national
reunification.
   ``Let's go and meet the northern people after driving out all
foreign forces!'' a speaker told the rally at Kyonghee University
in eastern Seoul. Students cheered and applauded.
   Officials said they would not permit the march because it was a
violation of the National Security Law and would be propaganda for
North Korea.
   Panmunjom is 35 miles north of Seoul, in the 2{-mile-wide
demilitarized zone that separates the Koreas, and is off-limits to
civilians.
   Lee Jong-nam, the prosecutor general, warned against
``left-leaning'' student activism and ordered a crackdown on
illegal campus activity favoring the North.
   At the rally, students shouted ``Yankee go home!'' and ``Let's
go to Panmunjom!''
   Giant posters showed students destroying U.S. flags and routing
U.S. troops. The United States has 42,000 soldiers in South Korea.
   Most campus rallies reported Friday were peaceful, but one at
Dankook University in Seoul turned violent when 50 students fought
police, hurling firebombs and rocks. Riot squads countered with
tear gas.
   Lee, the prime minister, wrote the letter proposing talks to
Premier Lee Gun Mo of North Korea. Chung Han-mo, the culture and
information minister, read it on radio.
   ``I respectfully propose talks between high-level authorities of
South and the North Korea to speedily dispel the mistrust that is
now standing in the way of peaceful unification,'' it said.
   South Korean officials said they told the North on Tuesday they
would deliver the letter to Panmunjom on Friday, but the North
Koreans refused to receive it.
   Korea has been divided since in 1945 and there has been a sharp
rise recently in public support for reunification, spurred by
President Roh Tae-woo's promise of full democracy.
   Radical students have demanded that North Korea be made co-host
of the Olympics and that the U.S. troops stationed in South Korea
withdraw. They claim the United States is reponsible for partition.
   South Koreans generally mistrust the North Korean regime of Kim
Il Sung, however, and support the U.S. military presence. They fear
another North Korean invasion like the one in 1950 that started a
three-year war.
   Lee's letter said the talks could be held either in Seoul or
Pyongyang, the North Korean capital, and should occur ``at an early
date, preferably within June.'' Delegations sides would consist of
about five officials each and be led by a Cabinet minister, he said.
   If held, the talks would would be the first contact since North
Korea suspended dialogue in the spring of 1986, citing joint
U.S.-South Korea military exercises.
   Among topics Lee suggested were North Korean participation in
the Olympics, exchanges of people and reactivating channels of
dialogue suspended in 1986.
   North Korea has promoted its own proposal for political talks,
to be attended by 50 politicians from each side. South Korea has
called that an ``unrealistic political offensive.''
   Opposition leaders have urged Roh's government to make
concessions as a means of persuading the North Koreans to
participate in the Olympics.
   North Korea has said it will boycott the games unless it is
co-host. The International Olympic Committee and South Korea
rejected the demand.
</TEXT>
