<HEAD>County Won't Send Mall Killer's Mom To Mental Illness Convention</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Local officials are balking at sending a
woman whose daughter killed three people and wounded seven others
in a shooting rampage to a national convention for families of
mentally ill people.
   The decision by the Delaware County Office of Mental Health has
upset the local chapter of the Alliance for the Mentally Ill, which
wants $800 to send Ruth Seegrist to its national gathering in
Boulder, Colo., over the July Fourth weekend. The alliance is a
self-help group for families of the mentally ill.
   Mrs. Seegrist's daughter, Sylvia, was convicted in the October
1985 shootings at Springfield Mall in this Philadelphia suburb.
Sylvia Seegrist has a history of mental illness.
   County Mental Health Director Diane Bricker said Thursday the
expenditure would be difficult to justify because she believes Mrs.
Seegrist could afford to pay her own way.
   Mrs. Seegrist, or anyone else the alliance would want to send,
would have to pass a screening for financial need before the county
would spend the money, Ms. Bricker said.
   ``I have already told my own staff they can't go because the
system is too impoverished,'' Ms. Bricker said. ``I could name you
a hundred people who would like to go to that conference, many of
whom are willing to pay their own way.''
   County AMI President Joy McCoy claims the county is
discriminating against Mrs. Seegrist. She said Mrs. Seegrist's
finances shouldn't be a factor in the decision.
   Ms. McCoy said Philadelphia, Montgomery and Chester counties are
sending four AMI representatives each to the conference.
