<HEAD>Woman Charged in Child Abuse Death Reportedly Has Brain Damage</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The longtime lover of a lawyer charged with
beating to death the couple's 6-year-old ward has suffered brain
damage from repeated beatings, New York Newsday reported Friday.
   Prosecutors building a murder case against Joel Steinberg said
they doubt they will call Hedda Nussbaum, who lived with Steinberg
for 17 years, to testify against him, even though she is willing,
the newspaper said.
   They are concerned that even if she is capable of appearing in
court, she she would fall under Steinberg's influence again, the
newspaper quoted law enforcement sources as saying.
   ``It's not clear how she will react when she sees Steinberg
again,'' one source said. ``She believed he had supernatural
powers.''
   Prosecutors interviewed Ms. Nussbaum last month at a private
psychiatric hospital.
   Ms. Nussbaum, who also was arrested but not indicted in the
death of Lisa Steinberg, has undergone plastic surgery to repair
the visible damage of repeated beatings.
   ``She did suffer brain damage. So far, it is limited to her
being unable to come up with some words when she's talking. She
forgets certain words or names,'' a source close to the case told
the newspaper.
   Her attorney, Barry Scheck, said recently that his client is
willing to testify against Steinberg, but refused to detail what
she would say. Scheck declined comment Thursday.
   Steinberg's attorney, Ira D. London, said he may call Ms.
Nussbaum as a witness if she isn't called for the prosecution.
   Sources also told the newspaper that Ms. Nussbaum, 45, probably
will not be prosecuted for Lisa's death.
   Ms. Nussbaum and Steinberg were arrested Nov. 2 after police
found Lisa unconscious in their Greenwich Village apartment. The
child died a short time later of a head injury.
   A grand jury indicted Steinberg, 47, on charges of second-degree
murder, first-degree manslaughter and two counts of endangering the
welfare of a minor, along with drug and weapon charges. He is in
jail at Rikers Island.
