<1ST_LINE>r a AM-NoDancing     06-03 0320</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-No Dancing,0329</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Can't Trip The Light Fantastic In Nicholasville</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICHOLASVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fingers are snapping but feet are
staying firmly planted on the ground in Nicholasville, where police
are enforcing an ordinance that bans public dancing without a
license.
   ``I stood there and cried,'' said Boots Nelson, a patron at the
Next Door Saloon who wasn't allowed to dance when a band played her
favorite song. ``The band was playing their hearts out, but people
were afraid to tap their feet for fear the law would come in.''
   Handmade ``No Dancing'' signs were posted in the bar after
police last week cited owner Billy Davis for violating the
ordinance. Officials said it was apparently the first time the
ordinance had been enforced.
   ``This is not a point where the city is trying to stop
dancing,'' Police Chief Carl Perkins said Friday. ``We're living in
the '80s like everyone else does.''
   But officials say the ordinance applies to dancing everywhere,
including parking lots and playgrounds.
   Last weekend, some square dancers who wanted to kick up their
heels to a band playing in a restaurant parking lot were asked to
refrain.
   And three clog dancers who appeared at a city commission budget
meeting Thursday to ask permission to clog next weekend were told
they would have to wait for a meeting of the full commission later
this month.
   Mayor James Mason told the cloggers the commission was ``boxed
in'' by the ordinance. ``I think it is sad, but we cannot vote on
it,'' he said.
   Commissioner Joe Daugherty said he thought the law was unfair
and that the commission would vote to change it.
   Perkins said police have begun enforcing the law in the city of
10,000 people because bars that have live bands may not meet city
and state fire codes. He said the intent of the ordinance was
safety.
   Davis is to appear in court June 13.
</TEXT>
