<1ST_LINE>u a PM-SchoolShootings 2ndLd-Writethru a0623 06-03 0704</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-School Shootings, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0623,0721</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Survivor Talked Dann Into Giving Up One Pistol, She Shot Him With
Another</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede CHICAGO</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 14 grafs to UPDATE with victim's story from news
conference today; picks up 8th graf pvs, ``Ms. Dann, 30 ... ''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRENDA C. COLEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HIGHLAND PARK, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 20-year-old man wounded when a
babysitter went on a shooting spree said today he talked the woman
into giving up one of her guns after she broke into his home, but
then she shot him in the chest with another pistol.
   Philip Andrew described for the first time what happened in his
parents Winnetka home when Laurie Dann burst in two weeks ago after
she killed one child and wounded five others at a nearby elementary
school.
   Andrew spoke at a news conference at Highland Park Hospital,
where he has been a patient since the shooting on May 20.
   ``This was a sick individual. You can't make sense of it _
that's how you make sense of it. The rest of the people who come
into my house aren't going to be shooting at me. It was a freak
incident,'' Andrew said.
   When Ms. Dann burst into the Andrew home the morning of May 20
after opening fire at Hubbard Woods Elementary School, she told
Andrew and his mother she had been sexually assaulted and had shot
her assailant.
   Andrew said he and his mother tried to calm Ms. Dann and
encouraged her to call the police. He said his mother left to warn
her daughters to stay out of the house and that he persuaded Ms.
Dann to give him one of her two pistols.
   But, he said, she clung to the other, a .32-caliber. She grew
fearful that police were approaching, suddenly turned and shot him
in the chest, Andrew said. He staggered out of the house and
collapsed in the driveway.
   Later, as police surrounded his family's house in the posh
suburb, Ms. Dann killed herself.
   Although Andrew and another of Ms. Dann's shooting victims
remain hospitalized, a third victim, Peter Munro, 8, was released
Thursday night from Highland Park Hospital, said spokeswoman Sue
Masaraccia.
   Police are continuing to investigate Ms. Dann's background and
say that an experimental drug she was using can cause suicidal
depression and is not approved for sale in this country.
   Ms. Dann obtained clomipramine, also known as Anafrail, from a
Canadian pharmacy using a Chicago psychiatrist's prescription,
Winnetka Police Lt. Joe Sumner said Thursday.
   Blood tests taken in an autopsy on Ms. Dann showed traces of the
drug, used to control some behavior problems.
   High dosages of Anafrail can cause suicidal depression in some
patients, said Dr. Robert DeVito, a pyschiatrist at Loyola
University Medical Center in suburban Maywood.
   However, DeVito said that he didn't think the drug caused Ms.
Dann's behavior. ``It is not a homicidal drug by any means,'' he
said.
   Ms. Dann, 30, was seeing Dr. John Griest, a psychiatrist in
Madison, Wis., where she once lived. He is authorized to dispense
Anafrail on a trial basis, but police said he only prescribed
lithium carbonate, a drug commonly used for treatment of
manic-depressive disorders, for Ms. Dann.
   Griest cannot comment on Ms. Dann's case due to doctor-patient
confidentiality, said Lauren Cnare, a spokesman at the Madison
clinic. ``We are involved in clinical trials of Anafrail,'' Ms.
Cnare said.
   Winnetka police apparently know the psychiatrist who supplied
Ms. Dann with Anafrail, but have not yet interviewed him, the
Chicago Tribune reported today.
   Officials at the Illinois Department of Professional Regulation
also were investigating how she got the drug, spokesman Steve
Waters said.
   Ciba-Geigy Corp., which makes Anafrail, has been selling the
drug outside the United States for the treatment of people
suffering from ``obsessive-compulsive disorders,'' company
spokeswoman Gloria Martini said.
   The drug also is used to check ``repetitive thoughts of random
violence,'' she said.
   Ms. Dann exhibited various symptoms of the disorder. Residents
of an apartment complex in Madison where she once lived said she
often rode the elevator for hours.
   Tests of the drug are being conducted in the United States with
government approval on 1,300 adult patients at 21 sites around the
country.
</TEXT>
