<FILEID>AP-NR-06-03-88 1257EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Malaysia-Detainees     06-03 0302</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Malaysia-Detainees,0310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Opposition Legislators Freed In Malaysia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARI S. MANIAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government on Friday freed
seven people, including two opposition members of Parliament, who
were held in prison without trial for seven months.
   The freed legislators were Tan Seng Giaw, vice chairman of the
opposition Democratic Action Party and Vethamuthu David, a party
Central Committee member, party member Madhavan Nair told The
Associated Press.
   Nair, who is a state Assembly member, identified the other five
as: Suhaimi Said, legal adviser to the opposition Pan-Malaysian
Islamic Party; Christian church worker Cecilia Ng; Lim Chin Chin, a
lecturer at a local university; and two Chinese educators, Lim Fong
Seng and Seng Maw Yu.
   The seven were among 109 people detained in October and November
of 1987 under the federal Internal Security Act, which allows the
government to imprison people indefinitely without bringing them to
trial.
   The 109 were taken into custody after Prime Minister Mahathir
Mohamad accused them of raising issues that could stir racial
tensions.
   The government cited the same reason for closing the
English-language Star daily newspaper, the Chinese-language Sin
Chew Jit Poh daily, and the Malay biweekly Watan in October 1987.
They were allowed to reopen earlier this year.
   The prime minister said at the time that he wanted to prevent
riots between Malays and Chinese such as those in 1969 that left
500 people dead. About 50 percent of the population is Malay and 30
percent Chinese.
   The government began releasing some of the 109 detainees on Nov.
20, 1987. No reason was given for the latest release, which left
about 30 of the original 109 still in prison.
   During past releases, the government has said the detainees it
was freeing no longer posed a threat to national security.
</TEXT>
