<FILEID>AP-NR-06-03-88 1332EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-YWCA-Men     06-03 0523</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-YWCA-Men,0539</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Decision To Hire Male YWCA Director Sparks National Debate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TACOMA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A decision by the YWCA's Tacoma chapter to
hire a male executive director in defiance of national organization
rules has set off debate over the future of the 133-year-old
organization.
   Last month, Alan Tiger, 36, of Eugene, Ore., was hired as
executive director. By definition, an executive director must be a
full voting member of the YWCA, but the organization's constitution
allows men only as associate, non-voting members.
   Tiger's hiring could result in the national organization
terminating its affiliation with the Tacoma chapter. And the
decision will set a precedent for the YWCA, said Marilynne Keyser,
a YWCA national board member.
   On Thursday, she and national Executive Director Gwendolyn
Calvert Baker fly to Tacoma to meet with chapter leaders to discuss
the issue.
   ``I think _ this is pure conjecture _ that the national has
simply lost touch with what's happening on a local level,'' said
Pene Modahl, president of the Tacoma board of directors.
   ``We believe here in Tacoma that men and women can work
together. We don't believe we're going to lose our focus by hiring
the best possible candidate, who happened to be a man,'' she said.
   Tiger said the Tacoma YWCA will remain committed to the battered
women's shelter, the job training programs and the other services
aimed primarily at women.
   ``We have to ask ourselves, when in the women's movement do we
stop talking about men and women and start to talk about
humanity,'' he said.
   However, some members say accepting men as full members may
shift the YWCA's focus away from women's concerns.
   ``We are working to reverse previous years of discrimination. We
are an organization to promote women, and provide a place for women
to learn to be powerful,'' said Barbara Dixon, executive secretary
of the Salem, Ore., YWCA. In that chapter, five of 35 board members
quit in May when the board denied membership to a man.
   While the YMCA focuses on health and fitness and allows both
sexes to join, the YWCA plays largely a social service and
political role, Ms. Keyser said.
   She said the Tacoma chapter's action is sure to be a subject of
debate at the national YWCA convention later this month in Chicago.
   ``We believe there is a need to reaffirm the commitment as an
autonomous women's organization,'' Ms. Keyser said.
   Some members say many of the 400 local chapters are under
pressure to allow men to join, partly because of the recent
inclusion of women in formerly all-male clubs such as Rotary.
   ``To me, it's a natural evolution. It's come to a point in the
1980s that we have to lay aside this us-against-them thing and
start to work together,'' said Gay Littleton, executive director of
the Ogden, Utah, YWCA.
   A few months ago, the Ogden chapter became the first in the
country to be disaffiliated from the national group because it
allowed men to join. Disaffiliation means the Ogden group may be
barred from using the YWCA name or symbol. No final decision on
that issue has been made, said Ms. Littleton.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
