<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PhillyPolice 1stLd-Writethru a0641 06-03 0415</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Philly Police, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0641,0423</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Goode Names Williams New Philadelphia Police Commissioner</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs with comment, quotes, picking up 4th graf
pvs, ``Tucker, 47 xxx; ADDS two grafs at end with more</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LEE LINDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor W. Wilson Goode today named deputy
commissioner Willie Williams as the city's new police commissioner,
putting him in charge of a department still recovering from
corruption probes and a confrontation with a radical group.
   Williams, the first black to lead the 6,700 member department,
will replace Kevin Tucker, who resigned last week after 2{ years on
the job.
   Williams, 44, has been a police officer for 24 years, starting
his career as a Fairmount Park guard. Goode said he chose Williams
from among seven candidates suggested by Tucker.
   ``The tenure of Kevin Tucker has represented the turning-around
of this department and the appointment of Willie Williams
represents a continuation of the reform of the department,'' Goode
said at a noon news conference.
   There has been speculation that because of budget cuts, there
would be some layoffs in the police department, and Williams told
reporters ``the patrol force on the street will not be cut. That is
our first priority.''
   Both Williams and Goode said the major task facing the police
department is the fight against drugs.
   Tucker, 47, quit May 26, effective June 10, citing a need to
spend more time with his family. Tucker is former head of the local
Secret Service office.
   Tucker took over a morale-shattered department reeling from
extortion convictions against 34 officers or former officers,
including a deputy commissioner.
   Tucker succeeded Gregore Sambor, who resigned after a fatal May
1985 confrontation between police and MOVE in which the radical
group's building was bombed by a police helicopter. The bombing
sparked a fire that destroyed dozens of houses.
   Goode has praised Tucker's work as commissioner, saying he
``turned the department around and it is now going in the right
direction. The job of the next police commissioner will be made
much easier by the job he has done.''
   Goode, asked if appointing a black police commissioner would
help the image of police in the black community, responded that
``race was never a factor in this appointment. ... I only sought to
find the very best person.''
   He said, however, that Williams will be able to turn around
negative views of police in the black community, which comprises
about 40 percent of the city's population.
</TEXT>
