<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-Demjanjuk     06-03 0266</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Demjanjuk,0274</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Demjanjuk Charged In Italy With War Crimes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John Demjanjuk, who was sentenced to death by
an Israeli court for being a brutal Nazi guard, has been charged by
an Italian court with committing war crimes in Italy, an Israeli
attorney said.
   The retired Ohio autoworker was advised of the Italian charge in
an official letter sent to him at his maximum security jail cell in
the Ayalon Prison near Tel Aviv, attorney Doron Beckerman said in
an interview Thursday.
   The letter said Demjanjuk had been charged with ``voluntary and
continuous aggravated homicide'' in Trieste, Italy, during the
years 1943-1945. It was signed by the Criminal Examination Office
in Trieste.
   On April 18, a three-judge panel convicted Demjanjuk, 68, of
being the brutal Nazi guard ``Ivan the Terrible,'' who operated gas
chambers that killed 850,000 Jews at the Treblinka death camp in
Nazi-occupied Poland in 1942 and 1943. He was sentenced to hang.
   The Ukrainian-born Demjanjuk, a retired autoworker who lived in
the Cleveland suburb of Seven Hills before being extradited to
Israel, claims he is an innocent victim of mistaken identity. He
said he will appeal the conviction.
   During the yearlong trial in Israel, testimony was submitted
that Demjanjuk was posted to Trieste after Treblinka was closed
down in August 1943.
   The Israeli weekly Haolom Haze published a copy of the Italian
letter and said Demjanjuk turned it over to his Israeli attorney,
Yoram Sheftel.
   Beckerman, Sheftel's law partner, said Sheftel could not be
reached because he was out of the country.
   A prosecutor in Trieste declined to comment Friday.
</TEXT>
