<2ND_LINE>PM-Duarte, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0626,530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Salvadoran President Gets Visit from Bush</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: TOPS with 3 grafs to give additional details of Bush's visit;
picks up 4th graf pvs, Duarte, one</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PHYLLIS MESSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush spent a half-hour
today with Salvadoran President Jose Napoleon Duarte, who is
hospitalized at Walter Reed Army Medical Center with stomach and
liver cancer.
   Bush ``wished Duarte well and expressed his gratitude for what
Duarte's done for democracy,'' a spokeswoman for the vice
president, Kristin Taylor, said.
   Bush arrived at Andrews Air Force Base late this morning,
following a week's stay at his Maine vacation home, and then
immediately boarded a helicopter for the short trip to Walter Reed.
   Duarte, one of the United States' staunchest allies in Latin
America, remains in guarded but stable condition as his doctors
review test results to determine how best to treat the stomach and
liver cancer, the hospital said in a statement today.
   The hospital said that doctors at Walter Reed and Duarte's
personal physician would look at all the test results and ``present
treatment alternatives to the president and his family.'' The
hospital added that ``no decision on treatment is expected or
required today'' and did not specify when a decision would be made.
   Duarte, 62, entered Walter Reed on Tuesday night. He visited a
special clinic on Thursday for magnetic resonance imaging tests to
determine the extent of his cancer.
   On his return to Walter Reed on Thursday, he spoke briefly with
reporters, telling them, ``I feel well.''
   He later added, ``One thing is assured. I'll fight it out
because I believe in God.''
   In a statement Thursday, Walter Reed said Duarte has a malignant
gastric ulcer and that preliminary tests showed ``some liver
involvement,'' but that no further spread of the cancer had been
detected.
   Duarte's personal physician, Benjamin Interiano, who is from El
Salvador, said Thursday that he is optimistic for Duarte even
though ``it's a very difficult situation, medically speaking. If a
person has decided to fight, I have all hopes.''
   Interiano said he did not know how long the Salvadoran president
would remain hospitalized in the United States. But he described
Duarte's condition as ``very guarded.''
   The magnetic resonance imaging tests, or MRI, were done at the
offices of Magnetic Imaging of Washington. The company uses MRI to
take three-dimensional pictures of soft tissue. The tests can
detect differences in the magnetic fields of tissues that cannot be
seen by X-rays and is useful in detecting cancers.
   Duarte spoke in Spanish and English, with his Spanish remarks
interpreted by Ambassador Ernesto Rivas-Gallont.
   One comment he made in Spanish but did not repeat in English
was: ``I leave a message for my country that they should never lose
the liberty they have now.''
   Duarte's son, Alejandro Duarte, said he did not have any
immediate concerns about the political stability of El Salvador
during his father's absence.
   ``The government is a team,'' he said in remarks translated into
English by the ambassador. ``A team is together, united. Obviously,
fundamental policies won't change.
   ``We still don't know how long the president will be away.
Therefore, we cannot say how his absence will affect the
(long-term) conduct of government.''
   Duarte is in the final year of his five-year term.
</TEXT>
