<HEAD>Little League Player Threatened with Arrest</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to correct spelling of Allingtown</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WEST HAVEN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 12-year-old girl staged a second
sit-down strike to protest Little League orders that she move up to
a higher league, but tearfully gave up her spot on the pitcher's
mound when threatened with arrest.
   As 100 spectators watched, Felicia Lewis, wearing the uniform of
the Allingtown Volunteer Fire Department, was led away by her
parents after local police warned she would be charged with
disturbing the peace if she didn't let the all-girls softball game
resume.
   West Haven Little League officials reiterated Tuesday that
Felicia must move up because she is too old and talented for the
Allingtown Volunteer Fire Department team, where she was assigned
in April at the beginning of her rookie season.
   Felicia, who forced cancellation of a game last week with a
similar protest, says she wants to stay on the Allingtown team,
which is made up of 8- to 12-year-olds, because she has made
friends.
   ``I like my team. I want to play,'' she said Thursday.
   Felicia arrived at the Morse Park ballfield shortly before
Allingtown's game against Brian Place and was greeted by television
crews and a large crowd of parents and children.
   She went to the outfield to shag a few flies with teammates
before the game and went out to the mound and sat down soon after
the game began.
   League officials were prepared for the protest and submitted a
written complaint to police, who ordered Felicia off the field, and
the game was resumed.
   Felicia was drafted by a team in a higher league because she was
such a good player, and under league rules she has to go to that
team.
   The dispute has pitted parents who say the league has gotten too
competitive against parents who say a violation of the rules will
ruin the league for everyone else.
   ``I think you have to take a stand sometime in your life. For
Felicia, this is it. This kid needs all the support she can get,''
said Jean Gollinger, who carried a sign reading, ``I Support
Felicia.''
   Ronald Lewis, Felicia's father, said his daughter has decided to
continue protesting at the four remaining games of the season and
he is considering taking legal action.
</TEXT>
