<FILEID>AP-NR-06-03-88 1407EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SriLanka     06-03 0502</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sri Lanka,0517</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Party Wins Elections; Extremists Kill 2 Candidates</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Junius R. Jayewardene's
party was declared the winner Friday in two regional elections
marred by violence, and Sinhalese extremists killed two candidates
in another election scheduled next week.
   India moved 2,000 more troops to Mullaitivu, a port town in
northeastern Sri Lanka, in a 12-day-old campaign against Tamil
rebel hideouts, military officials said.
   The elections were required under an agreement that India and
Sri Lanka signed last July in hopes of ending a Tamil separatist
war that has taken about 8,000 lives since 1983. India has more
than 50,000 soldiers in Sri Lanka to enforce the pact, which the
largest rebel group rejected.
   Extremists in the Sinhalese ethnic majority say the agreement
makes too many concessions to Tamils and have vowed to kill anyone
who supports it.
   Jayewardene's United National Party won 87 of the 158 seats at
stake in elections Thursday for district councils in western and
central regions, the government Election Department said.
   A three-party Communist alliance won 60 seats, the Moslem
Congress nine and the Liberal Party two, it reported.
   Sinhalese extremists killed two candidates for the the district
council election scheduled for next Thursdy in the southern region
of this tea and spice island off the tip of India.
   One represented Jayewardene's party and the other was from the
Communist alliance, police said.
   Authorities also blamed Sinhalese radicals for at least 75 cases
of arson in the southern province, including five fires set at
government buildings and around telephone and electricity poles.
   At least six people were reported killed Wednesday and Thursday,
among them two policemen and an election worker.
   The attacks are blamed on the People's Liberation Front, a
radical Sinhalese group that has gained strength in southern Sri
Lanka in the past several years.
   Also Friday, the United News of India said the Indian government
reported 18 Indian soldiers killed last Sunday when Tamil fighters
detonated a mine under their truck.
   It said the report of the bombing, one of the deadliest attacks
on Indian forces, apparently was withheld because of a three-day
visit to Sri Lanka by Defense Minister K.C. Pant that ended Tuesday.
   Nine district councils are to be created under the peace
agreement, and the government party won elections for four held in
April. No election dates have been set in the Tamil-dominated north
and east because of the insurgency.
   Tamils, most of whom are Hindus, make up 18 percent of Sri
Lanka's 16 million people and claim discrimination by the
predominantly Buddhist Sinhalese majority.
   India became involved in trying to end the war because 60
million Tamils live in its southern Tamil Nadu state.
   The main target of the Indian military campaign is the
Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam, which is the largest rebel group
and has not put down its arms.
   At least 480 Indian soldiers have been killed since their
peacekeeping mission began July 30, 1987.
</TEXT>
