<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Dukakis 2ndLd-Writethru a0576 06-03 0599</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0576,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Democratic Front-Runner Dukakis' Wife Kitty Undergoes Surgery</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with surgery completed, subbing 2 grafs for pvs lead</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Surgeons operated for more than five hours today
to relieve dangerous pressure on the spinal column of Kitty
Dukakis, wife of Democratic presidential front-runner Michael
Dukakis who canceled campaign plans to be with her at the hospital.
   ``Preliminary indications look good,'' hospital spokesman Martin
Bander said after the surgery.
   Dukakis spent the night on an extra bed in his wife's room,
according to spokesman James Dorsey. He spent about 15 minutes this
morning talking to the chief surgeon, Dr. Nicholas T. Zervas,
before the operation began at 7:30 a.m. EDT.
   ``The governor is going to spend the morning at the hospital
working,'' said Dorsey. ``He is going to await the results.''
   Dukakis flew from San Francisco to Boston on Thursday to be with
Mrs. Dukakis. Doctors intended to remove two herniated discs
pressing against her spinal cord in her neck. They expected the
operation to last from two to five hours.
   ``Kitty's feeling fine,'' Dukakis told reporters after the
late-night visit. ``She's in good spirits, looks good and is
anxious to get this over.''
   The Massachusetts governor said he would resume campaigning this
weekend ``if everything is OK.''
   Dukakis said his wife was satisfied the diagnosis explained the
puzzling health problems she had been experiencing. Mrs. Dukakis
had complained of numbness and coldness in her fingers and hands,
and pain in her neck, for about a month.
   ``When she went out walking, she would kind of stumble a little
bit,'' he said. ``So in a sense it's a relief to know this is what
it is.
   ``She started by having this feeling of numbness in her
fingertips. It started spreading to her feet, and now it's getting
to her legs. It's obvious these herniated discs are starting to
press on whatever it is they're pressing on,'' he said.
   Dukakis canceled a planned debate with Democratic rival Jesse
Jackson _ which was to have been the last of the primary campaign _
and flew home little more than 12 hours after arriving on the West
Coast.
   Doctors had decided Thursday to go ahead with immediate surgery
after analyzing results of tests performed on Mrs. Dukakis.
   ``My impression is that when you have anything that involves the
spinal cord, the faster you move on it the better,'' Dukakis said
in an interview.
   Led by Zervas, chief of neurosurgery at the hospital, surgeons
planned to take a bone graft from Mrs. Dukakis's hip and use it to
replace a portion of the discs.
   ``The plan is to remove the discs compressing on the spinal
cord. The bone graft taken from the hip will be split and fused
into the vertabrae to replace the two areas from which the discs
will be removed,'' hospital spokesman Martin Bander said.
   Mrs. Dukakis underwent sophisticated tests, including magnetic
resonance imaging, while in Los Angeles last Saturday, and had more
tests upon returning to Massachusetts on Wednesday.
   Zervas said surgery was scheduled quickly ``because of the
worsening of the condition.''
   Dukakis left San Francisco after attending only one public
event, a talk with grade-school students about the environment on a
city beach.
   He said he regretted having to cancel campaign appearances but
``this is obviously the most important thing.'' He said he hoped to
resume campaigning over the weekend, if the surgery goes well.
   Both Dukakis and Jackson were campaigning toward the June 7
primaries in California, New Jersey, Montana and New Mexico.
</TEXT>
