<1ST_LINE>u i AM-NaziBar Bjt   06-03 0390</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nazi Bar, Bjt,0401</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Nazi Bar' Stirs Controversy</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOLLY YONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A middle-aged woman spit and cursed at
a drawing of officers who served Germany's Third Reich. A European
man threw a beer mug to the floor, apparently enraged by the
decorations of Bangkok's ``Nazi Bar.''
   Trendy Thais are frequenting the new nightspot, but foreigners
have objected to the caricatures of Adolf Hitler, cartoons of
Italian Fascist leader Benito Mussolini, photos of storm troopers
and waiters with ``swastika'' armbands.
   ``For us, the bar is purely business-oriented, apolitical,
artistic and entertaining,'' said manager Aor Saratuk.
   He said he and business partners focused on the Nazi theme
because its ``powerful, catchy name and emotive appeal'' would draw
young patrons in a downtown area dotted with competitive pubs with
names such as ``Express'' or ``Studio West.''
   They flock to the bar to hear live music, seemingly oblivious to
objections that it glamorizes the brutal Nazi regime.
   Aor said there have been no complaints by Thais, but in recent
weeks several foreigners have criticized the bar in letters to the
English-language Bangkok Post newspaper.
   ``Simply stated, opening a bar that glamorizes any aspect of
Adolf Hitler or the Nazi regime is an offense against our common
humanity. If we can easily forget or trivialize the Holocaust, then
we are saying that human life is not sacred,'' one letter said.
   Thongbai Thongpao, Thailand's leading human rights lawyer, said
the management may not knowingly endorse Nazi Germany, but the
bar's name has had the ``unfortunate effect of hurting other
people's feelings because of memories evoked by the Holocaust
atrocity.''
   About 6 million European Jews were systematically exterminated
by Nazi Germany during the Holocaust.
   But not everyone finds the bar offensive.
   Jean-Paul Lorbach, a tourist from Brussels, Belgium, said,
``It's very pleasing here, just like any other bar. It's definitely
not Nazism.''
   A former Thai policeman, 25-year-old Boonserm Jitarasomkuan,
called Hitler a ``notorious criminal'' but advised the management
to keep the name because he said it was ``harmless.''
   Aor called some of the bar's decor ``deliberate distortions'' of
Nazism. A 10-foot portrait of Hitler reviewing troops in a trench
coat shows his moustache turned upwards and elongated _ not the way
he wore it. One color drawing depicted him in a straightjacket, and
was captioned: ``Captured German Painting.''
</TEXT>
