<1ST_LINE>u a PM-Steiger     06-03 0482</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Steiger,0497</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Congressman And Mecham Aide Is Sentenced</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY LOPEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former congressman Sam Steiger, convicted
of pressuring a parole board member while working for then-Gov.
Evan Mecham, was sentenced today to four years' probation.
   Judge Ronald Reinstein of Maricopa County Superior Court also
fined Steiger $5,480 and sentenced him to perform 700 hours of
community service work. He suggested that Steiger, well known for
criticizing lawyers, consider doing volunteer work for the Arizona
Bar Association.
   Reinstein's sentencing options ranged from probation to five
years in prison.
   Assistant Attorney General Michael Cudahy had urged that the
judge consider giving Steiger jail time to impress upon him the
seriousness of the crime and to deter others. But a probation
officer recommended no jail and the judge agreed, saying he did not
think it would do Steiger any good.
   And Cudahy said after the sentencing he had no problem with
Steiger being put on probation.
   Steiger repeated his contention that he was singled out for
prosecution because he had been critical of Attorney General Bob
Corbin. He said he was not remorseful even though, ``prejudice and
precedence would dictate that I should be remorseful.''
   Reinstein said he was impressed by the outpouring of more than
170 letters on Steiger's behalf and did not believe that Steiger
was motivated by political or personal gain.
   But he said Steiger ``clearly broke the law,'' abused his power
and was trying to ``deflect your obvious wrong in this case'' on
others. He told Steiger one of the main reasons for the conviction
was that, ``Frankly, Mr. Steiger, you came off as a bully.''
   Steiger, 59, was convicted April 7 of theft by extortion for
threatening Board of Pardons and Paroles member Ron Johnson over a
personnel vote.
   Steiger claimed it was simply hardball politics, but Cudahy said
Steiger threatened Johnson's part-time job as a justice of the
peace ``in order to steal his vote'' on retention of the board's
executive director.
   Steiger, as congressman, rancher and newspaper columnist, has
taken on his colleagues, neighbors, business associates, former
wife, police and highway officials in a colorfull career.
   He was 28 and a Republican when he ran for the state senate from
a 10-1 Democratic district and won the first of two terms.
   Steiger spent 10 years in Congress as a Republican before he
made a losing bid for a U.S. Senate seat. He ran for the
governorship on the Libertarian ticket in 1982.
   About a year ago, in the Prescott Sun, he repeated some of his
favorite advice.
   ``Shun lawyers, ignore lawyers, but above all, do not elect them
to public office,'' he said. ``Lawyers are the running sores of the
20th century, and if they are not isolated and done away with as
humanely as instinct will permit, they will be the cause of the
downfall of this culture.''
</TEXT>
