<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CigaretteSuit 2ndLd-Writethru a0622 06-03 0656</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cigarette Suit, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0622,0673</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cancer Victim's Free Choice Stressed In Defense Summations</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 3 grafs after 15th pvs, ``Bleakley, Lorillard xxx,
with more material on claim that smoking doesn't cause cancer and
research</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL J. WAKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawyers defending three tobacco companies
against liability charges ended their cases by claiming that
smoking doesn't cause cancer and cigarette makers researched the
issue enough to fulfill their corporate responsibility.
   The judge in the case today granted a delay in closing arguments
to an attorney for the man suing the companies over his wife's
lung-cancer death.
   The company lawyers' closing arguments mainly centered on the
will and motives of Rose Cipollone, a 58-year-old woman who died of
lung cancer in 1984. Her husband, Antonio, is seeking damages from
the companies that made the cigarettes she smoked for 40 years.
   ``Mrs. Cipollone made a decision you and I make every day of our
lives: to do, or not to do, something that is risky,'' Philip
Morris Co. attorney Peter K. Bleakley told the U.S. District Court
jury Thursday.
   Bleakley also defended industry research efforts as legitimate
and worthy.
   Attorney Marc Z. Edell, representing Cipollone, said he needed
more time to prepare his closing arguments, which had been
scheduled for today.
   U.S. District Judge H. Lee Sarokin also said he will grant the
``extraordinary remedy'' of a half-hour of rebuttal to each company
after Edell makes his arguments Monday. He said the companies felt
Edell's delay would prejudice the jury against them.
   The judge said he expected the case to go to the jury Tuesday.
   Cipollone claims the industry's research was inadequate and
partly an attempt to deflect health critics, and that advertising
and public relations were used to muddle the issue, all as part of
an effort to mislead the public.
   On Thursday, the second day of summations in the four-month
trial, Bleakley continued the theme of the lawyers for Lorillard
Inc. and Liggett Group Inc. who preceded him: that Mrs. Cipollone
was an intelligent, strong-willed woman who knew the risks and
chose to smoke out of pleasure.
   ``People have been claiming that smoking is bad for you, that
it's bad for your health, that it kills you, as long as these
products have been on the market,'' he told the jury. ``People do
things all the time they know to be risky.''
   Cigarette ads have nothing to do with undermining that
knowledge, Bleakley argued.
   Enjoyment of tobacco ``predates advertising by several hundred
years,'' he said, attacking Cipollone's contention that ads kept
his wife hooked on cigarettes.
   The companies presented evidence to support their contention
that Mrs. Cipollone was intelligent, knew of smoking's risks
through newspaper articles and the warnings of relatives and made a
strong-willed choice to smoke.
   Bleakley, Lorillard attorney Robert Northrip and Liggett
attorney Donald J. Cohn referred to testimony by relatives that
Mrs. Cipollone's husband constantly told her to stop smoking, that
her mother blamed cigarettes for her father's death when Mrs.
Cipollone was a child, and that two sisters called cigarettes
``coffin nails'' as youths.
   Bleakley defended the Council for Tobacco Research, formed and
funded by the tobacco companies to study the health effects of
smoking.
   He said no evidence showed the scientists on the council's
advisory panel were anything but reputable and disinterested, and
that the companies had fulfilled their research responsibility
through the council.
   The cigarette companies still maintain that there is no proof
that cigarettes directly cause cancer.
   Northrip also focused on medical testimony by physicians who
treated Mrs. Cipollone, pathologists who studied her cancer and
cancer experts.
   He said physicians disagreed over what kind of lung cancer
killed Mrs. Cipollone.
   ``Some (kinds) are statistically associated with cigarette
smoking _ small cell carcinoma. Some are not _ carcinoid, or
atypical carcinoid,'' said Northrip.
   Cipollone's experts said Mrs. Cipollone had small cell
carcinoma, and argued that atypical carcinoid also results from
smoking.
</TEXT>
