<HEAD>Whaling Commission Rejects Norway's Bid to Kill 35 Whales</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WELLINGTON, New Zealand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The International Whaling
Commission on Friday rejected a Norwegian proposal to kill 35
whales in the North Atlantic for scientific purposes.
   Delegates at the end of the whaling commmission's annual meeting
said Japanese plans for coastal whalers to kill 210 whales by the
end of September would be considered by the commission in two
months.
   The recommendation that Norway spare the whales was approved by
a 14-4 vote. There were 10 abstentions.
   Norway had planned to kill 35 whales this year and an
unspecified number each year until 1992.
</TEXT>
