<DOCNO> AP880603-0164 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-03-88 1423EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Libya-Terrorism     06-03 0427</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Libya-Terrorism,420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Libyan-Backed Groups Linked to Anti-U.S. Acts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HENRY GOTTLIEB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Groups supported by Libya are the ``prime
suspects'' in a spate of recent attacks against Americans and U.S.
facilities around the world, a State Department spokeswoman said
Friday.
   ``There has been an upsurge in recent weeks of terrorist attacks
against U.S. and other western European interests in Europe, Latin
America and Africa,'' spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley said. ``Although
these incidents are still under investigation in numerous cases,
the prime suspects are groups which have received support from
Libya.''
   The suspicion, she said, is accompanied by ``concrete evidence,
including the seizure of Libyan arms destined for the IRA (Irish
Republican Army) and the arrest in Senegal of Libyan operatives,
that Libya continues its support of terrorism.''
   Mrs. Oakley referred to reports that a weapons shipment
intercepted by France last November was bound for the outlawed IRA
and that suspected Libyan agents were arrested carrying bomb-making
materials in Senegal in February.
   For years, Libya has been one of less than a half-dozen
countries on a list of nations identified by the State Department
as sponsors of terrorist groups. The Reagan administration has
accused Libyan leader Moammar Gadhafi of fomenting terrorism and in
April 1986 U.S. warplanes attacked his personal living quarters in
Tripoli. He was not hit.
   Around the second anniversary of the attack, there were several
terrorist attacks on installations and clubs owned or frequented by
Americans.
   Among the targets hit this year were U.S. Information Agency
offices in Costa Rica, Colombia and Peru and the bombing of a club
frequented by American servicemen in Naples, Italy. Five people
were killed in the Naples attack. Two Americans were wounded in an
attack on a club in Khartoum, Sudan, in mid-May and the office of a
U.S. bank in New Delhi was also a target.
   Mrs. Oakley stopped short of directly accusing Libya in the
attacks, and U.S. officials have been quoted as saying there is no
``smoking gun'' to prove Gadhafi's involvement.
   ``We want to make sure that when we make statements about this,
that they correspond absolutely with the facts and the evidence
that we have,'' Mrs. Oakley said.
   A State Department official, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said it is widely believed that Libya is the headquarters for an
organization led by Abu Nidal, a Palestinian accused of terrorism
who was expelled last year from Syria.
   The department has blamed Abu Nidal for the December 1985
attacks that killed more than 20 people at the Rome and Vienna
airports.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880603-0165 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-03-88 1427EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People     06-03 0957</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People,0993</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American singer Laura Branigan
cried when she saw hungry black children eating their one daily
meal, but she voices no regrets about breaking the cultural boycott
of South Africa.
   Branigan concludes a series of six concerts this weekend at Sun
City, a sports-and-casino resort in the nominally independent black
homeland of Bophuthatswana.
   She is one of the few American pop stars to perform in South
Africa in recent years. In the early 1980s, Frank Sinatra, Dolly
Parton and Cher sang in the racially segregated country.
   ``People in the U.S. are so ignorant, to look down on
entertainers who come out here,'' said Branigan, who is white.
``You can come out here and help. They are hurting people by not
coming out, when they can come here and do good.''
   Earlier this week, Branigan was taken to schools and child-care
centers in a poverty-stricken part of Bophuthatswana where a
private charity, Operation Hunger, is active. Branigan had donated
$50,000 of her undisclosed performing fee to Operation Hunger.
   ``This is terrible,'' she said. ``How can they let this happen?
There's no excuse for it in such a rich country.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Jackson's concert in this city of
Mozart and Strauss was so exciting to 130 female fans that they
fainted, police said.
   Fifty thousand fans crammed Vienna's Prater soccer stadium for
Jackson's show Thursday night, the third on his European tour.
   Though the fans were enthusiastic, the Austria Press Agency
sniffed, ``Jackson is the product and part of the U.S.
entertainment (industry), which every once in a while deems itself
better than it actually is.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MICHIGAN CITY, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Country singer Loretta Lynn's
brother-in-law James Lynn has been approved for parole after
spending 20 years in prison for the fatal shooting of his wife.
   The Indiana Parole Board voted 3-1 Thursday to release Lynn, 50,
after he testified at a hearing at the State Prison, where he has
participated in substance-abuse counseling.
   ``He indicated Thursday that he has a weakness for alcohol and
has to be aware of it,'' said board Chairman Lewis J. Gregory, who
voted against Lynn's release.
   Lynn was granted clemency in 1986 and was put on a work-release
program, but was returned to prison after two alcohol-related
incidents, said Gregory.
   He said Lynn's parole plans must be approved in advance by the
state of Wisconsin, where he will live. That is expected to take a
couple of months, during which Lynn will remain in prison.
   Once released, Lynn, the brother of the singer's husband, Moody,
is expected to work in a restaurant owned by Ms. Lynn's daughter.
   Lynn was convicted for the March 31, 1968, death of his wife,
Sandra. Witnesses said he got out of a car and shot his wife in the
head and chest with a .38-caliber revolver as she sat in another
car.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>AUGUSTA, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A congressman's praise of ``Soul Man'' James
Brown as ``our No. 1 ambassador'' was not intended literally, a
lawyer for the singer's wife, Adrienne, has concluded, so he's
dropping his motion seeking diplomatic immunity for her.
   Attorney Allen W. Johnson had asked a Richmond County State
Court judge to dismiss misdemeanor traffic charges on grounds of
diplomatic immunity, but he said Thursday he would withdraw the
motion.
   Mrs. Brown, 38, was charged with driving under the influence of
drugs, speeding and criminal trespass last September. She pleaded
innocent, and the case is expected to go to trial later this month.
   Rep. Douglas Barnard, D-Ga., said two years ago on James Brown
Appreciation Day in Augusta, near Brown's home on Beech Island,
S.C.: ``James is indeed our No. 1 ambassador.''
   Johnson said he asked for diplomatic immunity for the singer's
wife only because every possible defense had to be explored. He
said he has since determined that Barnard intended his comments as
a figure of speech.
   Diplomatic immunity shields officials of foreign nations from
criminal charges while they represent their countries in the United
States.
   The Browns have recently had several highly publicized fights,
and Brown has said he plans to file for divorce.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Oregon Symphony, led by a high school
classmate of Bill Cosby, has recorded a new arrangement of the
theme music to NBC-TV's top-rated ``The Cosby Show.''
   The jazz-influenced theme, which lasts just one minute, was
arranged and conducted by James DePreist, the symphony's music
director.
   The recording session Thursday was closed to visitors because
the show's producers don't want the music revealed until the new
television season begins in October.
   Each year Cosby requests a new arrangement to introduce and end
the show. This year he asked DePreist, who attended high school
with Cosby in Philadelphia, to do it.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Designer Bob Mackie says he's too preoccupied
with his new ready-to-wear collections to entertain his celebrity
clients.
   ``Usually they like to come down, spend the day and have lunch.
I give them advice if they need it, but I don't like to be a
confidante,'' said Mackie, whose fantasy gowns have adorned such
notables as Cher, Carol Burnett and Bernadette Peters.
   ``I don't want to know who is sleeping with whom or who is
getting a divorce. I don't want to be their date when their
husbands are out of town _ I'll leave that to the hairdressers.''
   Mackie, 49, said his new collections are a departure from his
beaded and feathered costuming.
   ``Now I have to think of the needs of women who buy
high-price-range clothes. What do they do?'' he asked. ``They go to
meetings, they go to lunch, they go to openings, they go to charity
balls.''
