<HEAD>Dealership Dogs Killed By Thieves</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thieves who entered a luxury car dealership
shot to death two guard dogs and peppered several cars with bullets
before making off with a $20,000 BMW, police said.
   Dirk Essert, manager of Louis Motorcars, said he found the dogs
dead and the car missing when he came to work Thursday. Several
other BMWs and some Subarus were shot up, and tires were stolen
from a Cadillac, he told police.
   Essert estimated damage to the cars at $11,000, but said the
killing of the Doberman pinscher and German shepherd was more
upsetting.
   ``I felt sick. Plain and simple,'' said Essert, 39. ``The holes
in the cars can be fixed up. The dogs can't be replaced.''
   The dogs were owned by K-9 Orlando, a private company that
provides guard dogs at night and on weekends.
   Orange County sheriff's deputies said they have no suspects.
