<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     06-03 0576</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright & Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As every comic book reader knows,
Metropolis is the home base of Superman, while Gotham is where
Batman wages his war against crime. Now, it seems, Maine's largest
city can lay claim to a superhero, too.
   Portland's ``Mr. Jigsaw,'' known to friends and family as
Charlie Grant, is a crime-fighter with detachable body parts that
continue to function after they leave his body.
   The character is the creation of comic book writer Ronald
Fortier of Somersworth, N.H.
   ``I love Maine and my wife and I come to Portland all the
time,'' Fortier said. ``So I decided to put the hero in Maine
because people are so warm and friendly there.''
   The 41-year-old Fortier writes the texts for the comic and sends
them to an illustrator in Hawaii, Gary Kato, who came up with the
suggestion for the kind-hearted hero.
   ``He told me he'd like to do a comedy superhero that can
dismember himself but still control the parts of his body,''
Fortier recalled. ``I thought he must be kidding.''
   In the initial episode of the hero's adventures, Mr. Jigsaw and
a reporter from the Portland Herald are waylaid by three escapees
from the Maine State Prison. Mr. Jigsaw dispatches the villains and
teams up with the reporter to fight crime and corruption.
   In an upcoming episode, Mr. Jigsaw catches a robber at a
shopping mall by throwing his hand at him.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Herbert Bayer's controversial bright yellow,
85-foot-tall ``Articulated Wall'' sculpture in the Broadway Plaza
complex has developed a new problem: Its paint is peeling.
   The bright yellow color of the 850-ton concrete sculpture didn't
please everyone at its unveiling three years ago. Now, Broadway
Plaza's new owner, Western Equities Group, is negotiating with the
Denver Art Museum, which owns the ``Wall,'' to get permission to
paint the art work gold.
   Museum spokesman Lewis Story said changing the color might
violate Bayer's intent. The museum also is studying Western
Equities' plans to use drawings of the ``Wall'' as a logo on
marketing materials for Broadway Plaza.
   Bayer, an exponent of the Bauhaus school of modern design, died
in 1985. Bayer, and later his widow, Joella, tangled with former
Broadway Plaza owner Allan Reiver, claiming they were not
adequately paid. Mrs. Bayer recently settled the lawsuit.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HUTCHINSON, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There was a buck on the line, a ``Buck''
on the bench and a city prosecutor bucking the system.
   City Prosecutor Ed Britton took Hutchinson's First National Bank
to court, alleging bank workers charged him more than agreed to
sort a handful of coins.
   Britton told District Court Judge William F. ``Buck'' Lyle the
bank clerk told him it would cost 50 cents.
   The coins amounted to $5.10, Britton said. The bank said that
because the amount was more than $5, the fee went up to a buck.
   They gave him $4.10, keeping the buck.
   Britton protested he hadn't been told of a sliding fee scale.
   During court proceedings, Lyle asked bank officials whether any
such fee schedule had been shown to Britton. They said, no. Lyle
then found for Britton, awarding him 50 cents.
   Britton also sought punitive damages but found the law does not
provide punitive damages in small claims cases.
   ``I wanted them penalized in the same percentage they penalized
me,'' he said.
   He got part of his wish.
   Judge ``Buck'' Lyle assessed court costs of $10 against the bank.
</TEXT>
