<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Soviet-Missiles     06-03 0303</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Missiles,0312</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Demonstrate How SS-20 Missile Transports Will Be
Eliminated</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soldiers at a military base in the Ukraine showed
foreign reporters today how they will dismantle transports and
launchers for Soviet medium-range missiles, Tass said.
   The missiles are banned under a treaty which took effect
Wednesday when President Reagan and Soviet leader Mikhail S.
Gorbachev exchanged ratification documents during the superpower
summit in Moscow. The leaders signed the agreement in Washington
last Dec. 8.
   The treaty mandates the destruction of all superpower
intermediate-range missiles, including the triple-warhead Soviet
RSD-10 rockets that are known in the West as SS-20s.
   Tass, the official news agency, said 43 broadcast journalists
from the United States, Britain, France, Japan and other countries
were invited today to the Sarny military base in the western
Ukraine to observe how SS-20 transports and launchers will be
eliminated.
   A detachment of Soviet soldiers under Col. Yevgeny Kozlov gave a
step-by-step demonstration, Tass said.
   The missiles themselves will be destroyed at another military
base, Kapustin Yar in the Volgograd region, Tass said. Their
nuclear charges will be extracted and used in the civilian economy,
it said.
   More than 600 launchers and wheeled transports used to carry the
missiles will be dismantled at Sarny over the next three years, in
accordance with the treaty, Tass said.
   American inspectors are expected to arrive at the base about 60
miles from the city of Rovno by July 1, where they will monitor the
elimination of the equipment, Tass said.
   Two two-story buildings with 10 one-room apartments apiece have
been built for the American inspectors, as well as a mess hall for
32 people and a bar, Tass said.
   Cottages have also been built in a nearby forest near a lake for
the Americans to use for off-hours relaxation, it said.
</TEXT>
