<DOCNO> AP880603-0174 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-03-88 1500EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel Bjt   06-03 0644</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel, Bjt,0661</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>200th Arab Killed; Another General Strike in Territories</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto TLV1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN IZENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Another Arab strike paralyzed the occupied
lands Friday, and a 20-year-old man shot in the chest became the
200th Palestinian killed since a rebellion against Israeli rule
began six months ago.
   Officials at Alia hospital in Hebron said relatives of Mustafa
Ahmed Halaika told them the man was shot by Jewish settlers in the
nearby West Bank village of Shuykh.
   He died of a bullet wound in the chest, and three other Arabs
were wounded by gunfire in the village, the hospital officials
said. Soldiers wounded two other Palestinians during a protest in
Nablus.
   The three-day strike that began Friday was total. Stores were
closed, streets were deserted and there was no public
transportation throughout the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   Halaika's relatives said five Jewish settlers opened fire when
Palestinians protested their presence in Shuykh, the hospital
officials said.
   A Palestinian driver who accompanied two journalists to the
hospital quoted a 15-year-old villager, Nael Ayaide, as saying the
settlers beat him and another Arab.
   Villagers began stoning the settlers, who then opened fire, the
driver quoted Ayaide as saying. The driver said Ayaide had a broken
arm.
   The driver and hospital officials would not allow their names to
be used. A military spokesman said the army was investigating the
reports.
   The driver said the two Arabs wounded in Nablus were shot when
soldiers opened fire on protesters who erected barricades and threw
stones.
   According to U.N. figures, 200 Arabs have been killed since the
uprising began Dec. 8 among the 1.5 million Palestinians of the
West Bank and Gaza, which Israel captured from Jordan and Egypt in
the 1967 war. An Israeli soldier and a teen-age Jewish settler also
have been slain.
   The army prepared for more violence by restricting the movements
of more than 200,000 Palestinians with curfews and closures at 12
refugee camps, towns and villages.
   In the Gaza Strip, Israeli soldiers orders a metalworks closed
for three years. The army accused the owner, Nasser Youssef, of
making large nails that Arabs scatter on roads to puncture the
tires of Israeli-owned cars.
   In Bethlehem, protesters hung Palestinians flags on telephone
wires and painted slogans on walls that said, among other things,
``Observe the strike or we are going to burn.'' Israel has declared
the Palestinian flag illegal.
   Palestinian leaders ordered the three-day strike to protest the
current Middle East tour of George P. Shultz, the U.S. secretary of
state. It began Friday in Cairo and will include a stop in Israel
on Sunday.
   Israeli officials said the trip is important for keeping the
peace process alive, but they do not expect dramatic results. Prime
Minister Yitzhak Shamir's right-wing Likud bloc opposes an exchange
of occupied land for peace, the basis of the U.S. plan Shultz is
promoting.
   In a leaflet calling for the strike, underground leaders accused
Shultz of trying to abort the rebellion.
   ``The masses and activists must make more demonstrations and ..
. the land must burn under the feet of the fascist occupier,'' the
leaflet said.
   A general strike declared last Monday had little effect, and
this one has been seen as a test of the ``intefadeh,'' the Arabic
word for uprising.
   Shamir, Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin and other Israeli leaders
have said recently the rebellion was abating and Clinton Bailey, an
Arab affairs expert at Tel Aviv University, said Palestinians were
losing their enthusiasm.
   ``It's kind of hard to get people out in the streets right
now,'' he said. ``You don't have that mass identification you had
in the past.''
   Shamir said in a statement carried Friday on Israel radio
``there are signs the uprising is waning,'' but added that
``undesirable intervention by Jews and Israelis'' helped keep it
going. He did not elaborate.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
