<1ST_LINE>u a PM-Mecham 2ndLd-Writethru a0676 06-03 0666</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mecham, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0676,0683</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Denies Mecham Mistrial Motion</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 9 grafs to UPDATE with judge denying mistrial
motion, picking up 10th graf, `About 90 ...;' SUBS 18th graf,
`William Flynn ...,' to delete first reference to him.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LAURIE ASSEO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge today refused to grant a mistrial
in former Gov. Evan Mecham's criminal trial, rejecting a defense
argument that the prosecution introduced improper testimony during
the trial's first day.
   The motion contended that testimony Thursday by a prosecution
witness ``suggests that the defendants had committed prior bad acts
or criminal conduct involving altered campaign records.''
   It referred to testimony by William Flynn, a state handwriting
expert, that there had been ``white-outs, erasures and
alterations'' in a campaign checkbook, defense lawyer Thomas Crowe
said.
   Crowe contended the changes were merely innocent corrections,
but that the prosecution implied there was ``something sinister''
about them.
   Mecham and his brother, Willard, are charged with concealing a
$350,000 campaign loan. Willard Mecham was his brother's 1986
campaign treasurer.
   Prosecutor Barnett Lotstein said today there was no negative
implication in the testimony about the checkbook. He said the
prosecution was seeking to show that Willard Mecham was a
meticulous bookkeeper who was not prone to mistakes.
   Maricopa County Superior Court Judge Michael Ryan said in his
ruling that he thought Flynn's testimony was ``quite innocuous.''
   In opening statements Thursday, defense lawyers said the failure
to report the loan was an innocent mistake, while Lotstein alleged
the Mechams purposely broke the law when they failed to include the
loan from Tempe developer Barry Wolfson in a financial report.
   ``It was no oversight, no mistake,'' said Lotstein, an assistant
attorney general. ``No person looking at this report would have any
idea that Barry Wolfson had anything to do with the $350,000 that
came into the campaign.''
   About 90 minutes before the start of the trial Thursday, the
Arizona Supreme Court rejected a defense bid to dismiss the charges
or return them to the state grand jury for a new determination of
probable cause. The defense has claimed the grand jury was misled
by the state attorney general's office.
   Mecham faces up to 22 years in prison if convicted on all six
counts of perjury, willful concealment and filing false documents.
   The Republican governor was removed from office April 4 when the
state Senate convicted him of two unrelated impeachment counts.
Mecham took office in January 1987.
   Willard Mecham faces three similar counts and up to 9{ years in
prison if convicted.
   Mecham long has contended the $350,000 loan was properly
reported on his Dec. 5, 1986, financial report. He said it was
included in a $465,000 lump sum that was listed as a contribution
from himself.
   ``If you wanted to conceal a loan you could do it very easily,''
Scott said. ``The prosecution's case is made out of smoke.''
   Lotstein told the jury that Mecham had a 1986 campaign theme
``of being beholden to no one'' and that the theme could have been
harmed by public knowledge that a major part of his war chest came
from a developer.
   But Scott noted that Mecham was elected Nov. 4, 1986, a month
before the financial report was filed.
   Flynn testified that the ``Evan Mecham'' signed on one of the
governor's 1986 campaign financial reporting statements was not
Mecham's handwriting, ``but is rather an attempt to simulate or
draw the signature of Evan Mecham.''
   The signatures on Mecham's other documents were genuine, Flynn
testified. Scott objected, saying no one had disputed the
authenticity of the forms themselves.
   Scott also said a Mecham administration official, Mac Matheson,
was responsible for omitting the debt to Wolfson from Mecham's
personal disclosure form filed in early 1987. The defense lawyer
added that other officials were allowed to amend their forms
without being prosecuted.
   Willard Mecham's lawyer, Joe Keilp, said in his opening
statement that his client did not intentionally violate the law as
the 1986 campaign's bookkeeper.
</TEXT>
