<HEAD>Hollywood Author's Glitz Novel Near Top of Charts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jackie Collins, self-appointed doyenne of
Hollywood writers, says she, like the subjects of her novels,
searched for and found the American dream.
   ``You see it all the time on television,'' said the British
expatriate and younger sister of ``Dynasty'' vixen Joan Collins.
``Real people who come out to Hollywood with nothing and parlay
that into something. People like Hefner, Cartier, the Kennedys.
It's their story.''
   Ms. Collins recounted recently how she was expelled from her
exclusive English high school for smoking, after which her parents
told her: ```You're not bad looking. Why don't you go off to
Hollywood and be a movie star like your sister.'''
   Dismal bit parts steered Ms. Collins away from acting and toward
writing about the players. Her latest ode to life in the fast lane,
``Rock Star,'' held steady at No. 4 on last week's New York Times
best-seller list, following her last two local tell-alls
``Hollywood Wives'' and ``Hollywood Husbands.''
   ``Some people tend to regard me as the Hollywood expert,'' she
said. ``I could write a book tomorrow with all the real names _
short one-liners that would let you know exactly who everybody
really was.''
