<FILEID>AP-NR-06-03-88 1517EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Sakharov Bjt   06-03 0796</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sakharov, Bjt,0821</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sakharov Says Gorbachev Deserves Time and Trust</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Human rights activist Andrei D. Sakharov said
Friday that Mikhail S. Gorbachev has not yet guaranteed human
rights but that the Soviet leader must be given time and trust to
carry out his reforms.
   Sahharov, the 1975 Nobel Peace Prize winner and a former
political exile, told reporters at the Foreign Ministry press
center that his unprecedented appearance at a government building
``reflects a change in the situation in this country, and it's not
a matter of me changing my position.''
   He held his news conference in the same hall where Soviet leader
Mikhail S. Gorbachev on Wednesday held his first formal meeting
with reporters in the Soviet Union.
   Sakharov, 67, handed Gorbachev a list of names of 200 political
prisoners when they met for the first time in January. On Friday,
he called again for the release of those who remain incarcerated
for their beliefs.
   The physicist, who helped develop the Soviet hydrogen bomb and
found the Soviet human rights movement, also criticized officials
for withdrawing a job offer to a dissident who met with President
Reagan during the summit.
   The move was ``a blatant example of a return to the practices of
the past,'' Sakharov said.
   Sakharov sat at a desk in front of hundreds of foreign and
Soviet reporters rather than on the elevated dais, and he drew a
larger crowd than Gorbachev.
   Until recently, such a news conference would have been
unthinkable for Sakharov, who was exiled to the closed city of
Gorky in January 1980 for criticizing Soviet intervention in
Afghanistan.
   Gorbachev allowed Sakharov to return to Moscow in December 1986.
   ``I believe sizeable changes have taken place of late. Of course
they are not exhaustive and do not ensure the full implementation
of human rights,'' Sakharov said. ``On the whole, I believe
perestroika (Gorbachev's social and economic reforms) is a serious
undertaking, and its international and domestic implications are
very serious, too.
   ``An expression of trust in this country ... would only promote
perestroika in this country. In particular, an expression of
confidence in this country and this government will help promote
human rights issues, too.''
   He said he is worried about the future of Gorbachev's reforms
but believes they will succeed because there is no alternative.
   Sakharov called Gorbachev an ``outstanding statesman'' and
added, ``from the bottom of my heart I wish him luck, mainly for
the cause with which his name is now associated.''
   Sakharov has been reluctant to talk to reporters since returning
from Gorky, instead concentrating on scientific work and expressing
his views in occasional letters to the official press.
   He said he still is not free to travel abroad, ostensibly
because of his access to secret material until 1968, but feels he
is free to do and and say what he wants in the Soviet Union.
   Sakharov's wife, Yelena Bonner, said her husband held the news
conference at the government press center because reporters
covering the summit meeting had called ``from morning to night,''
asking for interviews.
   On other issues in a wide-ranging discussion, Sakharov:
   _Welcomed the Soviet withdrawal from Afghanistan, which started
May 15. He said it should go on regardless of the conduct of
anti-Marxist Afghan rebels. Any Afghan who wants it should be given
political asylum in the Soviet Union or another country, he said.
   _Urged the Soviet Union to cut its military personnel by 50
percent, and criticized what he said is abuse of inductees in the
Soviet military.
   _Said he believes the Soviet Union eventually will have more
than one political party.
   _Supported the demands of two ethnic groups _ Crimean Tatars who
want to return to their home area from which they were exiled by
dictator Josef Stalin, and Armenians who want to annex the
Nagorno-Karabakh region of Azerbaijan.
   _Called for greater religious freedom and official recognition
of the underground Ukrainian Catholic Church.
   Sakharov, who has spoken out on nuclear arms reduction, said the
summit between Reagan and Gorbachev was important but did not
achieve much.
   He urged the two sides to work for more progress on a treaty to
halve their long-range nuclear missiles, saying they can work
around their disputes over verification problems and Reagan's
Strategic Defense Initiative.
   Sakharov praised Reagan's meeting on Monday with Soviet
dissidents and refuseniks but criticized the Soviet reaction. A
long-time dissident lost a job opportunity because of his
attendance, Sakharov said.
   He said Sergei Kovalov, a biologist, had reached an agreement to
receive a job in a Moscow institute, but was told the day after his
meeting with Reagan that the institute had changed its mind.
Kovalov was exiled in the 1970s for his work publishing underground
political material.
</TEXT>
