<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Iran-Iraq Bjt   06-03 0608</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iran-Iraq, Bjt,0622</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iranian Warplane Tries To Bomb Iraqi President's Home</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MONA ZIADE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraqi forces on Friday drove off an
Iranian warplane that flew 110 miles into Iraq and tried to bomb
President Saddam Hussein's family home north of Baghdad, a military
command announced.
   While maneuvering to evade Iraqi ground fire, the Iranian jet
``dropped all its load of explosives indiscriminately'' in the
village of Ouja, just south of Tikrit, Saddam's hometown, the
official Iraqi News Agency said.
   No injuries were reported in the attack at 5:55 a.m., according
to the news agency. The report, monitored in Nicosia, did not say
whether Saddam was home at the time. It was the first time the
Iraqis have reported an attack on Saddam's hometown during the
nearly 8-year-old Iran-Iraq war.
   The report did not say whether the U.S.-built Iranian F-4
Phantom jet was hit.
   Iran's official Islamic Republic News Agency said its warplanes
on Friday attacked military targets in three raids on Iraq,
including one near Tikrit at 5:25 a.m., but it gave no other
details.
   Iran's new acting commander-in-chief, Hashemi Rafsanjani, urged
his countrymen to take the war with Iraq ``more seriously.''
   The Iraqi News Agency did not explain how the Iranian plane flew
undetected all the way from the border, 110 miles to the east, to
attack Saddam's home, which is 100 miles northwest of Baghdad.
Military analysts said an F-4 flying at low altitudes is capable of
evading detection by radar.
   After the attack, Saddam led a meeting of the governing
Revolutionary Command Council.
   An official spokesman, who was not identified by name, said the
leadership decided ``not to carry out a direct retaliation today
... to help the Iranian people liberate themselves from the
nightmare of these evil charlatan rulers.''
   But, he added, ``Iraq will reserve its right to carry out a
crushing and comprehensive retaliation at the appropriate time.''
He called the Iranian attack ``a flagrant violation'' of a truce in
the ``war of the cities.''
   Thousands of civilians in both countries were killed in
long-range missile duels and air raids that raged for two months
before the April 21 cease-fire in the war of the cities. Many of
the missiles hit Tehran and Baghdad.
   Rafsanjani, the speaker of Iran's Parliament, was appointed by
Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini on Thursday as acting
commander-in-chief, a post Khomeini had held since the Islamic
Revolution in 1979.
   Rafsanjani told a prayer meeting in Tehran on Friday there
should be ``no compromise, no submission and no backing down from
our rights'' in the war. His speech was carried by IRNA, which also
was monitored in Nicosia. ``We should take the situation more
seriously,'' he told the worshipers.
   The Iranian agency also reported that Rafsanjani sent a cable to
the 87-year-old Khomeini thanking him for the new appointment.
   Iran suffered two recent major defeats on the battlefield. In
April, Iraqi forces retook the southern Faw peninsula, two years
after it was captured by the Iranians. Last month, the Iraqis
recaptured Salamchah, east of the city of Basra. The latter region
had been overrun in an Iranian thrust last year.
   Earlier Friday, Rafsanjani told a congress commemorating a 1963
attempted uprising against Shah Mohammad Reza Pahlavi that the war
with Iraq should continue until all the objectives set by Khomeini
are reached.
   Rafsanjani said: ``If we back down even a bit in the war, we
will sustain major losses.'' He called on armed forces to recruit
more people into ``war-related affairs'' so that ``arrogance will
be deprived of its last weapon and we can prepare to face the next
schemes of the world-devourers.''
</TEXT>
