<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Iran-Arrests     06-03 0517</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iran-Arrests,0534</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Politician Who Denounced Khomeini Protests Arrests</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELAINE GANLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leader of Iran's only legal opposition movement
has protested to Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini about a series of
arrests that followed criticism of the ayatollah's policies,
according to reports reaching Paris on Friday.
   In a telegram to Iran's spiritual leader, Mehdi Bazargan took
responsiblity for letters written by himself and his supporters
calling for an end to the war with Iraq, the French newspaper Le
Monde reported.
   ``Our only crime is to be concerned about the dangers which
threaten the existence of our country and its survival,'' Le Monde
quoted the telegram as saying.
   There had been concern that Bazargan also had been arrested, but
he was at his Tehran home on Thursday, Le Monde reported.
   In late May, Bazargan circulated an open letter to Khomeini
accusing him of practicing ``despotism worthy of the pharaohs'' and
making Iran a symbol of hate around the world.
   Security forces subsequently rounded up numerous sympathizers of
Bazargan who had circulated their own letter, according to Le Monde
and Paris-based opposition figures with sources in Iran.
   Bazargan, a former Iranian prime minister and parliamentary
deputy, heads the Freedom Movement, the only opposition group
tolerated by Khomeini's regime.
   It was not clear how many arrests were made. Le Monde suggested
that several dozen people, many former government ministers, could
have been detained.
   The letters from Bazargan and his supporters, said to have been
distributed over the past two weeks, called for negotiations to end
the Iran-Iraq war.
   Former Iranian President Abolhassan Bani-Sadr, living in exile
in Paris, said his contacts in Iran were able to confirm that
Bazargan was not under arrest.
   Observers say Bazargan's open letter was his strongest protest
to date and had special impact because of an increasingly tense
climate in Tehran after recent setbacks in the Iran-Iraq war.
   Bazargan ``has protested in the past, but not in these terms and
in this situation,'' Bani-Sadr said in a telephone interview with
The Associated Press. ``The arrests show that this letter is not
like others. It reveals the condition of public opinion in Iran.''
   On Thursday, Khomeini appointed Parliament Speaker Hashemi
Rafsanjani as acting commander-in-chief of Iran's armed forces. On
Friday, Rafsanjani called on Iranians to take the war ``more
seriously.''
   Bani-Sadr, first president of the Islamic Republic and former
armed forces commander-in-chief, said he had ample information to
show an ``intense dispute'' over the conduct of the war within the
armed forces.
   On Thursday, Le Monde printed excerpts from Bazargan's letter to
Khomeini.
   ``In truth, for seven years Iran and Islam have become
synonymous in the world with hate and malice,'' the excerpt read.
``It is a shame and not an honor. ...
   ``When are you going to stop making commerce with the blood of
our martyrs?''
   Bani-Sadr said that among those arrested were Ali Ardalan, a
former finance minister, Husseini Shah Hussein, president of the
welcome committee when the exiled Khomeini returned to Iran in
1980; former Interior Minister Hachem Sabbaghian; and former
Justice and Interior Minister Ahmed Sadr Djavadi.
</TEXT>
