<HEAD>Kitty Dukakis Recovering After Surgery; Husband to Resume Campaign</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates throughout with more information about surgery,
Dukakis campaign plans and quotes.
^By JOHN KING</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kitty Dukakis, wife of the Democratic presidential
front-runner, underwent five hours of delicate surgery Friday to
correct a spinal problem that doctors had feared could lead to
paralysis. Husband Michael Dukakis canceled campaign plans to be
with her.
   ``I talked to Kitty in the recovery room and she said she wanted
an ice cream and a massage,'' Dukakis said following the surgery.
``I'm prepared to provide both.''
   Dr. Lawrence Borges said, ``The operation went very well. There
were no problems at all.''
   Borges said Mrs. Dukakis would be in the intensive care unit
overnight, and would remain in Massachusetts General Hospital for
about a week. Doctors said she woke up immediately after the
operation.
   Surgeons removed two herniated discs from Mrs. Dukakis' neck and
replaced them with bone taken from her hip. She had been
experiencing pain and numbness fr several weeks and doctors
determined both problems were caused by dangerous pressure on her
spine because of the discs.
   Her husband, the Massachusetts governor, returned from
California Thursday night and spent the night in his wife's room at
the hospital.
   Dukakis said that if no complications developed from the
operation he would resume campaigning Saturday afternoon in New
Jersey. He said he planned to return to Boston Saturday night to
visit his wife again, then go back to New Jersey Sunday morning and
then head to California for campaigning through Tuesday, the last
day of the 1988 primary season.
   The governor canceled a debate Thursday with Democratic rival
Jesse Jackson to return to Boston, and he said he thought it
unlikely the debate would be rescheduled.
   New Jersey, California, New Mexico and Montana hold the final
Democratic presidential primaries Tuesday. Dukakis is favored to
win in all four states, gaining enough delegates to assure him the
Democratic nomination to face likely Republican nominee George Bush
in November.
   Mrs. Dukakis was campaigning in California on behalf of her
husband when she was diagnosed as having herniated discs. She
returned home Wednesday night for additional tests, and doctors
decided immediate surgery was the best course.
   Because she had more than one herniated disc and because the
problem was in her neck, doctors said waiting before correcting the
problem could lead to permanent nerve damage and possibly
paralysis. The discs serve as soft cushions between the bony
vertebrae that protect the spinal cord.
   After the surgery, her doctors said Mrs. Duakakis should regain
full mobility of her neck but would have to wear a cervical collar
for several weeks. She also likely will walk with a limp for
several weeks because of the surgery to remove the bone from her
hip.
   Mrs. Dukakis is considered to be in good overall health. Last
year she said she had been addicted to amphetamines for 26 years
before entering a drug clinic in 1982.
</TEXT>
