<HEAD>Government Gives Awards to Church Leaders on Eve of Millenium</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government gave awards to 15 leaders of the
Russian Orthodox Church on Friday, two days before they begin
celebrating the 1,000th anniversary of Christianity in what is now
the Soviet Union.
   Alexander Ogorodnikov, a Russian Orthodox dissident, said police
had prevented a Moldavian man from traveling to Moscow for an
unofficial commemoration of the millenium. Ogorodnikov also said
officials turned down his own request for space in the city to hold
unofficial alternative celebrations.
   Dissidents criticize church leaders for their close contacts
with the government, which controls church activity.
   A statement by President Andrei A. Gromyko, carried by the
official news agency Tass, awarded the Red Banner of Labor to the
Patriarch Pimen, leader of the church; Metropolitan Filaret of Kiev
and Galitsky, and two archbishops. Ten other leading clerics were
given the Order of Peoples' Friendship.
   Celebrations of the millenium, expected to bring thousands of
church officials and tourists to Moscow, begin Sunday with a
worship service in Epiphany Cathedral. They continue through June
13 in Moscow, then move to the former church centers of Kiev,
Vladimir and Leningrad.
   Ogorodnikov, a former political prisoner, plans seminars and
worship services in Moscow next week as alternatives to the
official celebration.
   He applied to the city for meeting space for the commemoration,
but said Friday he was refused.
   Yuri Rudenko of Kishinev, capital of Moldavia, was taken off a
train Thursday and stopped in a car Friday while trying to come to
Moscow, Ogorodnikov said.
   Rudenko was taken before a prosecutor in Kishinev and told he
was being investigated for slandering the situation of believers in
Moldavia, the dissident said.
