<HEAD>Pentagon Demonstrators Call for Home-Building, Not Bombs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A small group of protesters staged a peaceful
demonstration on behalf of the homeless outside the Pentagon on
Friday, announcing similar rallies would be held in 34 other cities
on Saturday.
   The demonstration was mounted by a coalition led by the Jobs
With Peace Campaign, a Boston-based group which lists among its
advisory board Democratic presidential candidates Michael Dukakis
and Jesse Jackson; Sen. John Kerry, D-Mass.; and Reps. Patricia
Schroeder, D-Colo., Ronald Dellums, D-Calif., and Don Edwards,
D-Calif. _ none of whom attended the rally.
   The new ``Build Homes, Not Bombs'' campaign is designed to
develop public support for cutting the defense budget and using the
funds to provide housing for the homeless.
   ``Over the past seven years, we've seen the military budget
double while funds for housing were cut by 78 pecent,'' said Ann
Wilson, a co-chairwoman of Jobs with Peace. ``We need to change
this situation.
   ``We can have peace with jobs, or we can have death with war,''
added Molly Yard, president of the National Organization for Women.
   Friday's demonstration, which lasted about 75 minutes, attracted
about 70 protesters and ended with the ``construction'' of a
prefabricated house on a Pentagon lawn.
   There were no incidents or arrests.
