<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WayneWilliams     06-03 0342</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wayne Williams,0350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Williams Attorney: Parole Denial ``Doesn't Disappoint Us''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wayne Williams, convicted of two murders and
suspected of many more in the series of killings of young blacks
that rocked the city in 1979-81, lost his first chance at parole,
state officials announced Friday.
   The Georgia Board of Pardons and Paroles announced that it had
denied parole for Williams, 29, who is serving two life sentences
at the Georgia Diagnostic and Classification Center in Jackson.
Spokesman Silas Moore said the board informed Williams of its
decision in a letter mailed Wednesday.
   Williams' attorney, Lynn Whatley, said the board's decision was
not disappointing because the board routinely denies parole on an
inmate's first review.
   ``I think it was done in a manner of course, what they do for
all inmates,'' Whatley said. ``It doesn't disappoint us, doesn't
take away our momentum.''
   Whatley said he and Williams are more concerned with appealing
his convictions for the murders of Nathaniel Cater and Jimmy Ray
Payne. There may be some action on Williams' appeal in Butts County
Superior Court during the summer, he said.
   ``We expect to be successful in the appellate court before the
end of the year,'' Whatley said. ``We have a tremendous amount of
suppressed evidence, and we intend to use it in court.''
   Williams, a free-lance photographer, was convicted Feb. 27,
1982, of two counts of murder in what had become known as the
Atlanta child slayings. He was not charged in the 27 other deaths
of young blacks that took place between 1979 and 1981, although 22
of the cases were closed and attributed to Williams after his
conviction.
   Georgia law requires that inmates serving life sentences
automatically be considered for parole after seven years. Williams,
who was arrested in June 1981, will be eligible for parole
consideration again in 1996, Moore said.
   ``You can be assured that it was the majority decision of the
board,'' Moore said, adding that the five-member board cited ``the
circumstances and nature of the offenses'' as reasons for denying
parole.
