<1ST_LINE>u a AM-PhonesAtLast Bjt   06-03 0611</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Phones At Last, Bjt,0628</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>First Full Phone Service Since May 8 Set for Chicago Suburbs</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto staffing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HINSDALE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police Chief Robert O'Malley will never
forget the Great Phone Outage, like the morning he spent on a
cellular car phone trying to reach Fire Chief Stan Bulat, who was
parked just a few feet away.
   ``I guess everybody will have something to remember that outage
by, and that phone call to Stan will be mine,'' O'Malley said.
   Both were dependent on their cellular car telephones and kept
missing each other. When they finally hooked up, ``I said, `We need
to meet, where are you?' He said `Behind the fire station.' I said
`Me too,''' O'Malley recalled.
   ``That's when we realized we were parked just feet from each
other,'' on either side of a van, he said.
   ``Quite frankly, I'm glad it wasn't a crime wave _ or something
more serious like that.''
   At 12:01 a.m. CDT Sunday, about 35,000 customers in Hinsdale and
five other west Chicago suburbs are to be returned to full phone
service for the first time since a Mother's Day fire at a Illinois
Bell switching station.
   ``There hasn't been a lot to laugh about on this one. ... But
the people who worked there can deservedly feel some pride,'' said
Bell spokesman Tim Bannon.
   Some residential and business service, as well as
``pass-through'' telephone traffic from Chicago, Joliet and
elsewhere, has returned in stages. All that remains to be done
Sunday is to transfer customers still dependent on damaged
equipment to new gear.
   ``It will mean no more static, clicking or buzzing, no more
broken connections or any of the other meddlesome things that were
upsetting customers,'' Bannon said.
   As many as 250 workers worked 12-hour shifts at the site since
the May 8 fire, ``but we've cut back on that number, and we've even
given most of these people some days off,'' he said.
   Hannah Beube already misses those Bell workers.
   Many of them patronized her business, ``The Monogram Shop,'' one
of the few that actually prospered during the outage.
   ``They had us make up T-shirts with their names and titles on
them on the front and Hinsdale '88 on the back,'' said Ms. Beube.
   Few other shopkeepers in this quiet community of 16,700 will
share her fond memories.
   ``Business was off by 60 (percent) or 70 percent for about two
weeks,'' said Maria Rendon, co-owner of Jane and Maria's Flower
Shop. ``The first few days we filled existing orders and we
thought, `Maybe this won't be so bad.'
   ``Then we ran out of work to do and we started reorganizing
things. ... Then we started getting upset.''
   Although Illinois Bell has promised rebates, several businesses
were angry enough to file lawsuits charging the utility was
negligent in failing to staff the switching station, which houses
computerized equipment to connect local and long-distance calls.
Firefighters reached the scene 82 minutes after an alarm registered
at Bell's Springfield monitoring station.
   And Illinois Attorney General Neil Hartigan has filed a
complaint with the Illinois Commerce Commission seeking to have
Bell pick up the tab for financial losses.
   Some local governments face bills as high as $65,000 for police
overtime pay and emergency equipment, ``but we've had to ... show a
police presence, and I think everybody understands that,'' O'Malley
said.
   Hinsdale officials and some downtown merchants plan a promotion
and party June 18 to celebrate.
   ``We're doing the T-shirts,'' said Ms. Beube. ``They'll be
Illinois Bell's colors _ blue, white and a little gold _ and across
the front they'll say: `The Bells are Ringing in Hinsdale.'''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
