<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Vietnam-MIAs     06-03 0332</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Vietnam-MIAs,0340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vietnam Checking 32 Reports On Missing Americans</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vietnam is investigating more than 30
cases that may involve Americans missing in action from the Vietnam
war, a U.S. military team that visited Hanoi said Friday.
   The team made the announcement after three days of talks with
Vietnamese government officials on accounting for a total of nearly
1,800 Americans missing from the war.
   ``The Vietnamese reported to us that they are now investigating
32 instances in which they have received information or remains
which could be associated with missing Americans,'' the team said
in a statement.
   ``Some of this investigative work is still in the preliminary
stages,'' it said. ``Consequently, no conclusions can be drawn at
this time from these investigations.''
   In the past, the Vietnamese often have followed up on such
announcements with returns of remains. The last return was on April
6, when Hanoi handed over 27 sets _ the largest such transfer since
U.S. forces withdrew from Vietnam in 1973.
   The American team said it provided specific information to the
Vietnamese and reviewed progress since technical specialists of the
two sides last met in March. The statement described this week's
meeting as ``positive and productive.''
   The five-man team was from the U.S. Joint Casualty Resolution
Center and the Army Central Identification Laboratory in Honolulu,
which are entrusted with resolving the fates of Americans missing
in foreign wars. It was led by Lt. Col. Paul Mather, head of the
resolution center's office in Bangkok.
   This week's meeting was the fifth since the two countries
reached an agreement in August under which Vietnam would accelerate
the MIA search and the United States would consider its requests
for humanitarian aid.
   Since then, Vietnam has complained that the Americans
misinterpreted the agreement and that it still wanted aid from the
U.S. government, not just from private agencies. The United States
has replied that it will not consider lifting an embargo on
official aid until Vietnamese troops leave Cambodia.
</TEXT>
