<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Lebanon-Amal     06-03 0265</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon-Amal,0272</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pro-Syrian Militia Disbanded in Beirut</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lebanese Justice Minister Nabih Berri on
Friday disbanded his Shiite Moslem Amal militia in all but southern
Lebanon after its defeat by pro-Iranian factions in Beirut's
southern slums, radio stations reported.
   They said Berri announced his decision at a news conference
barred to the international media and attended only by local
journalists at his heavily fortified house in Moslem west Beirut.
   The Syrian-armed Amal, Arabic for hope, suffered a crushing
defeat in south Beirut last month in a bloody three-week power
struggle with the fundamentalist Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party
of God.
   Police said 296 people were killed and 1,000 wounded before an
estimated 2,400 Syrian troops were deployed to enforce a truce.
   Berri was quoted as saying he dissolved the military wing of the
Amal movement throughout Lebanon except for the southern region of
the country, where the militia had gained exclusive control after
defeating Hezbollah in a four-day confrontation in April.
   He instructed all Amal militiamen in Beirut and the
Syrian-controlled Bekaa valley in east Lebanon to restrict their
activities to politics, banning them from carrying arms or engaging
in military confrontations, the radio reports said.
   He was quoted as saying the militia's central political office
in the Shiyah district of south Beirut would continue to function,
but all other military and other offices belonging to Amal would be
closed down.
   The exact size of the Amal faction is unknown. By police
estimates, 7,000 Amal militiamen battled Hezbollah, but the group
is said to be able to field an additional 3,000-4,000 men.
</TEXT>
