<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Afghanistan-Najib     06-03 0361</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghanistan-Najib,0370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Afghan President Leaves For Moscow</HEAD>
<HEAD>One name for Najib cq</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARLEEN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KASBUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Najib left Friday night for
Moscow with the selection of a new Afghan government still
undisclosed.
   Najib eight days ago announced his choice for a new prime
minister and instructed him to form a new Cabinet.
   The composition of a new government rests with the ruling
People's Democratic Party of Afghanistan. Its lack of haste in
announcing the ministers has prompted speculation in diplomatic
circles here that there are either divisions within the party or
efforts were being made to bring in outsiders who could at least
nominally be considered opposition members.
   Najib shook hands with members of his government and diplomats
during a red carpet send-off at Kabul airport, complete with
military band and honor guard with fixed bayonets.
   When asked by a reporter why the announcement of a Cabinet was
taking so long, the 41-year-old former secret police commander
said: ``It is not too late. After two days, everything will be
solved.''
   The president's departure was marked by the secrecy that
surrounds official government ceremonies in a country wracked by
war for the past decade. Although government officials had said
they expected Najib to fly to Moscow on Saturday morning, late
Friday afternoon they suddenly put out the word that the president
would leave within a few hours.
   The airport was guarded by Soviet troops as well as Afghan
security forces. The Soviets started withdrawing troops from
Afghanistan nearly three weeks ago, heralding the end of their
military intervention that began in 1979 to prop up a pro-Moscow
regime.
   Najib's choice for prime minister is Mohammad Hasan Sharq, who
is regarded as an amiable technocrat and a political survivor. He
has served as deputy prime minister and as minister for refugee
affairs to oversee the return of the more than 5 million Afghans
who fled the country during the war between Moslem guerrillas and
the Afghan army and its Soviet allies.
   Following his visit to Moscow, Najib was scheduled to travel to
New York to address the United Nations, followed by a visit to Cuba.
</TEXT>
