<HEAD>Panel Backs Extension of Aid to the Homeless</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Housing Banking sriday
approved a two-year extension of federal aid for the homeless.
   The measure, passed on a voice vote, would reauthorize the
Stewart B. McKinney Homeless Assistance Act and would provide
$717.5 million for the fisubcommittee on Fcal year ending Sept. 30, 1989.
The money
would go toward emergency shelters, food, health care, education
and job training.
   Although the bill originally authorized $735.9 million for
fiscal year 1990, an amendment changed the money figure to ``such
funds as necessary.''
   The banking subcommittee approved the entire bill but authorized
spending for only the housing provisions. It set that total at $297
million. Other House committees previously had voted on separate
portions of the measure.
   The Senate Banking Committee has approved $280 million for the
housing programs. No other committee in the Senate has acted yet on
the health and education, agriculture and veterans programs.
   Rep. Marge Roukema, R Utah,
site to be considered for the improved rockets, which are expected
to be introduced in the next decade.
   Hercules Inc. of Magna, Utah, together with Atlantic Research
Corp. of Gainesville, Va., proposed a site eight miles west of
Montgomery, Ala.
   At stake are a $1.2 billion plant and the employment a contract
would bring for a decade or more. The advanced rockets are expected
to arrive in the mid-1990s and replace the current boosters
completely in 1997.
