<FILEID>AP-NR-06-03-88 1634EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-BirthControlPills     06-03 0620</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Birth Control Pills,610</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>No Evidence of Ovarian Cysts From Multiple-Dosage Birth Control
Pills</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There is not enough evidence to determine
whether the latest generation of birth control pills contributes to
non-cancerous ovarian cysts as some doctors suspect, a Food and
Drug Administration panel concluded Friday.
   But the agency's outside advisory committee on fertility and
maternal health drugs said it backs further studies already ordered
by the FDA to gather more data on the question.
   A Los Angeles physician who was instrumental in first raising
the issue said following Friday's hearing that he never has claimed
to have more than anecdotal evidence _ from his own practice and
other doctors who contacted him.
   ``Obviously, we don't have the answers yet,'' Dr. James C.
Caillouette said in an interview. ``The data has not been developed
yet. I am pleased they (the committee) recognized there is a
potential problem.''
   The FDA already has instructed the three companies that sell the
multiple-dosage, or triphasic, birth control pills to undertake
studies to determine whether there is a higher incidence of
functional ovarian cysts among women taking the new type pills.
   None of the three has filed its study plans with the FDA, but
such Phase IV studies typically involve post-market monitoring of
the medical records of large numbers of patients _ perhaps
thousands _ using a particular drug.
   Dr. Ridgely C. Bennett of the FDA told the advisory panel the
agency also was in the first stages of a larger study looking at
California Medicaid recipients taking different types of birth
control pills.
   There is no indication when any of those studies will be
completed.
   Meanwhile, there is no change in the status of the four
triphasic pills, which have carved out about a third of the total
birth control pill market since their introduction in 1984.
   FDA figures presented at the hearing showed that one triphasic
alone _ Ortho-Novum 7@7@7 _ is the No. 1 seller, with 17.6 percent
of the market as of last March. The other triphasics are Triphasil,
with 9.5 percent market share; Tri-Norinyl, with 3.6 percent; and
Tri-Levlen, with 2.6 percent.
   In all, it is estimated that more than 50 million American women
take some type of oral contraceptive.
   Caillouette, a professor of gynecology at the University of
Southern California School of Medicine, said he remains convinced
that the single-dose pills are safer than the multiphasic versions.
   ``I still have strong feelings that we have pills that in my
experience are safer than the multiphasics,'' he said.
   A triphasic comes in three different colors denoting their
different dose levels. A woman taking such a prescription would
take one color pill on certain days of the month and the other
colors on other days.
   Representatives for the three U.S. companies that market
triphasics _ Ortho Pharmaceutical Corp., Wyeth Laboratories Inc.
and Syntex Corp. _ all say they are convinced of the pills' safety,
but are cooperating with the FDA-ordered studies.
   The other three major U.S. distributors of birth control pills
sell only single-dose versions.
   Caillouette became concerned about two years ago when he had
seven patients develop ovarian cysts within four months and
realized he had prescriped the new multiphasic for each of them.
   When he returned them to higher-dose monophasic prescriptions,
the cysts went away, he said.
   Since publishing a paper on his own experience in a medical
journal last summer, Caillouette said he has received similar
accounts from other doctors and now knows of 74 cases of ovarian
cysts that may be linked to multiphasic birth control pills.
   Although not life-threatening, ovarian cysts sometimes have to
be removed surgically and some women lose an ovary in the process.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880603-0205 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-03-88 2014EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SchoolShootings     06-03 0561</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-School Shootings,0576</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>College Student Denies Being A Hero In School Shootings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENDA C. COLEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HIGHLAND PARK, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A young man who was wounded by a
gun-toting baby sitter on a shooting spree after he tried to calm
and disarm her said Friday he was neither angry nor fearful because
his assailant was ``a sick individual.''
   ``It was a freak incident,'' said Philip Andrew, 20, at a
Highland Park Hospital news conference. It was his first public
comment on the shooting two weeks ago, when 30-year-old Laurie Dann
went on a rampage in his hometown of Winnetka, a suburb north of
Chicago.
   Ms. Dann burst into the home of the Andrew family, whom she did
not know, on May 20 after shooting six children, one fatally, at
the nearby Hubbard Woods Elementary School. After shooting Andrew,
Ms. Dann fatally shot herself while police surrounded the home.
   ``The only way to really explain it is that this was a sick
individual,'' said Andrew, who was in fair condition recovering
from a chest wound. ``You can't make sense of it. ... The rest of
the people that come into my house aren't going to be shooting at
me.''
   Rep. John Porter, R-Ill., issued a statement Friday calling
Andrew ``an authentic hero'' for trying to disarm Ms. Dann. Andrew
was to have started working this week as an intern in Porter's
office in the suburb of Deerfield.
   The University of Illinois senior, a history major and swim team
captain, turned aside the accolade.
   ``I wasn't forcing myself to do anything,'' he said. ``I think I
acted just naturally in that situation. I don't think I did
anything really heroic.''
   In addition to Andrew, one of the five wounded children remains
hospitalized.
   Andrew was in the kitchen with his mother when Ms. Dann burst in
the back door, saying she had been sexually assaulted and had shot
her assailant.
   In the 40 to 50 minutes while she was in their house, Andrew
said he and his parents tried to calm Ms. Dann and persuade her to
call police. He said they also tried to persuade her to give up her
guns.
   ``We continued to talk to her. I explained to her that I was
familiar with the system and what was going to happen and I told
her I was going to stay with her. I was close enough to put my arms
around her. I was touching her,'' Andrew said.
   ``It was going through my head that I could take the gun from
her, but I thought it was best at this point that she just give it
up. And I thought ... she would,'' he said.
   Andrew finally decided to take one of the guns when Ms. Dann set
them both on a table, but she became agitated and more possessive
about the other weapon, he said.
   He said his mother left to warn his sisters not to enter the
house, and to call police.
   Then Andrew and his father decided they would leave, too, but
Ms. Dann raised her remaining pistol and told him to stay, he said.
   Then she may have seen a police officer, Andrew said, because
she suddenly turned around and shot him.
   Andrew said he didn't learn until after surgery that Ms. Dann
had fired shots in the nearby elementary school.
</TEXT>
