<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TeacherKilling     06-03 0224</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Teacher Killing,0227</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Teen Draws 206 Years for Killing Teacher, Wounding Three in School</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LEWISTOWN, Mont. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 16-year-old boy was sentenced Friday
to 206 years in prison for killing a high school teacher and
wounding three other people in a shooting he said stemmed from a
failing grade in French.
   District Judge Peter Rapkoch imposed consecutive 100-year terms
on 16-year-old Kristofor Hans for the murder of substitute teacher
Henrietta Smith and the attempted murder of Lewiston High School
Assistant Principal John Mofatt. He then added three years to each
for use of a weapon. Two students also were wounded in the December
1986 shootings.
   Besides the two consecutive 100-year terms, Rapkoch sentenced
the youth to concurrent 10-year sentences for each of the assault
charges involving the other students, who were hit with bullet
fragments. Rapkoch also added three years to each count for use of
a weapon.
   Hans, who pleaded guilty, said he intended to kill his French
teacher, Lavonne Simonfy, because she was giving him a failing
grade. That would have meant, under terms of an agreement with his
separated parents, that he had to leave his mother's home in
Lewistown and go to live with his father in Casper, Wyo.
   Smith was filling in that day for Simonfy and was shot as she
opened the door of Simonfy's classroom.
</TEXT>
