<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Steiger     06-03 0595</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Steiger,0610</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Congressman From Arizona Gets Probation</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Mecham Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY LOPEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former U.S. Rep. Sam Steiger on Friday was
placed on four years' probation and fined $5,480 for pressuring a
parole board member over an administrative matter while working for
then-Gov. Evan Mecham.
   Judge Ronald Reinstein of Maricopa County Superior Court also
ordered him to perform 700 hours of community service work and
suggested Steiger, who is well known for criticizing lawyers,
consider spending some of those hours on Arizona Bar Association
projects.
   Steiger, 59, was convicted April 7 of theft by extortion in
threatening Board of Pardons and Paroles member Ron Johnson over a
personnel vote. He could have been sentenced to up to five years in
prison.
   Steiger claimed it was simply hardball politics, but jurors at
the seven-day trial agreed with the prosecution that Steiger
threatened Johnson's part-time job as a justice of the peace ``in
order to steal his vote'' on retention of the board's executive
director.
   Steiger clashed repeatedly with Attorney General Bob Corbin
while a special assistant to Mecham, who has since been impeached.
   He told the judge he was frustrated by problems at the parole
board and could not say he regretted his actions even though
``prudence and precedence would dictate that I should be
remorseful.''
   Referring to interviews with Corbin investigators, he said: ``I
lied to the attorney general for the same reason that I would lie
to a stick-up man in an alley who asked me if I had any money. .. .
What is important in this matter is that it is my absolute, honest
conviction that the attorney general singled me out for elimination
from state government because I was critical of a serious problem
in that office.''
   Reinstein said he was impressed by the more than 170 letters on
Steiger's behalf and said he did not believe Steiger was motivated
by political, financial or personal gain.
   But he said Steiger ``clearly broke the law,'' abused his power
and was trying to ``deflect your obvious wrong in this case'' on
others.
   ``Frankly, Mr. Steiger, you came off as a bully,'' Reinstein
said, citing conversations that the parole board member secretly
recorded.
   Steiger, a former five-term congressman, rancher and newspaper
columnist has taken on his colleagues, neighbors, business
associates, former wife, police, highway officials and burros in a
colorful career.
   Steiger began his political career at 28 as a Republican, when
he won the first of two terms in the state Senate from a 10-1
Democratic district.
   ``The only reason a Republican had never been elected was
because nobody good had ever run,'' he said later. ``Everybody
laughed. After all, who's gonna vote for a New York Jew
horse-trader who was a Republican on top of everything else?''
   In a 1968 television interview he referred to some of his
congressional colleagues as ``dumb clucks I wouldn't hire to push a
wheelbarrow.'' In 1975 he shot and killed two burros that he said
attacked him.
   In 1979, Steiger pointed a rifle at a man who tried to collect a
debt at his ranch. In 1982, he was convicted of disorderly conduct
after directing ``abrasive and abusive'' language toward a Highway
Patrol officer.
   In 1986, he repainted a crosswalk that the state highway
department had eliminated in downtown Prescott and later beat a
criminal-damage charge in the case.
   As a special assistant to Mecham the next year, he was in charge
of overseeing the highway department. The crosswalk was painted
again, this time by highway crews.
</TEXT>
