<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PoliceCommissioner     06-03 0469</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Police Commissioner,0483</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Williams Replaces Tucker As Philadelphia Police Commissioner</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE LINDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Deputy police commissioner Willie L.
Williams is the first black to win the department's top job, with
the 24-year police veteran pledging Friday to carry on reforms
begun by outgoing Commissioner Kevin Tucker.
   Williams, 44, will take over next week when Tucker's resignation
becomes effective. He said he would prepare the department ``to
enter the 21st century.''
   ``We will also have honor and integrity as the cornerstone of
our every working hour,'' Williams said at a news conference where
Mayor W. Wilson Goode announced his appointment.
   Tucker resigned last week after a 2{-year tenure marked by
efforts to improve the credibility of a police force rocked by
extortion scandals in recent years. He had suggested Williams and
six other candidates for the job, Goode said.
   ``The tenure of Kevin Tucker has represented the turning around
of this department and the appointment of Willie Williams
represents a continuation of the reform of the department,'' Goode
said.
   Goode, the city's first black mayor, had said the new
commissioner would come from within the department.
   Budget cuts have prompted speculation of layoffs in the police
department, and Williams told reporters ``the patrol force on the
street will not be cut. That is our first priority.''
   City Council President Joseph Coleman called the appointment
``magnificent. He is a good man and is very qualified.''
   Robert Hurst, president of the Fraternal Order of Police Lodge
5, said the union was pleased, ``especially that the mayor named
someone from within who had worked his way up through the ranks.''
   Williams, who started with the 6,700-member department in 1964
as a park guard, was chosen by Tucker as a deputy commissioner. In
that role, he was responsible for the operations of the
administrative, training and staff services bureaus.
   Both Williams and Goode said the major task facing the police
department is the fight against drugs and that the battle would be
stepped up.
   Goode, asked if appointing a black police commissioner would
help the image of police in the black community, responded that
``race was never a factor in this appointment. ... I only sought to
find the very best person.''
   He acknowledged, however, that in the black community, which
comprises about 40 percent of the city's population, Williams will
be able to help turn around negative views of police.
   Tucker, 47, a former head of the local U.S. Secret Service
office, succeeded Gregore Sambor, who resigned in the wake of the
fatal May 1985 confrontation between police and the radical group
MOVE and was commissioner during federal investigations of
extortion by police officers.
   Tucker took over a morale-shattered department that was reeling
from extortion convictions against 34 officers or former officers,
including a deputy commissioner.
</TEXT>
