<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Brazil-Hostages     06-03 0312</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brazil-Hostages,0321</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bank Robbers Threaten To Kill Hostages</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two men who muffed a bank robbery
in a southern town threatened Friday to start killing their 12
remaining hostages if their demands for money and an escape car
were not met, police reported.
   Four other hostages slipped out of the bank through a bathroom
window early Friday, said officials in Goioere, a town of 30,000
about 550 miles southwest of Rio de Janeiro in Parana state. Ten
others were released after the men holed up in the bank Thursday
afternoon.
   Police chief Guaraci Abreu said the two men were young ``and
very professional. They know what they want.''
   He said the gunmen had doubled their cash demand to the
equivalent of $100,000 and wanted a car without license plates.
``Otherwise they said they would start killing hostages one by one,
and I believe them,'' he said by telephone.
   Justice Secretary Antonio Lopes Noronha, heading a negotiating
team, suspended payment of the ransom even though the money had
been collected from other banks.
   ``We won't try to storm the bank because we do not want to risk
hostages' lives, but we won't pay either. We'll just sit tight and
wait,'' he told reporters.
   The bandits, each armed with two revolvers, entered the Bank of
Brazil branch minutes before closing Thursday afternoon and
overpowered two guards, then the alarm sounded and police arrived
moments later.
   After the guards and 24 other employees were taken hostage,
about 150 state troopers and municipal police surrounded the bank.
   On Thursday night the gunmen released the two guards and seven
female bank tellers. They also freed a sick man.
   Bank holdups have increased in Brazil, where inflation is
running at a projected annual rate of 600 percent. Police often
have allowed robbers to flee in order to save the lives of hostages.
</TEXT>
