<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UN-Disarmament     06-03 0541</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Disarmament,0553</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cuba Gives Faint Praise to Reagan, an `Implacable Enemy'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cuba gave President Reagan faint praise
Friday for his arms treaty with the Soviet Union, but also said he
is an ``implacable enemy'' and demanded the U.S. Navy base at
Guantanamo be returned.
   King Hussein of Jordan told delegates to the special General
Assembly session on disarmament that Israel poses ``a terrible
threat'' to the Middle East and the world with nuclear weapons.
Israel neither confirms nor denies reports that it has nuclear arms.
   Cuban Vice President Carlos Rafael Rodriguez assailed
Washington's military policies and economic embargo of his
Caribbean nation. But Rodriguez also said this week's U.S.-Soviet
summit in Moscow and the treaty on eliminating intermediate-range
nuclear missiles represents ``an auspicious sign'' for the U.N.
session.
   ``We have the possibility of seeing a profound change in
international political relations,'' and the time when some U.S.
leaders thought their ends ``could be achieved through a policy of
force and arrogance has given way to laborious, systematic
negotiations,'' Rodriguez said.
   He said a positive response from the United States is required
to accompany Soviet initiatives and the international clamor for
peace. ``And the latest events seem to indicate that the Reagan
administration is heading in that direction.
   ``If Mr. Reagan takes the road to peace, no matter how
vacillating his manner or slow his steps, Cuba ... would not .. .
fail to recognize that positive attitude on his part,'' Rodriguez
said.
   He added, however, that Cuba still ``considers him (Reagan) its
implacable adversary, cannot forget his threats and is not yet free
of his economic and political pressures.''
   Rodriguez said military bases maintained by foreign powers
``constitute a virtual rental of national sovereignty of countries
eaten away by poverty.''
   Guantanamo is ``the most intolerable example'' of foreign
military presence, he said, adding: ``The U.S. occupiers imposed it
on our country and although our people are opposed, it is still
there and an insult to our national sovereignty.
   ``Cuba has not accepted it, cannot accept it and will never
accept it. That part of our national territory should be returned
to us.''
   The United States leased the base area on Guantanamo Bay for 99
years in 1898. President Fidel Castro's government refuses the
nominal annual rent of $5,000.
   Rodriguez said Cuba has no offensive weapons and wants only the
minimum armaments necessary to guarantee its own peace, but must
make its defense plans ``taking into account the uninterrupted
hostility of the nearby United States.''
   That has ``forced us to turn the war waged by the army into a
`war of all the people,' involving old people, housewives and
children,'' he said.
   In a speech read by Ambassador Abdullah Salah of Jordan, King
Hussein recommended strong U.N. measures to keep the Middle East
free of nuclear weapons and halt Israel's alleged nuclear arms
program.
   ``The situation has become more dangerous since Israel
introduced nuclear weapons to the Middle East,'' Salah said. ``It
has been building up its nuclear capabilities since the 1950s and
is continuing to develop and expand them so that it now represents
a terrible threat not only to the Middle East but to the world as a
whole.''
</TEXT>
