<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Reagan-Britain Bjt 1stLd-Writethru 06-03 0953</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Britain, Bjt, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0683,900</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Even For Close Friends, An Emotional Farewell</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Adds 5 grafs with Thatcher-Kinnock comment, edits throughout
to tighten</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Even for close friends, it was an emotional
farewell.
   Ronald Reagan, ending what was probably his last presidential
visit to Britain, quoted poetry Friday, joked about his age,
recalled Anglo-American alliances in war and peace and lavished
praise on Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher.
   And in the splendid setting of London's ancient Guildhall, seat
of city government for 1,000 years, Mrs. Thatcher responded, ``You
have restored faith in the American dream.''
   From red double-decker buses, the banks of the River Thames and
behind crowd barriers near the Guildhall, Londoners waved to the
U.S. president as his motorcade wound through the capital toward
the end of a 26-hour stopover after the Moscow summit.
   Eight British theater celebrities, including actress Julie
Christie, staged a demonstration against U.S. policy in Latin
America.
   But the only serious booing came from a crowd that had waited as
long as two hours outside the Guildhall for the arrival of Reagan
and his wife, Nancy _ and had their view blocked at the last moment
by a security van driven across the entrance to the courtyard.
   The 77-year-old Reagan delivered a speech focused on East-West
relations before an audience of 500 red-robed city dignitaries,
political leaders and diplomats.
   Yet, more than an political event, the occasion was a high point
in the special relationship between Britain and America, which has
flourished under the two conservative leaders who have held office
through the 1980s.
   The audience gave Reagan a standing ovation and, replying to his
speech, Mrs. Thatcher mixed praised for a political ally with
affection for a departing friend.
   ``Your personal courage, your gentle humor and your spirit of
optimism are all part of the special quality that you have brought
to the presidency,'' said Mrs. Thatcher, 62, into her third term
and expected to run for a fourth.
   ``Above all, and in this you have done the greatest possible
service not only to your own people but to free people everywhere,
you have restored faith in the American dream.''
   To a blast from gold-uniformed trumpeters, Reagan was escorted
into the Guildhall's Great Hall where towering statues of military
heroes Horatio Nelson and the Duke of Wellington are set amid
medieval stained-glass windows. The Stars and Stripes and the red
and white flag of St. George, England's patron saint, hung from
balconies.
   The Guildhall has been the scene of 16th century trials of
traitors, pleas to kings and Parliament, receptions for emperors _
and addresses by American presidents Ulysses S. Grant and Woodrow
Wilson.
   ``I wonder if you can imagine what it is for an American to
stand in this place,'' said Reagan.
   ``Back in the States, we are terribly proud of anything more
than a few hundred years old; some even see my election to the
presidency as America's attempt to show our European cousins that
we too have a regard for antiquity,'' he added, to laughter.
   After the jokes he concentrated on new hopes for peace and
another arms control treaty. And he intertwined history and
anecdotes to depict Britain: the country that produced Winston
Churchill, writer Evelyn Waugh and a pub-keeper who, hearing the
visiting Reagan's accent 40 years ago, recalled fondly the World
War II GIs sent to Britain ``from a place called Ioway.''
   Turning to Mrs. Thatcher, he said, ``At this hour in our
history, Prime Minister, the entire world salutes you and your
gallant people and gallant nation.''
   British opposition Labor Party leader Neil Kinnock, who
advocates unilateral disarmament, including shutting down U.S.
nuclear bases, and who describes Mrs. Thatcher as ``Reagan's
poodle,'' stared ahead expressionlessly from the rows of VIPs as
the president denounced one-sided disarmers.
   Kinnock said later of Reagan's tributes to Mrs. Thatcher, ``It
was a generous and gentlemanly thing to do. But I think that's
about where it stops.''
   Both Reagan and Mrs. Thatcher started out in office denouncing
the Soviet Union and both changed their minds through arms control
deals and Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev's new policies of
openness. Both spoke Friday of the dawn of new era of hope between
East and West.
   Reagan concluded, ```Come, my friends,' as it was said of old by
Tennyson, `it is not too late to seek a newer world.'''
   Responded Mrs. Thatcher, ``Thank you Mr. President. Thank you
for the summit, thank you for your presidency, thank you for your
testament of belief, and God bless America.''
   Mrs. Thatcher said later that she hoped Gorbachev would visit
Britain again in the spring or summer next year. In an interview
with Independent Television News, the prime minister said, ``He is
willing to do it and it is a question of what is the best timing.
... He will be very preoccupied with the changes going on in the
Soviet Union.''
   Kinnock later praised Reagan in an Independent Television News
interview: ``He deserves very full credit from our generation and
from future generations for making a positive response to
Gorbachev's initiatives.
   Asked whether he considered Reagan a great president, Kinnock
replied: ``Yes. I think Mrs Thatcher may be engaging in a mutual
match of hyperbole at the moment but it certainly is a highly
creditable performance in order to begin an era of nuclear
disarmament.
   ``She has over these nearly eight years now followed every twist
and turn and U-turn of American policy,'' he added. ``The least she
could expect is a public thank you from the president.
   ``She earned it, she deserved it from him and he gave it, which
was the presidential and gentlemanly thing to do.''
</TEXT>
