<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Soviet-Party     06-03 0629</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Party,0649</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reform Advocates Put Back on Ballot by Moscow Party Leadership</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Moscow party leadership put prominent
advocates of Mikhail S. Gorbachev's reforms back on the ballot
Friday for a key national Communist Party conference, the official
Soviet news agency Tass reported.
   It was a clear defeat for party conservatives.
   The Moscow party bureau sidestepped a decision of lower party
organizations in the capital, which had not submitted the names of
the reform advocates as candidates for the 19th Party Conference,
scheduled to open June 28.
   The conference is supposed to bolster Gorbachev's reforms by
approving a document published a week ago that outlines radical
changes to remove remnants of Stalinism from Soviet politics and
law. But reforms could be in doubt if conservatives are predominant
among delegates.
   Tass said Gorbachev, the party general secretary, took part in
the Moscow committee meeting, but did not say if he spoke in favor
of the restored candidacies.
   It did not say if those whose names were restored had been
elected, but the Moscow party committee would be unlikely to buck a
decision made by its supreme executive body, the Moscow party
bureau.
   Sociologist Tatyana Zaslavskaya, a leading proponent of
perestroika _ Gorbachev's program of economic and social
restructuring _ assailed conservatives for maneuvering to block the
election of reformers as conference delegates.
   ``The most pronounced advocates of perestroika were not
selected,'' she told a news conference.
   Zaslavskaya had failed to receive enough votes to stand as a
candidate for one of the 319 delegate spots to be filled from
Moscow. But the Moscow party bureau ordered her name to be put
before the Moscow party committee as a delegate candidate, Tass
said.
   Other prominent perestroika advocates whose names were restored
to the ballot included movie director Elem Klimov, economist
Nikolai Shmelev, playwright Mikhail Shatrov and Moscow News editor
Yegor Yakovlev.
   Vitaly Korotich, editor of the weekly Ogonyok, said this week
that Friday's meeting might revise some delegate selections to
include reformers like himself taken off the slate in
pre-conference maneuvering.
   Tass said Friday night that Korotich was elected as a conference
delegate from the regional party committee in the Ukrainian Black
Sea port city of Kherson.
   Zaslavskaya, Korotich, economist Abel Aganbegyan, historian Yuri
Afanasyev and writer Fyodor Burlatsky were among popular reformers
voted in as party delegates from their place of work, but axed at
the next level, the equivalent of precincts.
   Dissident Andrei D. Sakharov told a news conference this week
that Gorbachev should be given time and trust to continue his
pioneering reforms.
   ``I'm very much concerned with the anti-democratic actions and
the role the district party committees are playing in the elections
to the 19th Party Conference,'' Sakharov said. ``This is a direct
attack on perestroika.''
   Tass quoted Moscow party boss Lev N. Zaikov as telling the
Friday meeting that the party leadership decided to put the
additional names on the ballot because Moscow party organizations
and work collectives wanted to choose only their own members as
delegates.
   Zaikov said party leaders in the capital wanted the delegation
``to represent the interests of the city as a whole.''
   Tass said Friday's meeting elected 319 ``champions of
perestroika'' to represent Moscow at the conference, but identified
only a small number _ Gorbachev; Zaikov; the No. 2 man in the
Kremlin, Yegor K. Ligachev, and four other members of the national
leadership.
   The delegate battle has been the talk of Moscow for days, as
state-run media and even street protests brought an internal party
battle over reform into the open.
   According to party sources, there will be roughly one delegate
for every 3,800 Communist Party members at the conference, the 19th
in party history but the first since 1941.
</TEXT>
