<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Aspin     06-03 0282</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Aspin,270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Aspin: U.S. Should Have Used Military Force To Oust Noriega</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States should have used military
force to remove Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega from power in Panama
and missed its opportunity to ``go in there and snatch him,'' the
chairman of the House Armed Services Committee said Friday.
   ``I think it may be too late to use force now because he's
moving around,'' said Rep. Les Aspin, D-Wis.
   ``You don't know where he is ... what we should have done at the
very beginning was use military force _ not blowing a lot of people
up, but to go in there and snatch him and take him out.''
   Aspin was interviewed on John McLaughlin's ``One on One''
syndicated television program, taped for showing this weekend.
   Aspin answered affirmatively when McLaughlin asked whether he
favored ``surgically'' removing Noriega, who has been indicted by
the United States on drug charges.
   ``You can't do it so easily now, because they're on their
guard,'' Aspin said. ``He's got guards, he's protected, he's moving
around. ... At least if you know where he is, it's a whole
different problem. And I think that's where we are now.''
   Aspin also said that the medium-range missile treaty on which
President Reagan and Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev this week
exchanged ratification documents ``is a small step, but ... a small
step in the wrong direction.''
   The Wisconsin congressman says he opposes that treaty because
while it eliminates some nuclear weapon, it leaves an imbalance of
conventional arms.
   But he called the U.S.-Soviet summit in Moscow a success because
Reagan called attention to human rights issues by talking to
dissidents and visiting monasteries.
</TEXT>
