<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Yugoslavia     06-03 0257</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Yugoslavia,0265</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cotton Mill Workers Strike,</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSTAR, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 2,000 workers struck
Yugoslavia's largest cotton mill Friday to protest a government
austerity program that cuts wages, the state-run Tanjug news agency
reported.
   Also Friday, the official Slovenian Socialist Youth Union
strongly protested the arrest of leading activist and journalist
Janez Jansa and said widespread protests could follow.
   Jansa had reported alleged plans for a military coup in Slovenia
to quell dissent in that northern republic. An army prosecutor said
Friday that Janez was arrested Tuesday in Ljubljana on suspicion of
revealing a military secret.
   The strikers, mostly women, stopped work at the Djuro Salaj
cotton mill in Mostar, central Yugoslavia, after hearing that their
wages will be slashed by 14.2 percent this month.
   Tanjug later reported that about 1,000 strikers returned to work
after a meeting with management.
   The workers decided to send a protest letter to the government
``warning of grave consequences'' resulting from the wage cuts, the
news agency said.
   The remaining workers balked at having their salaries cut from
the present average of $130 a month and continued the strike, said
Tanjug.
   The average salary in Yugoslavia is $155 a month.
   The government last Saturday began a major austerity program
that included substantial price increases, wage cuts of up to 30
percent and a 23.9 percent devaluation of the dinar, the national
currency.
   The measures are designed to eventually curb communist
Yugoslavia's 170 percent inflation rate and help in repaying a $21
billion foreign debt by introducing a more market-oriented economy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
