<DOCNO> AP880603-0224 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-03-88 2027EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UNBudget-Soviets     06-03 0527</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN Budget-Soviets,0539</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Say More of Their UN Workers Will Be Permanent Civil
Servants</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union says more of its U.N.
staff members will become permanent civil servants, which addresses
a problem the United States has cited in withholding dues payments.
   Soviet practice has been for its nationals on the U.N. staff to
serve five years or less. U.S. officials say that makes them
inclined to favor Soviet policy over an impartial U.N. agenda
because they will be returning to the Soviet civil service.
   A United Nations staff member said Friday that the international
organization will be broke by the end of September unless new funds
are obtained. President Reagan needs to certify that U.S.
objections have been met before $44 million not paid for 1987 can
be released for the U.N.
   The staff member, speaking on condition his name not be used,
said that another solution would be for the Soviets to pay the
second half of their annual assessment early. The Soviet Union
usually pays in October.
   Vladimir Petrovsky, a Soviet deputy foreign minister, told a
Moscow news conference ``the most competent and experience Soviet
members of the Secretariat will ... be able to serve on the basis
of permanent contracts.''
   An English translation of Petrovsky's remarks, delivered May 19,
was made available to The Associated Press at the United Nations on
Friday. The U.N. information office in Moscow sent the text to New
York.
   The United States has withheld $44 million of the $144 million
it allocated for dues in 1987 partly because it said Soviet U.N.
personnel should be independent international civil servants.
America's total assessment is 25 percent of the budget.
   On Friday, the U.N. staff member called Petrovsky's comment
``the $44 million paragraph'' in the news conference text, which
covered such other topics as U.S.-Soviet relations and the current
special General Assembly session on disarmament.
   An American official said privately the Petrovsky statement
appeared to remove the last substantial U.S. objection to paying.
   ``It removes a lot of doubts,'' agreed Sergei Komolov, press
attache for the Soviet delegation to the disarmament session.
   Komolov suggested the announcement in Moscow went unnoticed
because few foreign correspondents attended the briefing. ``The
main press center was being renovated for the summit and perhaps
many reporters were not familiar with the room where the news
conference was held,'' he said.
   Reagan and Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev met in Moscow this
week, their fourth summit.
   Both the U.S. official and the U.N. staff member said the other
two conditions for releasing the money are being satisfied _ a 15
percent cut in the Secretariat staff, and a greater voice in the
budget process for large contributors.
   Staff cuts are being implemented and last year a budget review
committee was created that must approve the budget by consensus.
The United States is a member of the committee, giving it an
effective veto of budget decisions.
   Congress imposed the three conditions last year as part of the
U.S. budget appropriation. Reagan is required to give Congress an
annual evaluation of progress toward the goals.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
