<2ND_LINE>AM-Democratic Platform,180</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Democrats Focus On Family Issues, Call GOP Vulnerable</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Democratic Party can regain the
presidency in November if its national platform stresses family
issues, the head of the party's platform committee said Friday.
   At a forum on issues affecting families, Democratic Gov. James
Blanchard of Michigan, temporary chairman of the 163-member
platform committee, said the party should capitalize on an issue he
says Republicans have neglected.
   ``We have a good record of family issues ... (while) the
Republicans have spent the last eight years trying to regulate our
bedrooms and tell us what prayers to pray,'' Blanchard said.
   Republicans, he said, have gutted programs affecting low-income
families, the young and the elderly, while Americans see a need for
such programs.
   However, Blanchard added, Democrats must convince voters such
initiatives are financially feasible.
   Friday's forum was the last of four held this week on issues the
committee felt were key to winning the election. Earlier regional
forums dealt with jobs and the economy, education and youth, and
foreign policy and defense.
