<FILEID>AP-NR-06-03-88 2108EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Denmark     06-03 0256</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Denmark,0262</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Schlueter Resolves Deadlock, Forms New Government</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COPENHAGEN, Denmark (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Poul Schlueter
resolved a dispute over policy toward NATO and formed a new
minority government Friday, ending a three-week crisis created by
inconclusive elections.
   He presented the 21-member Cabinet to Queen Margrethe II at
Amalienborg Palace. The coalition includes Schlueter's Conservative
Party, which has 35 seats in the 179-member Parliament; the
Liberals with 22 and the Social Liberals with 10.
   Schlueter called his coalition ``the best foundation in a
difficult situation for stability in domestic and foreign
affairs.'' Denmark has not had a majority government since 1971.
   The way was cleared for the coalition when the parties agreed on
a method of reminding Denmark's North Atlantic Treaty Organization
allies of its 31-year-old policy barring nuclear weapons, Danish
radio said.
   Schlueter had refused to carry out an April 14 resolution by
Parliament requiring the government to notify visiting warships of
the policy, and called the May 10 election as a referendum on the
issue.
   Schlueter would not say how he resolved the matter but told
reporters he would explain it Tuesday in a speech to Parliament.
   The radio said he chose the ``Norwegian model,'' under which
Denmark's non-nuclear status would be mentioned in diplomatic
contacts before a port call but notification would not be sent to
captains as ships entered the harbor.
   The United States and Britain, the two nuclear powers in the
alliance military command, had said notifying ships might
compromise the policy of not acknowledging the locations of nuclear
arms.
</TEXT>
