<1ST_LINE>r i AM-GulfRdp     06-03 0431</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf Rdp,0443</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cypriot-Flag Freighter Reported Released By Iranians</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Cypriot freighter was reported to have
been freed by Iran on Friday and allowed to continue its voyage the
day after it was boarded and seized, apparently on suspicion of
carrying war-related cargo.
   The 10,000-ton motor vessel Vevey left the Iranian port Bandar
Abbas at midday and was ``proceeding normally'' to its destinations
in the Persian Gulf, according to the Lloyd's Shipping Intelligence
Unit in London.
   The brief report, which Lloyd's said was provided by the
shipowners, gave no details.
   An Iranian frigate tentatively identified by U.S. naval
officials as the 1,540-ton Alborz intercepted the Vevey on Thursday
as it entered the gulf, bound for Saudi Arabia and Kuwait with a
listed cargo of Italian marble chips and powder.
   Iranian naval personnel boarded the ship and forced it o
accompany the frigate to Bandar Abbas, site of a major Iranian
naval base, Lloyd's said.
   Iran frequently stops commercial vessels in the southern gulf to
search them for contraband or military-related cargo bound for
Iraq. It also sometimes takes the ships into custody for further
investigation.
   Such boardings are legal under international maritime law in
wartime circumstances, such as the gulf, where Iraq and Iran have
been at war for almost eight years.
   In seizing the Vevey, Iran appeared to risk a confrontation with
the U.S. Navy missile cruiser Vincennes, which was on patrol two
miles away.
   U.S. officers said the cruiser could have intervened if the
Vevey's captain decided he was being attacked and radioed for help.
   The officers would not speculate whether the Iranians were
purposely trying to defy the Vincennes, a high-tech Aegis-type
cruiser on its first patrol after arriving in the gulf last weekend.
   Under expanded rules of engagement that became effective a month
ago, U.S. warships can intervene in attacks on non-U.S. flag ships
provided the ships ask for help and are in international waters,
outside the ``war exclusion zones'' declared by Iran and Iraq.
   Iranian gunboats have conducted four raids on neutral shipping
since the new policy took effect, but in areas where patrolling
U.S. warships were too far away to have intervened if asked.
   The Belgian government announced Friday in Brussels it was
recalling one of its two warships in the gulf, the mine sweeper
command-support vessel Zinnia. That will dissolve a Belgian-Dutch
unit formed in September.
   Belgium and the Netherlands each sent three mine-sweeping craft
to the gulf as part of a multinational effort to clear the waterway
of mines laid by Iran.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
