<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Pope-Italy     06-03 0374</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pope-Italy,0387</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pope Begins Five-Day Trip To Leftist-Run Italian Region</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PIERO VALSECCHI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MODENA, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II on Friday began a
five-day tour of Emilia-Romagna, Italy's ``Red Region'' that has
been led by communist governments or leftist coalitions since 1946.
   In an address to residents at his first stop in the industrial
town of Carpi, the pontiff denouced ``the fall of moral values.''
   He also decried what he called a crisis in the basic aspects of
life such as ``the stability of the family ... a generous and
responsible fatherhood and motherhood ... and the respect of human
life at any stage.''
   He called for a return to ``ancient Christian traditions'' and
for giving up materialism and hedonism.
   The provincial capitals of Modena, Piacenza, Reggio Emilia,
Parma and Bologna in north-central Italy are on the pope's agenda.
They have the highest per-capita income in the nation.
   But they are also have increasing drug problems and the lowest
birth rates in Italy and are among the cities with the highest
number of abortions and suicides, according to recent regional
statistics.
   John Paul flew by helicopter to Carpi from the airport at
Bologna and later traveled to Modena, where he was welcomed by
communist Mayor Alfonsina Rinaldi.
   The 40-year-old mayor, in her address to the pope, said ``women
of Modena are increasingly feeling the need of a new sensibility,
to harmonize progress and respect of life.''
   During his 73rd trip to Italian districts outside of Rome, the
Polish-born pontiff will visit the headquarters of the famed
Ferrari car-racing team at Fiorano.
   He is scheduled to meet company workers and formula-one race
drivers Michele Alboreto and Gerhard Berger and have a private
meeting with the company chief, Enzo Ferrari, and his family.
   Company sources said the pope may unveil a new F-1 racer that
could make its debut in the formula-one world championship
competition in July.
   Ferrari, Italy's car-racing pioneer, celebrated his 90th
birthday in January.
   He has been known as an agnostic and made no secret of his
dislike of the Vatican, which had criticized the company because of
the deaths of some Ferrari drivers in racing accidents.
   ``It's an old and forgotten controversy,'' a Ferrari spokesman
said.
</TEXT>
