<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WrongBrother     06-03 0325</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wrong Brother,0333</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Confusion Over Look-alikes Sends Wrong Brother To Jail</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A veterinarian spent 26 days in jail before
convincing drug authorities that he isn't his brother, who has been
indicted on cocaine smuggling charges.
   Rafael Roca-Suarez gained his freedom at a hearing Thursday
before U.S. Magistrate William Turnoff.
   ``An honest mistake,'' Turnoff called it.
   He ordered Roca-Suarez's release on a $100,000 personal surety
bond and gave prosecutors and U.S. Drug Enforcement Administration
agents three weeks to make a few final checks on the situation.
   Roca-Suarez's wife, Patricia, said it was at least the second
time her husband has suffered from mistaken identity with his
look-alike brother, Renato. She said her husband was detained in
Panama in 1983 until a DEA agent was flown in to say he was the
wrong man.
   The same DEA agent, Rich Vandiver, had to be flown to Miami from
South America for the hearing Thursday.
   Renato Roca-Suarez, a pilot, is charged in a 1980 federal
indictment with conspiracy to import 854 pounds of cocaine from
Bolivia to the United States.
   Rafael Roca-Suarez was arrested last month in Houston. At a May
9 court hearing there, the 40-year-old Rafael testified that his
brother, Renato, who is a year and a half younger, is the man
authorities were seeking. But DEA agent David Gorman misidentified
Rafael as Renato, and Rafael was sent to Miami to face trial.
   The case was going forward based on a belief that Rafael was
Renato _ but defense attorneys met privately with Mark Schnapp,
chief of the criminal division of the U.S. Attorney's Office in
Miami, to show him military records, photos of the two brothers
together and newspaper articles about Renato, who, they said was
still in Bolivia. Schnapp said he questioned Rafael outside court
and was satisfied that he had veterinary training.
   By then, Schnapp said, he was convinced that the U.S. government
had to re-examine the question of identity.
</TEXT>
