<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SAfrica-Labor     06-03 0614</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-SAfrica-Labor,0631</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Employers Seek Court Action to Block Strike By Black Unions</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-South Africa, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURINDA KEYS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Major employers sought court
orders Friday in an effort to block a three-day protest called for
next week by black trade unions that is expected to become a
general strike.
   In other developments Friday, a white anti-apartheid activist
disputed the government's contention that no youngsters under the
age of 16 are being detained without charge under emergency-rule
decrees.
   And the government announced it would seek authority from the
Supreme Court to evict 1,800 people from a township where blacks
have lived for 40 years.
   Unions are barred by law from advocating strikes not related to
contract disputes. South Africa's two largest black labor
federations left it up to their affiliates to decide how to respond
to a call for a protest to begin Monday.
   The Congress of South African Trade Unions and the National
Council of Trade Unions, representing an estimated of 1.4 million
black workers, joined forces to protest a new labor bill they say
would cripple their unions by curtailing their ability to strike.
   ``Employers are not prepared to put effective pressure (on the
government) unless their interests are directly affected,''
congress general secretary Jay Naidoo told a news conference. ``We
believe if our members do take protest action some of that action
will affect their (the employers') interests.''
   Demonstrations are also planned over the next two weeks against
the 2-year-old state of emergency decreed on June 12 and the June
16 anniversary of the 1976 riots in the black township of Soweto.
   In their legal action the employers asked the courts for
injunctions against union officials participating in any unlawful
strike or job action.
   Max Coleman of the Detainees Parents Support Committee
challenged the claim last week by Law and Order Minister Adriaan
Vlok that no children younger than 16 were being held under
state-of-emergency regulations.
   Coleman released a statement listing the names of six black
detainees he said were 15 years old. He said others were under 16
when they were picked up and turned 16 in detention.
   Vlok said Coleman's statement ``reveals the shocking and chaotic
condition of the information that he has at his disposal and which
he and other radical persons use to vilify South Africa.''
   In his statement, Coleman said some children had been held for
more than a year without being charged.
   He said about 2,500 people are in detention under emergency
regulations, including about 250 youths under 18.
   Coleman's committee is one of 17 anti-apartheid organizations
banned in February from ``any activity whatsoever.''
   The government went to court to enforce its planned eviction of
1,800 people from the black township of Lawaaikamp near the white
city of George, east of Cape Town. It said the move does not
contradict its declaration that the policy of forced removals for
racial separation ended in 1984.
   Carel du Plessis, the George town clerk, said Friday the
evictions will be carried out under a law giving the municipality
authority over use of its land.
   Lawaaikamp residents at a meeting Thursday claimed the
government was reversing its policy because they would be forced to
move to make way for the development of a township for people of
mixed-race.
   Du Plessis said the residents would be given notices beginning
June 7 telling them of the city's plans to seek Supreme Court
approval for eviction orders.
   By law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated
society in which the 26 million blacks have no vote in national
affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and maintain
separate districts, schools and health services.
</TEXT>
