<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Simon     06-03 0342</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Simon,330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Simon Says He Hopes To Retain Influence Over Delegates To
Convention</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DOWLING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Paul Simon said Friday he hopes to
retain some influence over his eroding base of delegates to the
Democratic National Convention but acknowledged he cannot control
the delegates.
   The Illinois senator, who put his presidential campaign on hold
nearly two months ago, still has some 150 delegates but has lost
more than 30 in the last three weeks, most of whom have defected to
Democratic front-runner Michael Dukakis.
   ``I'm pleased that the huge majority of them are holding off
doing anything,'' he said. ``I think we want to do what we can to
stick together and be a force for good at the convention.''
   ``I don't think anyone controls delegates ... but I think you
can have some influence.''
   Simon, speaking at a news conference, said he plans to meet with
Dukakis after Tuesday's final four primaries to discuss topics
including the selection of a vice presidential candidate.
   He all but ruled out accepting the vice presidential nomination
himself, saying he would consider it only ``if some specific
responsibilities were spelled out.''
   ``I'm frankly not interested in spending four years cutting
ribbons and attending state funerals,'' Simon said.
   He declined to speculate on Jesse Jackson's potential as a vice
presidential candidate but listed three U.S. senators he said
Dukakis might consider.
   ``If Mike Dukakis goes the traditional route and ... recognizes
that the principal contribution a vice president may make is in
bringing in one state, then the two obvious choices I think are
John Glenn in Ohio and Lloyd Bentsen in Texas,'' Simon said.
   He said he doesn't see a similar vice presidential prospect in
California, but went on to praise Arkansas Sen. Dale Bumpers, who
for a time was Simon's choice for president.
   ``If you look at the number of electoral votes in the state of
Arkansas, he isn't a logical candidate, but I think there are other
reasons he should be considered,'' Simon said.
</TEXT>
