<1ST_LINE>u a AM-IndigentDefense     06-03 0447</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Indigent Defense,0459</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Appeals Court Upholds Guarantee of Legal Aid</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   No death-row inmate should be left to face
execution without a lawyer, a federal appeals court ruled Friday.
   The 4th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals overturned a December 1987
ruling by own of its own three-judge panels that denied such access
to the appeals process to inmates.
   In Virginia, unlike most other states, inmates who cannot afford
an attorney and have no volunteer counsel have no guarantee of
legal assistance once their sentences have been affirmed by the
state Supreme Court.
   Jonathan Sasser, a Durham, N.C., attorney, said Friday's 6-4
opinion apparently is the first time the right to counsel after
sentencing has been upheld by a federal appeals court.
   ``It's an access to the courts issue,'' said Sasser, who is
among the lawyers representing as a class all indigent Virginia
death-row inmates who are without personal volunteer attorneys.
``For a death-row inmate in Virginia, it means you have to have a
living, breathing attorney to represent you.''
   Gerald Zerkin, a Richmond attorney involved in the case, said
the ruling ``resolves a very difficult situation in which men on
death row did not have access to counsel to challenge their death
sentences.''
   The state will now be required to provide representation for
those men, Zerkin said, although the specifics of the system have
not been worked out.
   Sasser, who had been told about the decision but had not read
it, said the ruling stems from the case of Earl Washington, who was
condemned to die in August 1985. Washington could not afford to
hire a lawyer and no volunteers could be found to handle his case.
   ``He was sitting there waiting to be executed and he couldn't do
anything about it, because he didn't have an attorney,'' Sasser
said. ``The importance of this case is that that won't happen
again, unless the Supreme Court reverses it.''
   A lawyer was retained about a week before Washington's execution
date and he won a stay. Washington's appeals continue.
   Joseph Giarratano, another Virginia death-row inmate who had
legal counsel, was disturbed by the Washington case and contested
the lack of guaranteed counsel to a federal court in 1986.
   U.S. District Judge Robert R. Merhige Jr. agreed that such
representation is constitutionally warranted, but that decision was
overturned last year by the 4th Circuit panel.
   The latest decision is binding in the 4th Circuit, comprising
Maryland, North Carolina, South Carolina, Virginia and West
Virginia.
   Zerkin said the ruling also will serve as a precedent for cases
in other states, but said ``many, I would say most, states already
provide representation without having been required to do so.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
