<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-MIAs,330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grown Children Of MIAs Seek Meeting With Reagan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four grown children of American servicemen
missing in Southeast Asia went to the White House on Friday to seek
an explanation for President Reagan's willingness to help recover
Soviet soldiers missing from Afghanistan.
   Elizabeth Stewart, Washington representative of the American
League of Families of Prisoners of War in Laos, said it was an
``outrage'' that Reagan was willing to help the Soviets when he has
ignored her group's pleas for help. The group sought a meeting with
Reagan or a representative of the president.
   Ms. Stewart is the daughter of Air Force Col. Peter J. Stewart,
shot down over Dien Bien Phu, Laos, on March 15, 1966. She spoke by
telephone with White House spokesman B.J. Cooper, who declined to
meet with the group but promised a response would be forthcoming.
   ``I indicated I was appalled that the president was willing to
help'' recover missing Soviet troops, Ms. Stewart said.
   Before Reagan's trip to Moscow, her group wrote to Reagan and
requested that he ask Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev to use his
influence with Vietnam to help return missing Americans.
   At Moscow University, Reagan was asked by a student if he would
be willing to help recover more than 300 missing Soviet soldiers in
Afghanistan. ``Very much so,'' the president replied.
   The Pentagon lists 2,404 Americans unaccounted for from the
Vietnam War.
   Cooper said, ``A lot of efforts are made on a daily basis.
Sometimes they're not as visible (as a presidential promise in
Moscow). ... You're not always in a position to make all your
information public.''
   Cooper said Ms. Stewart's requested meeting with White House
officials would have to wait because experts on the subject had
gone for the day and the staff had to track down her pre-summit
letter.
   Ms. Stewart was accompanied by Michael Clark of Santa Barbara,
Calif., Gary Wright of McLean, Va. and Sherill Standerwick Long of
Germantown, Md.
</TEXT>
