<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MysteriousBoy     06-03 0399</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mysterious Boy,0410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Deaf-Mute Boy Found in Mexico Might Be American Crash Victim</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EL PASO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An 8-year-old boy found wandering in a
Mexican border city possibly survived a plane crash and might be
from the United States, officials said.
   The boy, who doesn't hear or speak and communicates only by
gesturing and drawing pictures, was found Nov. 7 by the side of a
highway in Ciudad Juarez. No one knows his name, but Juarez welfare
workers have named him ``Savat.''
   Authorities believe Savat is from the United States because of
his reactions to American cultural icons _ including hamburgers and
video games _ and they believe he lived through a plane crash
because of his drawings.
   ``He drew a plane, then he drew a plane that had crashed,'' said
Luis Torre of the Texas Department of Human Services. Torre works
as liaison between El Paso and Juarez child welfare agencies.
   Torre said Thursday that the second drawing depicted a lot of
blood and the bodies of two adults and a child.
   `We believe those represent his parents and a sister. He showed
me by using his fingers that he crawled away from the wreckage,''
said Torre.
   He said the boy has scars on his chest and back that look to be
2 to 3 years old.
   According to a report Torre filed with El Paso police, the boy's
pictures seem to indicate he was picked up after a plane crash by a
passer-by and taken to a hospital. After treatment, the boy
apparently left to look for his family.
   Authorities are stumped as to when or where the plane might have
crashed or how Savat got to Juarez, across the border from El Paso.
   The woman who found the boy, Guadalupe de la Vega of Juarez,
said she thinks Savat might be from the United States because he
doesn't like chili, tortillas or beans, but readily eats hamburgers
and hot dogs.
   He also is good at playing video games, which most young Mexican
children lack the money to play.
   ``We just recently got him into a school for the deaf,'' Torre
said. ``They showed him cartoons of American characters such as
Donald Duck and Mickey Mouse, and of Mexican characters, and he was
more familiar with the American cartoons and seemed to like them
better.''
   He added that Savat seems more familiar with U.S. money.
</TEXT>
