<DOCNO> AP880603-0244 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-03-88 2122EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Waldheim-Pope     06-03 0285</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Waldheim-Pope,0292</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Waldheim Says Pope Visit Will Help Austria</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Kurt Waldheim, shunned by world
leaders because of questions about his actions in World War II,
said the visit to Austria by Pope John Paul II will help the
country's image, a magazine reported Friday.
   ``The pope's visit will have a positive effect,'' Kathpress, a
Roman Catholic news agency, quoted Waldheim as saying in an
interview with the Italian Catholic monthly Trenta Giorni. John
Paul is to be in Austria June 23-27.
   Waldheim also was quoted as saying he regretted the protests
that followed his audience with the pontiff last year in the
Vatican. ``It was a shame that the pope was dragged into such a
slanderous campaign,'' he said.
   Excerpts of Waldheim's remarks were distributed in German by
Kathpress and translated by The Associated Press.
   The president said he did not believe John Paul's June visit to
Austria and their meeting would cause widespead protests, ``at
least not like those the last time.''
   The Vatican said that last year's audience was granted to the
presidential office, not to Waldheim as an individual.
   John Paul first visited Austria in 1983, three years before
Waldheim was elected president.
   Waldheim has denied allegations that he was involved in Nazi war
crimes while serving as a German army lieutenant in the Balkans
during World War II.
   An international commission of historians appointed by the
Austrian government at the president's request concluded in
February that Waldheim was aware of Nazi atrocities in the region
and did nothing to prevent them, but it left the question of guilt
open.
   Waldheim has not visited or received any Western heads of state
since his election in 1986.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
