<HEAD>North Korea Shuffles Economy-Related Posts</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-South Korea</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   North Korea changed ministers and commission
chairmen in six posts related to the economy, the official Korea
Central News Agency reported Friday.
   It was the fifth shuffle in three years involving top economic
positions.
   The North Korean news agency, in a broadcast monitored in Tokyo,
said President Kim Il Sung issued a decree Thursday involving
members of the Administration Council, which is similar to a
Cabinet and is headed by the premier.
   There are about 40 ministries and commissions in the council
with half related to economic planning, industries, mining,
transportation, construction, transportation and agriculture.
   Japanese analysts, including Katsumi Sato of the private Korean
Affairs Research Center, have said they believed the frequent
council changes indicated the communist government was struggling
to remove economic bottlenecks.
   Kim Young-sam, a major South Korean opposition leader, has
proposed that South Korea help North Korea pay its overdue foreign
debts, estimated at $4 billion.
   He told a news conference in Seoul Tuesday the North Koreans'
``international economic standing is so low they cannot pay back
the debt. We could help them by importing primary or parts of
secondary products from them.''
   North Korea broke off talks with South Korea on economic,
humanitarian and parliamentarian exchanges early in 1986 to protest
the annual U.S.-South Korean military exercises.
