<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Peru     06-03 0299</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Peru,0307</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Kill 16 in Jungle Drug Trafficking Zone</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Students and police clashed Friday in the
fifth straight day of campus protests that officials claim were
fomented by the Maoist Shining Path guerrilla organization.
   The Shining Path has been battling for eight years to topple the
elected government and the fighting has taken at least 10,000 lives.
   Students began blocking roads with burning tires and debris and
hurling rocks at police at San Marcos University and two other Lima
universities early this week to protest higher school fees and an
alleged massacre of highland peasants by soldiers.
   Police responded by firing tear gas and at one point went
through San Marcos University and arrested about 100 people, many
wearing masks and shouting Shining Path slogans, according to
police and reporters.
   Protests intensified Wednesday after a demonstrator was killed
in a shooting that is still being investigated. Students told
juournalists more than a dozen protesters have been wounded by
buckshot fired by police.
   No reports were available of any casualties or arrests from
Friday's campus violence.
   Officials said Friday that two Shining Path gunmen killed a
policeman as he guarded a courthouse Thursday in Chimbote, a
coastal state capital 255 miles north of Lima.
   The government said Friday that five more gunmen were killed in
jungle gunfights in a cocaine-trafficking region on Wednesday that
had previously been reported, bringing the number of
``narco-terrorists'' killed that day to 16 .
   Officials earlier had reported police killed 11 Maoist
guerrillas on Wednesday near Uchiza. They said Friday that five
drug traffickers were killed in a nearby clash later in the day.
   The government says the Shining Path provides protection to drug
runners in Peru's eastern jungles and officials use the term
``narco-terrorists'' to describe both groups.
  
