<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Mecham 2ndLd-Writethru a0789 06-03 0835</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mecham, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0789,0856</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mistrial Denied in Mecham Criminal Case</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts four grafs after 8th graf ``The effect...'' to UPDATE
with afternoon testimony. Picks up 9th graf pvs ``The
first-term...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LAURIE ASSEO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge on Friday rejected a defense
request for a mistrial on grounds that a prosecution witness'
testimony was unfair in former Gov. Evan Mecham's trial on charges
he concealed a $350,000 campaign loan.
   Judge Michael Ryan of Maricopa County Superior Court rejected a
claim by lawyer Thomas Crowe that the prosecution tried to
prejudice the jury by presenting testimony that Crowe said implied
wrongdoing in how the Mecham campaign's checkbook was handled.
   Mecham and his brother, Willard, are charged with concealing the
loan by Tempe developer Barry Wolfson. Willard Mecham was his
brother's 1986 campaign treasurer.
   Also on Friday, former U.S. Rep. Sam Steiger was placed on
probation for four years, fined $5,480, and ordered to perform 700
hours of community service work for pressuring a parole board
member over an administrative matter while working as an aide to
Evan Mecham while Mecham was governor.
   Steiger, 59, was convicted April 7 of theft by extortion in
threatening Board of Pardons and Paroles member Ron Johnson over a
personnel vote.
   In Mecham's trial Thursday, state handwriting expert William
Flynn testified there had been a number of ``white-outs, erasures
and alterations'' in the campaign checkbook. He did not speculate
on the reasons for the changes.
   Crowe contended the revisions were innocent corrections, but the
prosecution implied ``there was something wrong, something
criminal, something improper'' about them.
   ``The effect (on the jury) was devastating,'' Crowe said.
   During the afternoon session, jurors were read portions of
Willard Mecham's January testimony to the state grand jury, in
which he denied wrongdoing when he lumped the $350,000 loan into a
$465,000 total listed on financial reports as a contribution from
Evan Mecham.
   The transcript also showed Willard Mecham said he did not know
about a letter, in which his brother promised Wolfson the loan
would ``remain confidential,'' until after the loan's existence was
publicly disclosed by the news media.
   With the jury not present, the prosecution argued for admission
of testimony by a former Mecham Finance Commitee member who took
notes during a meeting in fall 1986 that say, ``show Evan borrowed
money'' and ``don't show borrowed money.''
   Ryan took the matter under advisement, saying he will rule
before testimony resumes Monday.
   The first-term Republican governor was removed from office April
4 when the state Senate convicted him of two unrelated impeachment
counts. The Senate opted not to consider the count against him
related to the loan after some members argued that to do so would
unfairly prejudice his criminal trial.
   The defense contends the failure to report the loan was an
innocent mistake.
   Prosecutor Barnett Lotstein said in court Friday there was no
negative implication in Flynn's testimony about the checkbook. He
said the prosecution was seeking in testimong Thursday to show that
Willard Mecham was a meticulous bookkeeper who was not prone to
mistakes.
   In denying the mistrial motion, Ryan said he thought Flynn's
testimony was ``quite innocuous'' and may prove relevant regarding
Willard Mecham's bookkeeping practices.
   The judge also refused a defense request to admonish the jury
against taking a negative inference from Flynn's testimony.
   The defense Friday also sought the exclusion of testimony about
a number of statements by Willard Mecham to the state grand jury
that indicted the brothers Jan. 8. Ryan granted some of the defense
requests to exclude such testimony but rejected many others.
   Ryan also chided attorneys on both sides, saying they should
have cooperated more fully in deciding what grand jury testimony
would be admitted. ``This is outrageous,'' the judge said after an
hour of arguments on the issue.
   The motions were argued without the jury present and took up
Friday morning's court session.
   The Mecham brothers sat with their attorneys and declined to
comment to reporters.
   In his opening statement Thursday, Lotstein said the Mechams
purposely broke the law when they failed to include the $350,000
loan from Tempe developer Barry Wolfson in personal and campaign
financial reports.
   Mecham faces up to 22 years in prison if convicted on all six
counts of perjury, willful concealment and filing false documents.
   Willard Mecham faces three similar counts and up to 9{ years in
prison if convicted.
   The Republican governor was removed from office April 4 when the
state Senate convicted him of two unrelated impeachment counts. He
took office in January 1987.
   Mecham long has contended the $350,000 loan was properly
reported on his Dec. 5, 1986, financial report. He said it was
included in a $465,000 lump sum that was listed as a contribution
from himself.
   The prosecution has said, however, that Mecham badly needed the
money to keep his campaign afloat and that he concealed it because
Wolfson asked him to and because his campaign had a theme of being
``beholden to no one.''
</TEXT>
