<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Jackson 1stLd-Writethru a0807 06-03 0654</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0807,650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Says Environmental Concerns No Fringe Issue</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 4 grafs for penultimate graf pvs, bgng: ``Jackson later
...'' to UPDATE with later appearances in Montana.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA FE, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson campaigned Friday in sunny
New Mexico and told the region's environmental constituency their
concerns are ``no longer a fringe issue'' but are central to human
existence.
   Heading down the home stretch to Tuesday's final primaries in
New Mexico, California, Montana and New Jersey, the Democratic
candidate also said he is still running to win the presidential
election.
   Jackson said he did not know the context of reported comments by
his campaign manager, Gerald Austin, that the strongest Democratic
ticket would be front-runner Michael Dukakis and Sen. John Glenn of
Ohio.
   Jackson told reporters not to ``take that seriously.''
   Austin was quoted in the Boston Herald as saying Jackson was his
first choice for vice president but that Glenn would make for an
almost unbeatable ticket. But Jackson told reporters Austin's
comments did not reflect any thinking on his part that he did not
want the vice presidential spot or that he has made any decision in
the matter.
   ``We are running to win the last four contests on June 7. We'll
then exercise our options for June 8 and beyond,'' he said, adding
that Austin is in good standing with the campaign and ``his
position is secure.''
   Jackson maintains he deserves consideration for the vice
presidential nomination if Dukakis wins and has said that if he
wins, he'll consider Dukakis.
   Jackson spoke to more than 1,500 people on a sun-baked plaza
surrounded by Sante Fe's trademark Indian sidewalk vendors who sell
an array of turquoise and silver jewelry.
   He spoke of the controversy over federal plans to store nuclear
waste near Carlsbad and said, ``safety before waste, that must be
your watchword.''
   The issue of nuclear waste storage and toxic dumps ``is no
longer a fringe issue,'' he said. ``Environmental protection is
central to our existence. ... It goes to the heart of the American
dream. I stand to protect that dream.''
   Jackson also told the audience of whites, Indians and Hispanics
that the many scientists and engineers who work on military
projects in New Mexico are being ``held hostage'' to the military
economy.
   Those scientific minds should be put to work instead on space
development, research on medical advances, global communications
and technical work to verify arms agreements, he said.
   Referring to President Reagan's recent summit meeting in Moscow,
Jackson said to applause, ``I want to respect all our people. If we
can honor an agreement with Russia we can honor an agreement with
American Indians.''
   Jackson was joined at the rally by Buffy Sainte-Marie, a singer
of Indian heritage, who traveled with the campaign from Los Angeles.
   Jackson later Friday campaigned in Montana, which has just 19
delegates at stake on Tuesday, and said at a rally in Bozeman: ``We
cannot measure human beings and their needs just by their political
capital. ... It's their humanity that's at stake.''
   Later, he spoke at a dinner sponsored by the state Democratic
Party in Butte, where he was warmly received by the few hundred in
attendance, most of whom wore Dukakis buttons.
   He offered a prayer for Dukakis' wife, Kitty, who underwent
spinal surgery on Friday.
   He then headed to Bakersfield, Calif., for the night. In nearby
McFarland, Calif., he planned to spend much of Saturday with a
march and rally centered around the mysteriously high cancer rate
in the small central valley town.
   Jackson had taken up the McFarland issue as a central cause of
his campaign in its closing days. He mentioned it in all his Los
Angeles speeches over the past two days. He called on supporters to
join him in McFarland to call for government action in finding and
correcting the cause of the cancer.
</TEXT>
