<HEAD>Explosive Device Found At Airport; Terminal Evacuated</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 9 grafs to UPDATE with details of youths
questioned, information that relic was from France, information
that youth who packed shell in box still in Europe. Picks up 6th
graf pvs ``People considered...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TODD RICHISSIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A war relic that a youngster packed aboard a
flight from Europe caused a bomb scare and partial evacuation
Friday at Seattle-Tacoma International Airport, authorities said.
   The artillery shell, picked up from a European battlefield by a
youth on a bicycle trip, dropped out of a bicycle box being
unloaded from Scandinavian Airlines System Flight 937 from
Copenhagen, Denmark, Port of Seattle police Chief Ed Ingram said.
   FBI agents questioned ``four young adults, three girls and one
boy,'' then released them to their parents, said airport
spokeswoman Margo Spellman.
   The youths said the boy who packed the shell in the box was
still in Europe, Ms. Spellman said.
   The youths were part of a tour group from the Bush School, a
private Seattle school, KING-TV reported.
   The shell came from a bunker in France, said Leif Eie, an SAS
spokesman in Seattle. She said transporting the shell wasn't
illegal because ``we permit live ammunition in the baggage
department like all other carriers.''
   ``We're still not sure if it's alive,'' said Ingram, who added
that explosive experts were photographing and studying the relic.
He was unsure of its age.
   The device was about a foot long and three inches in diameter,
Ms. Spellman said.
   The shell was loaded into a steel drum and taken by truck to a
concrete bomb bunker away from the terminal, where it was found
shortly after 2 p.m. That terminal, a satellite of the main
terminal normally used by Northwest Airlines, Japan Air lines and
Scandanavian Airlines, was reopened about 3:20 p.m., Ms. Spellman
said.
   People considered in a danger zone were evacuated almost
imediately, and a bomb squad and canine unit checked the area, Ms.
Spellman said.
   Sea-Tac has two satellite terminals or concourses separate from
its main terminal that are reached by subway trains.
   Ms. Spellman did not immediately know how many gates, flights or
passengers were affected by the closure.
   SAS spokeswoman Eileen Drutman in Los Angeles said she had no
information about the situation but that airline officials were
investigating it.
   One flight known to have been delayed was Northwest Airlines
Flight 156, which was scheduled to carry about 120 people to
Minneapolis-St. Paul, said Bob Gibbons, a Northwest spokesman in
St. Paul.
</TEXT>
