<DOCNO> AP880603-0262 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-03-88 1022EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e PM-APArts:SchoolforWives Adv07   06-03 0690</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AP Arts: School for Wives, Adv 07,0701</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv 07</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Tues PMs, June 7 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>A Buoyant, Bittersweet `School for Wives' at the Hartford Stage
Company</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Critic</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The sound of Fred Astaire singing ``Night
and Day'' floats through the theater as the house lights dim and
the play begins.
   It's an anachronistic but totally appropriate introduction to
Moliere's ``The School for Wives,'' a 17th-century comedy about
obsessive love, a subject Cole Porter's most haunting melody and
lyrics also celebrate.
   Director Mark Lamos and actor Gerry Bamman perfectly capture
that obsession in a buoyant yet bittersweet production of ``The
School for Wives,'' now running at the Hartford Stage Company.
   Bamman, relatively unknown on Broadway but who has made his mark
in regional theaters like Hartford and the Guthrie in Minneapolis,
is a revelation. He exudes a self-satisfaction that is most
delightful when it is deflated. The actor plays Arnolphe, a smug
middle-class gentleman who raises his young female ward, Agnes, to
be what he considers a perfect wife _ sweet, obedient and
empty-headed.
   Lamos has set ``The School for Wives'' in what looks like late
19th or early 20th century France. He gives it a quaint charm that
suggests the early films of Rene Clair, particularly his silent
classic, ``The Italian Straw Hat.''
   A soft pastel glow envelopes the production. There's a circus
feeling to the evening, accentuated by designer John Arnone's
storybook French farmhouse. The characters, some wearing white
pancake makeup, resemble clowns. Arnolphe looks like a bourgeois
Charlie Chaplin, complete with that smidgen of a mustache and a
bowler hat.
   Bamman expertly negotiates the play's poetry _ showcased in
Richard Wilbur's graceful and witty adaptation _ as well as its
pratfalls. He's an expert vaudevillian, a master of the slow burn
and double take worthy of a Jackie Gleason or a Bert Lahr.
   For a 300-year-old play, ``The School for Wives'' reverberates
with a modern sensibility about women and their roles in marriage
and a society dictated by men. Arnolphe desires an uncomplicated
wife _ one, he says, who will say her prayers, spin, sew and love
him. And he gets none of it.
   Arnolphe's exasperation grows more desperate and more hilarious
as his fiancee becomes more confident in herself. Her
singlemindedness strengthens after she falls in love with Horace, a
handsome young man.
   A lovely Barbara Howard makes the transformation of Agnes _ from
an innocent into an intelligent, questioning woman _ something to
savor. Her declaration of independence from her possessive guardian
should win cheers from the least militant of feminists.
   Lamos has surrounded his leading players with a fine assortment
of character actors, as distinct for their physicality as their
emoting. Eric Swanson is an impassioned, jittery neophyte suitor;
Don R. McManus and Alice Haining as Arnolphe's exasperating
servants get a few laughs from some low hijinks, and Ian Trigger is
deliriously funny as a pint-size notary.
   But Lamos coaxes something more from this ``School for Wives''
than laughs.
   Arnolphe's defeat is not unexpected, but it is surprisingly
moving considering the laughter that goes before it. By the end of
the play, Bamman has revealed the hurt as well as the humor in this
pompous man's loss of a wife as well as his dignity.
   And it's not only Arnolphe who faces a bitter truth. When Horace
finally wins Agnes, he retreats with the rest of the men to the
side of the stage. Agnes watches their clubby masculine conclave
with the realization that her schooling in the battle of the sexes
is far from over. It's a brilliant tableau.
   This production, originally done with the same two leads at the
La Jolla Playhouse in California last summer, is as memorable as
the delectable and laugh-filled Broadway revival that starred Brian
Bedford and Joan Van Ark more than 15 years ago.
   However, Lamos has taken the play a step further. In his
``School for Wives,'' the director shows that an education in love
can be just as difficult for the teacher as it is for the student.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PM Tues Junee 7</NOTE>
</DOC>
