<FILEID>AP-NR-06-03-88 0229EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-RetailSales Bjt   06-03 0622</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Retail Sales, Bjt,0642</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>May Sales Continue Sluggish Trend</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE M. ROSENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's largest general retailers reported their sales
remained slack in May as consumers continued to hold tight to their
purse strings.
   ``Retail sales have been in a recession since the middle of last
year, and they still are,'' Linda Kristiansen, a retail industry
analyst with the investment firm Dean Witter Reynolds Inc., said
Thursday after the retailers issued their monthly sales reports.
   High installment debt, an aversion to higher prices and boredom
with current fashions _ the same factors that have kept consumers
cautious for months _ contributed to the lackluster May performance
and were exacerbated by the unusually cool spring, analysts said.
   Jeffrey Feiner, an analyst with Merrill Lynch & Co., described
last month's sales as ``in line with or slightly below
conservatively budgeted expectations.''
   Feiner said storeowners have responded to the continued sales
slump by cutting back their inventories.
   He warned this could result in fewer orders to manufacturers and
``could potentially back up into the rest of the economy.''
   Consumer spending, which accounts for two-thirds of the gross
national product, is an important barometer of the economy's health.
   Analysts say June sales results could show a pickup if the
warmer weather that arrived at the end of May holds up, but a major
turnaround is not expected for several months.
   ``The next chance for a decent sales gain will be in August with
the back-to-school'' merchandise, said Monroe Greenstein, an
analyst with Bear Stearns & Co.
   Many retailers said their May sales were only marginally higher
or down from levels of a year ago.
   Sears, Roebuck and Co., the nation's largest retailer, said its
overall sales rose 5.1 percent when compared with May 1987, while
sales for the first 17 weeks of the fiscal year rose 3.5 percent
over last year. But sales at stores open at least a year, known as
same-store sales in the industry, rose only 0.2 percent last month
and 1.1 percent so far this year.
   Analysts pay closer attention to same-store sales because they
provide a more accurate picture of a retailer's performance.
   K mart Corp. said its overall sales rose 6 percent last month
and 4.8 percent so far this year. Same-store sales were up 2.3
percent for May and 1.7 percent for the year-to-date.
   Wal-Mart Stores Inc. said its overall sales gained 27 percent
last month and 31 percent so far this year. Same-store sales rose 8
percent for May and 12 percent year-to-date.
   J.C. Penney Co. Inc., which emphasizes its fashion lines, said
its overall sales fell 1.2 percent last month but were up 2.4
percent so far this year. Penney's same-store sales declined 1.4
percent in May and rose 1.5 percent for the first 17 weeks.
   Dayton Hudson Corp. said its overall sales rose 17.6 percent in
May and 18.1 percent so far this year. Same-store sales were up 1.7
percent last month and 1.5 percent year-to-date.
   May Department Stores Co. reported a 17.8 percent overall
increase in May and a 6.5 percent rise year-to-date. Same-store
sales were up 1.3 percent last month but down 0.3 percent during
the first 17 weeks. The company's May results included sales from
the newly acquired Foley's and Filene's divisions.
   F.W. Woolworth Co. reported a 14.2 percent gain in May and a
12.2 percent increase so far this year.
   Montgomery Ward & Co. said its overall sales rose 3.7 percent
last month and 3 percent for the year-to-date. Same-store sales
edged up 0.9 percent in May and 0.3 percent so far this year.
   The numbers reported Thursday were for general merchandise and
apparel retailers and do not reflect sales of auto dealers or
supermarkets.
</TEXT>
