<HEAD>Dollar Down, Gold Up</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: also ran on general news wires</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar reversed course and fell against all
major foreign currencies in European trading today.
   Gold bullion rose in active trading.
   The dollar opened strong in Tokyo, but came under pressure from
profit-taking before the European opening, traders said.
   At midmorning, the U.S. unit was losing ground against all major
currencies, although markets had calmed from the previous day's
sharp swings.
   Midmorning dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Thursday,
were: 1.7223 West German marks, down from 1.7295; 1.4345 Swiss
francs, down from 1.4425; 5.8275 French francs, down from 5.8502;
1.9343 Dutch guilders, down from 1.9413; 1,282.50 Italian lire,
down from 1,286.75; and 1.2303 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2325.
   The British pound edged up to $1.8005 from late Thursday's rate
of $1.7967. Major British banks raised their base lending rates by
half point Friday to 8 percent, but analysts said sterling still
appeared vulnerable.
   The dollar closed in Tokyo at 126.11 Japanese yen, up from
125.68 yen. But in later London trading today, the dollar slipped
back to 125.70 yen.
   Bullion prices, boosted by a rally in the commodities market,
jumped after a bout of profit-taking ran out of steam.
   London's main bullion houses fixed a recommended gold price at
midmorning of $464.85 a troy ounce, up from $454.30.
   In Zurich, gold was bid at $464.50, up from $453.
   Earlier, the metal closed in Hong Kong at a bid of $463.71, up
from $455.38.
   Silver bullion rose sharply in London, trading at a bid of $7.24
a troy ounce, up from $6.73.
