<HEAD>Dollar Gains, Shares Drop</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: also running on general news wires</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Reflecting strong gains in New York and London, the
U.S. dollar rose sharply against the Japanese yen in Tokyo today,
while share prices dipped for the first time in a week.
   The dollar closed the week at 126.11 yen, up 0.43 yen from its
125.68-yen finish Thursday. It opened the day's trading at 126.07
and changed hands between 126-126.25 yen throughout the day.
   The dollar last closed on the 126-yen level on April 14, when it
finished at 126.10 yen. The next day, the currency tumbled to
124.13 yen.
   Exchange dealers said the dollar opened too strong today and
dropped briefly in early trading but stabilized in the late morning
and afternoon sessions.
   ``Investors saw the opening level as being too high and sold the
dollar in profit-taking,'' said a dealer at a U.S. bank. ``But the
dollar is basically bullish, and it bounced back up,'' he said,
speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Dealers said Japanese trust banks, which sold as much as $1
billion at the 126.30-126.40-yen level, contributed to keeping the
currency at a higher level.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, meanwhile, the Nikkei Stock Average
of 225 selected issues lost 47.82 points, or 0.17 percent, from
Thursday's close to finish the day at 27,821.54. The loss snapped a
four-day winning streak in which the main market barometer had
gained a total 646.26 points.
   ``The market resisted unfavorable conditions such as higher
requirements for margin trading, profit-taking and concern over
inflation in the U.S. during the morning session,'' said a broker
at a major securities firm. ``But it could not maintain the current
level and dropped down a little in the afternoon,'' he added,
speaking on condition of anonymity.
   The Tokyo Stock Exchange announced Thursday it was raising its
margin requirement from 60 percent to 70 percent effective today.
   Volume traded on the exchange's first section was a strong 2
billion shares.
</TEXT>
