<1ST_LINE>d f BC-Turkey-Hazelnuts     06-03 0423</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Turkey-Hazelnuts,0440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Turkey Establishes an International Hazelnut Union</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ZEYNEP ALEMDAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANKARA, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In an attempt to live up to its reputation
as the world's largest hazelnut producer and exporter, Turkey has
recently established an international union in a joint effort with
some other exporter and importer countries.
   The members of the group include Italy, Spain and West Germany,
both importers and exporters, and the United States and France,
only importers.
   ``Turkey is the leading country in the global hazelnut market,
producing 75 percent of the world's hazelnut crop and having 70
percent of the world's import market,'' Ertugrul Onen, the general
director of the exports department at the Treasury and Foreign
Trade Undersecretary, told The Associated Press.
   But he added that Turkey also wanted to play an active role in
organizing the global hazelnut market.
   Onen said a powerful importers' organization in Hamburg, West
Germany, Waren Verein, had set all the rules in the global hazelnut
market until now. ``But this has got to be changed,'' he added.
   Onen said the union would not be a cartel-like organization.
``That is the reason why we invited importer nations along with the
producers to be the founding members of the union.''
   Onen said the union aimed at improving the workings of the
market, avoiding unnecessary conflicts, preventing delays in
arbitration cases and protecting the rights of both importers and
producers.
   He added that the union would also seek ways to increase
hazelnut production and consumption worldwide.
   The union is expected to start functioning in a few months
following a general convention meeting. Its headquarters will be in
Ankara.
   Turkey's Black Sea coast is the source of the country's hazelnut
production. About two million people make their living from the nut
crop in the region.
   Last year, the country earned 390 million dollars from sale of
hazelnuts, mostly to West Germany, France, Soviet Union, Britain,
Austria, Switzerland, Italy and the Netherlands. Hazelnuts are
mostly used in chocolate and other candy.
   The production amounted to 260,000 tons in 1987. This year's
crop is estimated to be 350,000 tons, well over the annual average
amount of 300,000 tons.
   Onen also noted that the crop totally recovered from fallout
from the Chernobyl nuclear accident two years ago.
   Following the disaster, hazelnuts from the eastern part of the
Black Sea coastal area showed radiation levels above the European
Economic Community limit of 600 becerel, a measure of nuclear
contamination.
   The latest measures showed radiation levels under 100 becerel
for the crop, Onen said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880603-0284 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-03-88 0826EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-UN-Commodities     06-03 0303</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-UN-Commodities,0315</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Global Fund To Stabilize Prices Nears Final Approval</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A planned United Nations fund to shore up
commodity prices is expected next week to come within one vote of
the minimum needed for ratification, a U.N. spokesman said Friday.
   Honduras recently became the 100th nation to ratify the 1980
agreement on a United Nations Common Fund for Commodities and
approval by the Maldives is due next week, spokesman Graham Shanley
said.
   Its ratification would mean that countries accounting for 66.46
percent of initial contributions totaling $470 million have
approved the fund. Two-thirds, 66.67 percent, are needed, so one
more ratification could finally launch the project, Shanley told a
news briefing.
   Hopes were boosted last December when the Soviet Union ratified
the agreement, reached under auspices of the Geneva-based U.N.
Conference on Trade and Development, the main forum for the
north-south dialogue.
   Moscow had signed at last July and is due to pay 5.78 percent of
the fund's starting capital.
   The United States, which would have to contribute 15.7 percent,
signed the pact under the Carter administration but has not given
its ratification.
   The fund would help finance buffer stocks, a device used in
commodity agreements to help steer world market supplies and
thereby prices. Major commodity accords have been negotiated under
the U.N. Conference on Trade and Development, including those for
cocoa and natural rubber.
   An additional $265 million in pledges, earmarked for financing
research and development in commodities, will be freed if the fund
enters force.
   The fund was central to an ambitious program launched at a 1976
conference that aimed to promote price stabiliziation for 18 major
commodities, from bauxite to vegetable oils.
   Enthusiasm for such accords has since waned among rich
countries, especially after an agreement regulating world tin
prices went bankrupt three years ago.
</TEXT>
