<HEAD>City Asks Court To Delay Koppers Sale</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS name of takeover company to BNS Inc. in 3rd graf.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   City officials have asked a U.S. District
Court judge to delay British industrialist Brian Beazer's $1.7
billion takeover of Koppers Co. until they can review the latest
developments in the deal.
   In court papers filed Thursday, the city argued it should be
allowed time to review an agreement to sell the construction
materials and chemicals company before an injunction blocking the
transaction is lifted.
   Beazer won a three-month battle to acquire Koppers this week
when the company agreed to a $61-per-share buyout by BNS Inc., a
company formed by Beazer, Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. and National
Westminster Bank PLC.
   City officials said they are concerned about the fate of 1,150
employees the company has in the Pittsburgh area. All but 40 of
Koppers' local workforce are attached to chemicals operations
Beazer plans to sell.
   Mayor Sophie Masloff sharply criticized Koppers on Thursday,
saying, ``I think they sold us down the river.... I thought we had
an agreement with them that there wouldn't be a sellout yet, but
apparently they didn't pay any attention to that.''
   Allegheny County Commissioner Tom Foerster has asked the city
and the state to join the county in helping Koppers' employees put
together a plan to buy the company's chemical and allied products
operations from BNS.
