<FILEID>AP-NR-06-03-88 0832EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BankBid     06-03 0505</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bank Bid,0521</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Delays Irving Bid for 10 Days</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bank of New York's hostile takeover bid for
Irving Bank Corp. is being interrupted for 10 days on a federal
judge's orders.
   U.S. District Judge Charles S. Haight Jr. barred Bank of New
York Thursday from purchasing Irving common stock for 10 days.
   Irving filed suit in federal court last month against Bank of
New York, claiming the unfriendly takeover bid violated federal
securities laws.
   Under its $1.1 billion tender offer, Bank of New York plans to
run Irving as a separate subsidiary, regardless of whether it could
win control of Irving's board. The offer is for $15 in cash and
1.575 shares of its stock for each of Irving's 18.5 million common
shares outstanding.
   Irving claimed Bank of New York failed to notify shareholders of
the financial ramifications of its amended offer and also failed to
disclose the effects of its proposal to operate Irving as a
subsidiary.
   In a 22-page opinion issued after the markets closed Thursday
evening, U.S. District Judge Charles S. Haight Jr. concluded Bank
of New York ``must issue and disseminate a supplemental prospectus
addressing certain issues.''
   He issued a temporary restraining order that bars purchase of
Irving common stock for 10 days pending additional disclosure.
   ``We have no objection to doing that,'' said John L. Warden, an
attorney for Bank of New York. He said the company was compiling
the necessary information and would have it ready by next Tuesday,
and added that most of it is already public.
   Haight rejected Irving's request for additional disclosure but
directed Irving lawyers to draw up another order that would extend
Bank of New York's offer for six business days after the additional
information is disclosed to shareholders.
   Irving has taken steps to prevent Bank of New York from
proceeding with its tender offer. Last month, it amended its
``poison pill'' so that it would be activated should any unwanted
investor acquire at least 20 percent of Irving shares on the open
market. The poison pill previously would have gone into effect in
the event of a takeover not supported by management.
   Poison pill defenses are designed to discourage takeover bids by
greatly increasing the cost of an acquisition. In Irving's case,
all existing shareholders except Bank of New York would be allowed
to buy Irving shares for half-price once Bank of New York acquired
20 percent of Irving shares.
   Irving has steadfastly rejected Bank of New York takeover
proposals, instead opting for a friendly merger with the state-run
Banca Commerciale Italiana SpA, Italy's second largest bank.
   The Banca Commerciale bid is part of a complex restructuring
plan that includes sale of Irving assets, several cost-cutting
measures and a special $10 dividend. The proposal still needs
regulatory approval.
   Bank of New York closed up 37.5 cents to $32.50 in composite
trading on the New York Stock Exchange before Haight's ruling was
made public, while Irving rose 62.5 cents to $64.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880603-0287 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-03-88 0840EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Japan-USChips     06-03 0360</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Japan-US Chips,0372</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Industry Groups Fail To Reach Agreement On Semiconductor Access</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. and Japanese electronics industry groups
failed to reach agreement this week on increased foreign access to
the Japanese semiconductor market, the two sides said Friday.
   In meetings in Tokyo, the U.S. Semiconductor Industry
Association and the Electronic Industries Association of Japan
``came close'' to an agreement on increased access for foreign
makers of computer chips, but talks broke down following
disagreement over whether concrete targets should be set for
foreign market share, the Japanese group said.
   Before the meetings, the third set between the two sides, the
Japanese group had presented the U.S. industry group with proposals
for a ``joint action program'' aimed at increasing sales of foreign
semiconductors in Japan.
   The proposals included establishment of long-term relationships
between Japanese semiconductor users and foreign makers, and
increased participation by foreign suppliers in the design stage of
Japanese electronic products, the Japanese group said.
   But the U.S. group insisted on a clearly stated target of sales
promotion for expansion of market shares, the Japanese group said
in a statement.
   Jeanne Locke, director of communications for the U.S.
Semiconductor Industry Association, said the differences focused on
how to address the ``process of market access.''
   ``It started to be apparent we (and the Japanese side) were
talking about two different things,'' she said.
   Locke said U.S. makers wanted to be able to measure progress
through actual improvements in market share.
   The Japanese government has urged Japanese firms to increase
their purchases of foreign-made semiconductor chips, but U.S.
makers say the growth of their sales in the Japanese market is too
slow.
   In April 1987, U.S. President Ronald Reagan imposed $300 million
in punitive tariffs on Japanese electronic products for Japan's
alleged violation of a 1986 semiconductor agreement. In the pact,
Japan pledged to boost foreign access to the Japanese market and
stop alleged sales of semiconductors by Japanese producers at
unfairly low prices, a practice called ``dumping.''
   A total of $135 million of the trade sanctions have since been
lifted, following a U.S. Commerce Department report that Japanese
makers had stopped dumping semiconductors on world markets.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
