<1ST_LINE>u f PM-EconomyRdp 1stLd-Writethru   06-03 0604</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Economy Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru,0626</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>May Retail Sales Continue Sluggish; Wall Street Slumps</HEAD>
<HEAD>Tops with 8 grafs on May unemployment data; picks up 2nd graf pvs,
Many of ...; fixes credit line.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The civilian unemployment rate rose to 5.6 percent in May, its
first increase in 20 months, the government said today.
   The 0.2 percentage point increase from a 14-year-low jobless
rate of 5.4 percent was accompanied by an increase of 173,000 in
the number of people listed by the Labor Department as officially
unemployed.
   The department said the labor force, those either holding jobs
or actively looking for them, shrunk by 363,000 to 122.7 million.
   The figures are based on a monthly survey of the nation's
households.
   A separate survey of employer payrolls showed the economy
creating 210,000 jobs in May, but that was down from an average job
growth over the last year of 250,000 a month.
   ``Almost all of the payroll job increase took place in the
service-producing sector,'' said Janet L. Norwood, the commissioner
of labor statistics.
   Ms. Norwood told the congressional Joint Economic Committee that
job growth in business services, which has accounted for one in
eight new jobs over the six-year economic expansion, has slowed in
recent months.
   In other economic news, consumers are still showing a reluctance
to open their wallets, and industry analysts say the slump could
continue through much of the summer.
   Many of the nation's largest general retailers, reporting their
May results Thursday, said sales were only marginally higher or
down from levels of a year earlier.
   High installment debt, an aversion to higher prices and boredom
with current fashions _ the same factors that have kept consumers
cautious for months _ contributed to the lackluster May performance
and were exacerbated by the unusually cool spring, analysts said.
   Wall Street had a slump of its own as stocks gave up some of
their recent gains amid rising interest rates.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, up 107.57 points
Tuesday and Wednesday, dropped back 11.56 Thursday to 2,052.45.
   Interest rates rose in the credit markets, reversing a sharp
decline Tuesday and Wednesday. That prompted many traders to sell
stocks in order to cash in on the gains of the past two sessions,
brokers said.
   Meanwhile, inflation fears, sparked by persistent rises in
agricultural commodity prices in recent days, pushed gold prices
sharply higher. Republic National Bank of New York quoted a bid for
gold of $466.25 a troy ounce as of 4 p.m. EDT, up $8.75 from late
Wednesday.
   In other economic developments Thursday:
   _A new study on competitiveness showed the standard of living of
workers in other major countries has risen four times as fast as
the U.S. standard of living in the past 15 years.
   _The Federal Reserve reported that the narrowest measure of the
nation's money supply, M1, rose to a seasonally adjusted $769.3
billion in the week ended May 23 from a revised $768.1 billion the
previous week.
   Consumer spending, which accounts for two-thirds of the gross
national product, is an important barometer of the economy's health.
   ``The (May) sales were sluggish by normal standards,'' said
Jeffrey Edelman, a retail industry analyst with the investment firm
Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.
   Jeffrey Feiner, an analyst with Merrill Lynch & Co., described
last month's sales as ``in line with or slightly below
conservatively budgeted expectations.''
   Retail sales have been sluggish for more than a year, and Feiner
said storeowners have responded by cutting back their inventories.
   He warned this could result in fewer orders to manufacturers and
``could potentially back up into the rest of the economy.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
