<HEAD>EEC Probes Charges Of Dumping Of Japanese Loaders, Backhoes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The European Economic Community said
Friday it is investigating allegations of EEC manufacturers that
Japan sells wheeled loaders and backhoes in the EEC at unfairly low
prices.
   The two dumping probes were announced four days before Japanese
Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita's visit here to discuss trade
relations between Japan and the 12-nation EEC.
   The EEC Commission said the European Trade Association for
Manufacturers of Construction Equipment alleges a surge of imports
of wheeled loaders and back hoes from Japan.
   The EEC probe names seven Japanese producers in the complaint
regarding wheeled loaders: Caterpillar Mitsubishi Ltd., Furukawa
Co. Ltd., Kawasaki Heavy Industries, Ltd., Kobe Steel Ltd., Komatsu
Ltd., Kubota Ltd. and Toyo Umpanki Co. Ltd.
   The Japanese companies named in the backhoe complaint are:
Furukawa Co. Ltd., Hitachi Construction Machinery Co. Ltd.,
Hokuetsu Industries Co. Ltd., Ishikawajima Construction Machinery
Co. Ltd., Ishikawajima-Harima Heavy Industries Co. Ltd., Iwafuji
Industrial Co. Ltd., Kato Works Co. Ltd., Komatsu Ltd., Kubota
Ltd., Mitsubishi Heavy Industries Ltd., Nissan Kizal Co. Ltd.,
Sumitomo Heavy Industries Ltd., Sumitomo (S.H.I.) Construction
Machinery Co. Ltd., Takeuchi Manufacturing Co. Ltd., Toyoda
Automatic Loom Works Ltd., UNIC Corp. and Yanmar Diesel Engine Co.
Ltd.
