<HEAD>Charles Schwab Announces 10 Percent Operating Reductions</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS chairman to parent in last graf.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Charles Schwab Corp. is temporarily cutting
management salaries and encouraging employees to take time off as
part of a plan to reduce operating costs by 10 percent because of a
slowdown in the brokerage business.
   ``We're taking action to reduce personnel expenses from the top
down, and at the same time, we are working to retain our valuable,
highly trained staff,'' Charles R. Schwab, the chairman, said in a
statement Thursday.
   The San Francisco-based company, parent of the nation's largest
discount brokerage, has about 2,300 employees in more than 110
offices nationwide.
