<FILEID>AP-NR-06-03-88 1048EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-BicSuit     06-03 0505</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Bic Suit,0517</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bic Ordered to Give Data</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bic Corp. has been ordered to release
hundreds of internal documents on its disposable lighter, including
results of safety tests performed by the company and complaints by
users of the lighter.
   U.S. District Judge E. Mac Troutman on Thursday told the company
to release the documents to attorneys representing the estate of
Ethel L. Smith, a Schuylkill County woman who died in 1985,
allegedly after a Bic butane lighter exploded in her hands. The
estate is suing Bic, which is based in Milford, Conn., for $11
million.
   Other cases of exploding lighters are pending in other courts
and attorneys said the Smith case could have an impact on them.
   Troutman's 25-page memorandum and order affirms a decision by a
federal magistrate in 1987 that required Bic to turn over the
documents. In addition, the magistrate's order, also affirmed
Thursday by Troutman, did not grant a protective order barring
Smith's attorney's from distributing the documents to anyone else,
including attorneys representing other plaintiffs suing Bic.
   ``It's very, very significant,'' said John W. Andrews, a Tampa,
Fla., lawyer heading a Bic litigation group for the American Trial
Lawyers Association. ``The more (information) that's public, the
easier it will be to get it before a jury ... To have this
information available (for plaintiffs) is going to save them a
tremendous amount of money and time. And as soon as this
information gets out, the public will know what's going on there.''
   Michael B. Oropollo, a New Brunswick, N.J., lawyer who
represents Bic in the Smith suit and other cases, would not comment
on Troutman's decision and declined to say whether the company will
appeal.
   Ethel Smith, 66, died on July 15, 1985, two days after the
lighter she was using exploded, ``causing her to sustain severe
second- and third-degree burns over a great portion of her body,''
according to the suit filed on behalf of her estate by her husband,
Francis.
   The Philadelphia Inquirer reported last year that there had been
at least 10 deaths and hundreds of injuries associated with the Bic
lighter since 1979. Andrews said he is handling more than 15 cases
against Bic, including five in which the users died, allegedly from
injuries resulting when the lighters exploded.
   According to a statement from Bic, the company has sold more
than two billion lighters since it began selling them in the United
States in 1973. Under Troutman's orders, Bic must release all
information about complaints and accidents dating to 1977, when the
current Bic Mod II design was first sold. In addition, the company
must release all design information and test results regarding the
lighter.
   ``We find Bic USA's arguments that it would suffer significant
embarrassment and harm as a result of public disclosure of other
incidents involving the Bic Mod II lighter particularly
disingenuous given the extensive and detailed adverse publicity it
claims to have already received,'' Troutman wrote in his opinion.
   Bic has 30 days to comply with the order.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
