<DOCNO> AP880603-0297 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-03-88 1057EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-EEC-JapanTrade     06-03 0190</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-EEC-Japan Trade,0197</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>EEC Trade Gap With Japan Up 13 Percent In 1987</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The European Economic Community's trade
deficit with Japan last year rose by 13 percent in dollar terms but
shrank 4 percent in terms of European currency units, the EEC
Commission said Friday.
   The weakening value of the dollar against European currencies
accounted for the discrepancy.
   The EEC's trade deficit with Japan rose to $24.2 billion in 1987
from $21.4 billion the year before. But in terms of European
currency units, or ecus, the gap narrowed to 20.9 billion ecus from
21.8 billion ecus.
   EEC exports to Japan rose 19 percent in 1987 to 13.62 billion
ecus, while Japan's exports to the EEC rose by a smaller 6 percent
to 34.5 billion ecus.
   The EEC's trade gap of $24.2 billion compares with a trade
deficit of almost $60 billion which the United States registered
with Japan last year.
   A Commission spokeswoman said the rise in EC exports to Japan
last year showed relations were improving slightly but said ``much
remained to be done'' by Japan to open up its market to EEC goods.
</TEXT>
