<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures opened sharply higher
today on the Chicago Board of Trade amid continuing weather-driven
speculation.
   Soybean meal opened up its daily $10-a-ton limit and that lent
strong support to soybean, corn and oat futures, which also were up
the limit within minutes of the opening.
   Some analysts linked the runup in soybean meal futures to rumors
of heavy Soviet buying of South American meal. But Cathy Leow, an
analyst in New York with Thomson McKinnon Securities Inc., said
traders were merely using such talk as an excuse to advance the
dry-weather rally.
   ``With no rains in the forecast, nobody wants to be caught
short, so you've got a lot of people wanting to buy and no one
wanting to sell,'' she said.
   Only scattered rains were predicted for the Grain Belt during
the weekend, and longer-range forecasts called for another week of
unseasonably warm, dry weather.
   In early trading, wheat was 7 cents to 8 cents higher with the
contract for delivery in July at $3.58 a bushel; corn was 7 cents
to 7} cents higher with July at $2.32 a bushel; oats were 9\ cents
to 10 cents higher with July at $1.96{ a bushel; soybeans were 9{
cents to 26{ cents higher with July at $8.45 a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mostly lower in early trading on
the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .15 cent lower to .13 cent higher with June at
72.57 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .20 cent to .50 cent lower
with August at 76.10 cents a pound; hogs were .90 cent lower to .05
cent higher with June at 52.95 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies
were .53 cent to .70 cent lower with July at 56.35 cents a pound.
   Cattle futures advanced on Thursday while pork futures settled
lower.
</TEXT>
