<FILEID>AP-NR-06-03-88 1315EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Japan-Trade Bjt   06-03 0417</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Trade, Bjt,0432</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japan's Current Account Surplus Shrinks 12.7 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The broadest measure of Japan's trade surplus
shrank 12.7 percent in April from its level of a year earlier as
imports climbed 30 percent to record levels, according to
government figures released Friday.
   The current account, which covers trade in merchandise as well
as services and investment income, posted a $7.12 billion surplus,
down from $8.15 billion surplus a year earlier and an $8.12 billion
surplus in March, the Finance Ministry said.
   Japan's surplus also declined in the narrower measure of
merchandise trade alone, falling 4.5 percent to $8.49 billion from
$8.89 billion a year earlier and $9.24 billion in March.
   The strength of the Japanese yen and a government-promoted
economic expansion are encouraging strong growth in imports. The
trade gap is shrinking because imports are rising even faster than
Japan's rapidly expanding exports.
   Imports, measured when contracts were settled, climbed to a
record $13.5 billion in April from $10.4 billion a year earlier.
They were up 2 percent from $13.2 billion in March.
   Exports, also gauged at the time of customs clearance, grew 14.1
percent to $21.9 billion from $19.2 billion in the year-earlier
month. They fell 2.2 percent from $22.4 billion in March.
   The trade pattern is encouraging for the Japanese government,
which has been trying to restore balance to international trade in
a coordinated effort with such other industrial countries as the
United States, West Germany and Britain.
   Imports of manufactured goods have been rising especially fast,
they noted, accounting for 49.9 percent of the total imports in
April, the largest in Japan's recent history. In March,
manufactured goods held a 47.7 percent import share.
   Officials also pointed out that a growing number of Japanese
companies are stepping up imports of products they have made at the
plants that have been established overseas in an attempt to cushion
the impact of the yen's strength.
   The export growth was supported by considerable overseas demand
for products like business machines and computers, according to
officials. April's exports were the third largest on record.
   After seasonal factors were taken into account, the April
current account registered a surplus of $6.37 billion, down 12.6
percent from $7.28 billion in the previous month.
   The seasonally adjusted trade balance was in the black by $7.74
billion dlrs, dwindling from $8.40 billion in March. Seasonally
adjusted imports increased 3.7 percent to $12.9 billion from $12.4
billion but exports dipped 1 percent to $20.6 billion from $20.8
billion.
</TEXT>
