<1ST_LINE>r f AM-SupercomputerGiveaway     06-03 0243</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Supercomputer Giveaway,0250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Four High Schools Named Finalists In Supercomputer Giveaway</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four high schools _ one from Florida, one from
California and two from the Washington, D.C., area _ have been
named finalists in a contest to receive a million-dollar
supercomputer.
   ETA Systems Inc. of St. Paul, Minn., which is donating the
computer, says the machine would be the first in the world to be
installed in a secondary school.
   Named as finalists were North Florida Christian School in
Tallahassee, Fla.; James Logan High School in Union City, Calif.;
Thomas Jefferson High School for Science and Technology in
Alexandria, Va.; and Montgomery Blair High School in Silver Spring,
Md.
   ETA, a subsidiary of Control Data Corp., says the contest is
intended to ``identify and encourage excellence in computational
science at the U.S. secondary school level.'' It also gives the
company publicity in its bid to take business away from Cray
Research Inc., the dominant supercomputer maker.
   The four finalists were culled from 99 semifinalists. Some 1,500
schools, or roughly 6 percent of secondary schools in the country,
responded to the SuperQuest announcement. The winner will be
announced Aug. 12.
   Teams at each school, composed of four students and a teacher,
had to say what they would do with the supercomputer. Ideas ranged
from studying the life cycle of the Southern bald eagle and
improving school climate to ``calculating Van de Wall forces for
peptide chains and amino acids.''
</TEXT>
