<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Britain-Stocks 1stLd-Writehtru   06-03 0178</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Stocks, 1st Ld-Writehtru,0185</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>London Stocks Close Up 8.9 Points</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES with close.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices rose Friday as the opening of a new
trading account on London's Stock Exchange prompted some fresh
buying.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-stock index closed 8.9
points, or 0.5 percent, higher at 1,819.2. Volume was a healthy
616.6 million shares, compared with Thursday's 516.2 million shares.
   Traders said there was a bit of buying at the opening of the new
two-week trading account, pushing the 100-stock index up an
additional 5 points, but there was a lack of follow-through and the
index drifted back.
   London's Stock Exchange divides trading into two-week and
three-week trading periods for accounting purposes. Trades must be
completed within 10 days of a period ending.
   ``Some buying crept back into the market,'' said Nicholas
Knight, an equity analyst with James Capel and Co.
   Selected international stocks were aided by the pound's
weakening over the course of the week.
   Sterling was little changed, but investor demand for certain
dollar-dependent issues had not subsided, dealers said.
</TEXT>
