<FILEID>AP-NR-06-03-88 1430EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Eastern     06-03 0592</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Eastern,0614</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Analysts Say Federal Studies Should Boost Airline</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The favorable results of federal investigations
into Eastern Airlines' safety and management should boost the
struggling carrier's business, although many travelers may still
hesitate to book flights, analysts and travel agents say.
   The Federal Aviation Administration said Thursday its
plane-by-plane inspections showed no serious problems and the
Department of Transportation concluded, after an unprecedented
probe, that Houston-based Texas Air Corp. was capable and willing
to run Eastern and its other key carrier, Continental Airlines.
   The results ``should probably help them (Eastern). They passed
the test,'' John Pincavage, airline analyst for PaineWebber Inc.,
said.
   Anthony Hatch, analyst for Argus Research in New York, said the
reports help ``restore their reputation and begin the healing, now
that the worst of the wound is over. The worst of the hemorrhaging
is over.''
   But even more important than the government's report would be
news reports of on-time, courteous service, he said.
   Eastern lost $181 million last year and its management has
reported more losses and declines in passengers this year. It has
complained about campaigns led by Eastern unions charging that
management was creating unsafe conditions.
   Pincavage said some resistance to flying Eastern is likely to
remain because of its lackluster service.
   Bill Cooper, owner of Adventure Travels in Pompano Beach, said
client surveys have shown travelers have been more satisfied with
Eastern service in recent weeks. But only time will tell, he said,
if those who switched airlines and signed up with another
frequent-flier program will be willing to go back to Eastern.
   Norman Koppen, owner of Viking Travel in Coral Gables, said: ``I
think the problems are deeper'' than safety.
   ``Just the fact that there's ongoing internal strife within the
company gives people cause for apprehension,'' he said.
   Business travelers, in particular, ``have a very long memory''
about service problems, said Koppen, a former manager at Eastern.
   ``I think the fact that they got a clean bill of health is going
to have a nominal effect on restoring people's confidence,'' he
said.
   The Department of Transportation probe ``found no basis for
serious concern about management competence,'' said Transportation
Secretary James Burnley.
   After their six-week scrutiny of owner Texas Air Corp.'s
fitness, the investigators also decided that neither Eastern nor
Continental is in any immediate danger of financial failure.
   The 30-day ramp inspections of Eastern and Continental by the
FAA proved ``an unsafe condition does not currently exist among the
carriers,'' FAA Administrator T. Allan McArtor said.
   When the government investigation was launched in April, airline
analysts called it a victory for union lobbying in an election-year
Congress.
   Machinists President Charles Bryan charged that Texas Air
lobbying had influenced investigation findings.
   He called the final report ``an absolute clear whitewash'' and
said Texas Air Chairman Frank Lorenzo ``has proved he's the darling
of the FAA and the DOT.''
   Lorenzo, at a Washington news conference Thursday, hailed the
federal report as showing Eastern and Continental ``are absolutely
safe and absolutely fit. Those airlines passed inspection with
flying colors.''
   Eastern spokesman Robin Matell called the investigation
``comprehensive and thorough'' and said that ``any charge to the
contrary by a union leader is simply more of the same distorted
rhetoric we've been hearing for years. The findings vindicate
Eastern's operations and maintenance practices. No amount of
soap-box grandstanding can change those findings.''
   Eastern and the Machinists are in federal mediation and the
pilots union's contracts is opened to be amended July 1. Eastern
wants to cut labor costs by $450 million, or nearly 30 percent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
