<FILEID>AP-NR-06-03-88 1720EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Icahn-Texaco 1stLd-Writethru   06-03 0790</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Icahn-Texaco, 1st Ld-Writethru,0816</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Icahn Pitch Falls Flat on Wall Street</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf, But the ... Stock Exchange., to update with
final stock price.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN C. GIVEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Financier Carl C. Icahn's multibillion-dollar
bid for Texaco Inc. gained no ground Friday as Wall Street remained
unmoved by his latest attempt to drum up support from investors.
   In a meeting with more than 300 oil industry and investment
specialists late Thursday, Icahn, Texaco's largest shareholder,
gave the first details of how he would finance the proposed
acquisition and said he was certain he would have no trouble
getting the money.
   But the oil giant's stock stayed around the $50 level Friday _
or $10 below Icahn's offer _ where it had hovered since the bid was
announced. It slipped 50 cents a share to close at $50 on the New
York Stock Exchange.
   ``That basically tells you that probably not a huge number of
minds were changed'' by Icahn's presentation, said Sanford
Margoshes, who studies oil companies for the Shearson Lehman Hutton
Inc. securities firm.
   Icahn is seeking to buy the 86.2 percent of Texaco's stock he
does not already own for $12.4 billion. His proposal puts the
company's total value at $14.6 billion.
   He told the analysts he would need $8.86 billion in loans to
finance the deal. He said he would sell two subsidiaries _ Texaco
Canada Inc. and the company's 50 percent interest in Caltex _ then
borrow against an anticipated $2.98 billion in 1988 cash flow to
cover the financing.
   Some analysts said they agreed with Icahn's assertion that the
deal was ``eminently doable.'' Many others were not so sure.
   Texaco also scoffed at the plan, saying it was ``still
illusory'' and dismissing the details he provided as ``sketchy,
sloppy and wrong.''
   Texaco's board refused last week to let shareholders vote on the
takeover offer at the company's annual meeting June 17.
   On Thursday, Icahn admitted he would first have to win his proxy
fight for five seats on Texaco's 14-member board before he would
have a chance of getting the offer before Texaco's shareholders.
   He said several banks had told him if the proposal were then
accepted, he ``would have no trouble'' raising the necessary cash
to complete the deal.
   Once elected, Icahn argued, he and his associates would have no
problem pursuading the board to field the proposal for a vote,
simply because the ``mandate'' their election would be irresistable.
   Some analysts disagreed.
   ``The record of proxy contests is so irrational,'' said Philip
L. Dodge, of Nomura Securities International Inc. ``Management
almost always wins, and as a rule the price of the stock goes
down.''
   Even if Icahn won, Dodge continued, he still would only have
five of 14 members, which could lead to a long internal fight.
   And ``there is no mandate a management can't ignore,'' Dodge
said.
   Icahn won something of a victory in a related development
Friday, when a federal judge in White Plains, N.Y., rejected
Texaco's request that he void Icahn's directors slate before the
annual meeting.
   But U.S. District Judge Gerard Goettel left open the possibility
that he might still overturn the election should Icahn's slate win
and Texaco prevail in a suit charging Icahn with alleged violations
of federal securities laws.
   Several analysts said that no matter how the proxy fight comes
out, the market still doubted Icahn's explanation of how he would
come up with the money to pay for the Texaco takeover.
   ``The disappointment was that there's no firm financing in
place,'' said Rosario Ilacqua of Nikko Securities Co.
International, Inc.
   Ilacqua said Icahn would have to put up hefty fees to line up
the money _ fees he might not want to pay in advance.
   ``It all boils down to the proxy fight. If he loses, he's not
going to need the money,'' Ilacqua said.
   Oppenheimer & Co.'s Paul Ting also said there was ``a lot of
skepticism about Icahn's financing ability.''
   In particular, Ting said he believed Icahn had sharply
underestimated the money Texaco would have to pay for future
exploration and production costs.
   ``If you're a bank, you're going to lend money to Mr. Icahn only
if you feel comfortable about getting it back. So banks are going
to look at that more than anything else,'' he said.
   Other analysts suggested Icahn's figures did not include
adequate provisions covering payments of the company's debt.
   Texaco said Icahn's $8.86 billion figure ``simply wished away or
ignored more than $5 billion in debt and other obligations he would
also have to immediately finance.''
   ``Morgan Stanley & Co., our financial adviser, has informed
Texaco that Icahn's plan is simply not financeable in their
opinion,'' the statement added.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
