<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     06-03 0525</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dollar-Gold,0542</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Slightly Down, Gold Slips</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose Friday against most major
currencies except the Japanese yen and gold gave back some of its
gains in another busy session.
   Republic National Bank of New York said gold bullion was bid at
$464 a troy ounce as of 4 p.m. EDT, down from $466.25 an ounce late
Thursday.
   Traders said there was no major economic news to account for the
activity, although the Labor Department announced the U.S. civilian
unemployment rate rose in April for the first time in 20 months, to
5.6 percent from 5.4 percent the previous month.
   ``People are trading off the charts,'' that is, trying to pick
out trends in rates, said Mark Pletscher, an assistant vice
president for corporate foreign exchange at BankAmerica
International. ``Fundamentals you almost have to put aside right
now.''
   Gold rose sharply in Asia and Europe, catching up with the gains
made in Thursday's hectic session in New York. Gold continued to
rise in New York, climbing as much as $2 an ounce, but then sank
late in the session and finished below late Thursday's levels.
   ``These two days have been as active as we've seen in months''
in the precious metals markets, said James Koppel, managing
director of Deak International Trading (U.S.) Ltd.
   In Tokyo, the dollar rose 0.43 yen to a closing 126.11 yen.
Later, in London, it was quoted at 125.95 yen. In New York, the
dollar finished at 125.97 yen, down from 126.12 yen late Thursday.
   The British pound rose against the dollar in London, to $1.8005
from $1.7967 late Thursday. But later in New York, sterling dipped
to $1.7970 from $1.8044.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late
Thursday's rates, included: 1.7266 West German marks, up from
1.7211; 1.4391 Swiss francs, up from 1.4351; 1.2314 Canadian
dollars, up from 1.2308; 5.8333 French francs, up from 5.8270; and
1,283.75 Italian lire, up from 1,281.75.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Thursday's
rates, included: 1.7248 West German marks, down from 1.7295; 1.4363
Swiss francs, down from 1.4425; 5.8293 French francs, down from
5.8502; 1.9355 Dutch guilders, down from 1.9413; 1,282.00 Italian
lire, down from 1,286.75; and 1.2311 Canadian dollars, down from
1.2325.
   Gold closed in Hong Kong at a bid of $463.71 a troy ounce, up
from $455.38.
   Later in London gold rose to a late bid of $464.75 a troy ounce,
compared with late Thursday's $454.30. That was its highest price
since Jan. 28, when it fetched $466.50 an ounce.
   In Zurich, gold gained $12.50 an ounce, closing at a bid $465.50
compared with $453 late Thursday _ its best since Jan. 8.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold bullion for current
delivery fell to $464.80 a troy ounce from $467 an ounce.
   Silver bullion prices, powered by gold's gains, also jumped on
the London market, where the metal was trading at a late bid price
of $7.31 a troy ounce, compared with Thursday's $6.73. On New
York's Comex, silver bullion for current delivery fell to $7.225 a
troy ounce from $7.260.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
