<FILEID>AP-NR-06-03-88 1741EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-CommodityRdp     06-03 0769</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Commodity Rdp,0795</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grains, Soybeans Soar On Dry Weekend Outlook</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean, corn and oat futures soared the limit allowed for daily
trading on the Chicago Board of Trade Friday amid fears of crop
damage due to dry weather. Wheat futures also moved sharply higher.
   On other markets, pork futures prices plummeted while cattle
futures were mixed; precious metals dipped; energy futures
retreated; and stock-index futures were lower.
   The Commodity Research Bureau's index of 21 commodities advanced
2.02 points to 255.10, with 10 components scoring gains, eight
showing losses and three ending mixed.
   Friday's session ended a week of dramatic gains for the grain
and soybean markets and reflected concerns that the emerging crops
face a real threat if arid conditions in the Midwest continue,
analysts said.
   The amount of spring rain in the Midwest has been far below
normal. Most of the region's central portion _ including Illinois,
Indiana and Missouri _ received no measurable rainfall for 10 days,
the National Weather Service reported Friday, and south-central
Wisconsin had gone more than three weeks without measurable
precipitation.
   Weather forecasts called for no rain in the region this weekend
and the weather service, in a six-to-10-day forecast issued after
the close, predicted below-normal precipitation and above-normal
temperatures in the Midwest through June 13.
   ``This is the first time in at least six weeks that we're
fininshing up a Friday afternoon without having to worry about a
weekend weather system moving in,'' said Rich Feltes, grain analyst
for Refco Inc. in Chicago. ``This weekend, it clearly is not going
to rain.''
   Feltes said field observers had reported that the soybean and
corn crops were off to a ``sub-optimal start'' and were in worse
condition than in either 1980 or 1983, years that also had unusally
dry springs.
   Wheat settled 2 cents lower to 14 cents higher with the contract
for delivery in July at $3.62} a bushel; corn was up 9} cents to 10
cents, the daily limit, with July at $2.34{ a bushel; oats were up
the 10-cents-a-bushel limit across the board with July at $1.96{ a
bushel; soybeans were up 8} cents to 30 cents, the daily limit,
with July at $8.49 a bushel.
   Most pork futures posted sharp losses on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange in response to a drop in cash prices, analysts said.
   ``We had lower-than-expected cash hogs come in this morning on
the heels of a larger-than-expected country hog run yesterday,''
said Philip Stanley, an analyst in Chicago with Thomson McKinnon
Securities Inc.
   ``The packers had already fulfilled their Saturday slaughter
requirements and demand diminished,'' he said. ``That caught the
trade by surprise and washed the market out pretty good to the
downside.''
   Cattle futures were mixed as selling sentiment spilled over from
the pork pits, offsetting the positive effects of anticipated
higher boxed beef prices, Stanley said.
   Live cattle settled .30 cent lower to .33 cent higher with June
at 72.65 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .10 cent to .68 cent
lower with August at 75.92 cents a pound; hogs were 1.40 cents
lower to .23 cent higher with June at 52.45 cents a pound; frozen
pork bellies were .83 cent to 1.50 cents lower with July at at
55.55 cents a pound.
   Precious metals retreated on profit-taking after three days of
sharp gains.
   ``I think the metals have established that they are in an
uptrend, a pretty strong uptrend,'' said Craig Sloane, metals
analyst in New York with Smith Barney, Harris Upham & Co.
``Sometimes when you get a market in an uptrend it backs off a bit,
then continues on its way. I think that's what we're seeing here.''
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold settled $1.80 to
$2.20 lower with the active August contract at $469.30 a troy
ounce; silver was 1.8 cents to 3.5 cents lower with July at $7.27 a
troy ounce.
   Platinum on the New York Mercantile Exchange was $17.40 to
$17.60 lower with July at $610.60 a troy ounce.
   Oil prices slipped lower on the New York Mercantile Exchange in
quiet trading based mostly on technical factors, analysts said.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 10 cents to 15 cents
lower with July at $17.50 a barrel; heating oil was .25 cent to .31
cent lower with July at 47.13 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was
.38 cent to .62 cent lower with July at 50.89 cents a gallon.
   Stock index futures retreated slightly on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange, where the contract for June delivery of the Standard &
Poor's 500 index settled .25 point lower at 266.10.
</TEXT>
