<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0210</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Lower in Light Trading</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: for Saturday PMs</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil prices ended the week by slipping lower in
quiet trading.
   Analysts said most of Friday's activity involved traders trying
to square positions taken earlier in the week when prices ticked
upward. Prices of both crude and refined products weakened as
traders sold contracts to take their profits, observers said.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, contracts for July delivery
of West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark U.S. crude, closed at
$17.50 per 42-gallon barrel, down 15 cents.
   Among July contracts for refined products, wholesale unleaded
gasoline settled down 0.62 cent at 50.89 cents a gallon, while
wholesale heating oil closed at 47.13 cents per gallon, off 0.25
cent.
   Traders remained reluctant to make large moves in the market
until they see what happens at the upcoming summer meeting of oil
ministers of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries. The
conference opens June 11 in Vienna, Austria.
   ``The market is more bearish going into the OPEC meeting than
other recent meetings,'' said Richard Redoglia of Merrill Lynch
Energy Futures. ``But there is still a week to go, so there's not
much to worry about.''
</TEXT>
