<1ST_LINE>d f PM-EconomyRdp     06-03 0493</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Economy Rdp,0509</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jobless Rate Posts First Rise of Year; Wall Street Gains</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: for Saturday PMs</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock and bond markets have gotten a boost from news that
the nation's unemployment rose for the first time this year to 5.6
percent in May.
   The Labor Department reported Friday that unemployment in May
increased 0.2 percentage point from April's 14-year-low civilian
jobless rate of 5.4 percent. The small May rise reflected a
seasonally adjusted shrinking of the U.S. labor force by 363,000
people, with 536,000 fewer Americans at work.
   Wall Street interpreted the figures as showing a little less
strength in the economy than had been anticipated, and thus serving
to dampen worries about inflation somewhat.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials climbed 18.85 points
Friday to 2,071.30, extending its gain for the week to 114.86
points. That surpassed the previous record weekly point rise of
108.26 set last Dec. 14-18, although it fell well short of some
past weekly percentage increases.
   Bond prices also rose in response to the jobless data, pushing
interest rates lower. The yield on the Treasury's closely watched
30-year bond dropped from 9.14 percent late Thursday to 9.04
percent _ its lowest level since late April.
   However, government officials and private economists cautioned
the job figures for last month are too unreliable to suggest the
economy is losing steam.
   In other economic developments Friday:
   _Auto companies reported sales of domestic cars and trucks
picked up in late May despite lower incentive offers and rose 14.8
percent over the same period a year earlier.
   _The broadest measure of Japan's trade surplus shrank 12.7
percent in April from its level of a year earlier as imports
climbed 30 percent to record levels, Japanese government figures
showed.
   Before the seasonal adjustments made in the government's jobless
survey, to reflect a historically burgeoning job market in May with
the end of school terms, the actual number of Americans working
increased by 317,000.
   A separate government survey of employer payrolls also showed
209,000 new jobs in May, down from an average net gain of 250,000
new jobs monthly over the past year but reflecting a still-tight
labor market.
   Janet L. Norwood, commissioner of the Bureau of Labor
Statistics, said it would be premature to draw any conclusions from
the May change in the jobless rate based on her agency's household
survey.
   The unadjusted increase in May employment was very low by
historical standards, particularly when compared with a 1.3 million
rise the same month a year ago, Ms. Norwood told the congressional
Joint Economic Committee.
   Private economists agreed, and some even suggested the
unemployment rate may still be on a downward trend despite the
slight increase in May.
   ``You really can't identify a 0.2 percentage point move as a
change in the trend,'' said Chris Caton, an analyst for Data
Resources Inc. in Lexington, Mass. ``Next month it will probably go
down a tenth of a percent.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
